<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SovietMilitary     09-13 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Military,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Urged To Develop New Proposals On Arms Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should develop new proposals
for U.S.-Soviet conventional arms control talks in case Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev succeeds in cutting back on military
spending, says a key congressman.
   The plans should be prepared even though there's no indication
Gorbachev has yet been successful, said Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis.,
chairman of the House Armed Services Committee.
   ``A central element of Gorbachev's `new thinking' is that the
Western threat can be reduced by political means _ that is, arms
control _ which then reduces Soviet defense requirements,'' the
report said.
   ``For Gorbachev, arms control can cut the size of the Western
threat and a revised military doctrine can scale back the
military's response to that threat,'' it said.
   The panel's defense policy subcommittee concluded Monday that
``to date, there have been no significant, identifiable changes
traceable to Gorbachev's drive to scale back defense spending.''
   The study by the Democratic-run panel was based on a series of
hearings, including testimony from the CIA, Defense Intelligence
Agency, and other experts in government and private industry.
   Republican members of the panel issued a dissent, disputing the
majority's implication that the Soviets may be moving away from
what the GOP legislators said is a drive to achieve nuclear
superiority over the West.
   Gorbachev has called for economic and military reforms aimed at
shifting more spending into consumer goods and away from the huge
Soviet military structure, Aspin noted.
   ``Gorbachev's reform agenda for the military is driven primarily
by domestic concerns, not military or strategic factors,'' the
study said. ``The equation is simple: In order for his economic
reforms to succeed, Gorbachev must shift resources from the defense
sector to civilian use.''
   The current five-year plan began in 1986 and was developed
before Gorbachev took power in March 1985, Aspin said at a news
conference. Some changes may be seen in the Soviets' next five-year
plan, he said.
   ``There is a growing consensus among the experts that Gorbachev
intends to shift some of the Soviet Union's economic capacity from
military to civilian use,'' said Aspin.
   ``What the United States ought to be doing is probing. ... We
should move cautiously and carefully, but we should move,'' he
said. ``We need some concrete proposals in conventional arms.''
   He was referring to the long-stalled talks aimed at reducing
non-nuclear weapons and troops in Europe.
   The upcoming ``year we're looking at is a critical year,'' Aspin
said. ``It's too bad the United States is in transition.''
   As the Reagan administration winds down, no new proposals are
likely. In addition, a new administration will take six to eight
months to prepare its plans, no matter whether Republican George
Bush or Democrat Michael Dukakis is elected president, Aspin said.
   U.S. officials have a difficult time estimating Soviet military
spending, since the Soviets don't publish details about their
programs.
   The Soviets appear to be spending about 18 percent of their
gross national product on defense, compared to about 6 percent for
the United States, the study said. But the U.S. GNP is much larger.
   Soviet military spending increased about 2 percent annually in
the decade before Gorbachev took power, and has increased about 3
percent in each of the past two years.
   The study cited the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces (INF)
treaty, which includes strict verification procedures and bigger
cuts in the Soviet arsenal than in the U.S. stockpile of weapons.
   The GOP minority, led by Rep. William Dickinson, R-Ala., the
ranking Republican on the committee, criticized part of the report.
   ``This report accepts, without the slightest qualification, the
idea that the Soviet leadership has accepted the implications of
nuclear parity _ implicitly meaning that the Soviets reject the
concepts of superiority, pre-emption, first use and victory,'' the
GOP members said.
   ``The apparent justification underlying this assumption appears
to be a decade of both Soviet public statements and arms control
activities. However, neither can be taken at face value as evidence
of a meaningful transformation in Soviet nuclear doctrine,'' the
dissent said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
