<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EmptySeat     09-13 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Empty Seat,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Even Without Biaggi, Congressional Office Carries On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the Capitol Hill office for New York's 19th
Congressional District, phones still ring, mail comes in, letters
go out.
   The only thing missing is a member of Congress.
   Until Aug. 5, the district was represented by Rep. Mario Biaggi,
a Democrat who for nearly 20 years represented the East Bronx and
part of Yonkers. Biaggi, who was convicted of racketeering last
month in the Wedtech trial, resigned rather than face almost
certain expulsion by his colleagues.
   But even without an elected representative, the work of the
congressional office goes on. House rules provide for keeping
offices running in the event that a member resigns, dies or is
expelled.
   Constituents still get some services; what they don't get is
their own advocate who can sponsor and vote on legislation and
perform work in committees.
   In the case of Biaggi's constituents, they lost their voice in
Congress last year when Biaggi agreed to stop voting on the House
floor after being indicted for accepting illegal paid vacations. He
later was convicted of that charge in a separate trial.
   Deputy Clerk W. Raymond Colley said that when a vacancy occurs
in the House, ``The clerk of the House becomes in effect the
supervisor or manager of the vacant offices until a successor is
elected.''
   The clerk usually selects one of the former House member's
senior staffers to run the office, Colley said. Robert Blancato,
Biaggi's longtime administrative assistant, was appointed to run
the office upon the congressman's departure.
   ``We are carrying on the way that not only Mario Biaggi would
expect of his staff and the years of experience that we have, but
also using our own standards of what we believe we should do,''
Blancato said.
   Blancato said he still talks daily to Biaggi, who has returned
to the Bronx, and that the business of the congressional office
inevitably comes up.
   ``I don't know if there are rules about discussing business,''
Blancato said. ``... His advice and guidance and counsel, do I
still need it for what I do everyday? Absolutely, sure.''
   Colley said such communications are to be expected, and voiced
confidence that Blancato ``understands his role and what he's
doing.''
   Blancato said he has no sense of role reversal during
conversations with Biaggi.
   ``Every time I speak to him ... in a philosophical way, even if
it isn't in a literal way, I'm stll speaking to my boss,'' he said.
   Even the hurdle of sponsoring legislation is not insurmountable
without an elected representative. If the appointed administrator
believes some problem requires legislation, ``He can talk to the
other members of the delegation from that particular state and ask
them to support the issue,'' Colley said.
   ``These are not unusual situations,'' Colley said. ``We have had
vacancies for various reasons over the years.''
   Ten seats, including one belonging to the delegate from American
Samoa, have been vacated since the 100th Congress began almost two
years ago, Colley said. Most of those seats have been filled
through special elections.
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo has called no special election to fill
Biaggi's seat, so whoever is elected on Nov. 8 won't begin serving
until January 1989.
   Chances are good that Biaggi will be re-elected to the seat he
vacated, but he has said he would not serve. If he wins, it is
expected that he would quit again and a special election would be
held.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
