<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Rowan-Shooting     09-13 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rowan-Shooting,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inspector Says Rowan Violated Weapons Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A District of Columbia police inspector
testified that syndicated columnist Carl T. Rowan broke a local gun
control law when he fired on a backyard intruder in June.
   Following a pre-trial hearing Monday that included testimony
from police Inspector James R. Lee, D.C. Superior Court Judge
Arthur Burnett said he would rule by Friday on a motion that
weapons charges against Rowan be dismissed.
   Rowan, 63, has been charged with using an unregistered revolver
to wound a teen-ager who was intruding in the backyard of his home.
He also has been charged with unlawful possession of ammunition for
the handgun.
   Rowan, who has written and spoken frequently on behalf of gun
control, maintains that his son, Carl Jr., a former FBI agent, was
told by city officials he was not required to register the weapon
used in the June 14 shooting.
   Rowan testified that he had complained repeatedly to police
about trespassers and said that death threats heightened his
concern over intruders.
   The columnist, who contends the police knew he had a gun, said
he had warned a police officer that if anyone ever confronted him
on his property late at night, he would have to shoot them and he
didn't want to do that.
   The officer, Jasper L. Chatman, contradicted Rowan's testimony,
saying, ``He never made a statement to me about any action he was
going to take.'' Chatman said he'd been to the Rowan house between
10 and 20 times in the last few years, all on complaints about
trespassers using the pool.
   Lee, who has worked in the district's gun records division since
1976, said Rowan had broken the law that prohibits anyone but the
registered owner from using a weapon.
   He acknowledged that city police officers and federal law
enforcement agents are not required to register weapons, but he
insisted that only those individuals are allowed to use the weapons.
   Lee added that it is a violation of law for other family members
even to touch an agent's weapon.
   The FBI does not require agents to register with local
authorities weapons used for official duties, according to Ray
McElhaney, an FBI spokesman. He declined to say whether a
.22-caliber revolver, the weapon used in the shooting, would
normally be approved for use by FBI agents.
   Rowan Jr., a lawyer, testified Monday that he spoke three times
with police about whether the weapon should be registered and was
told he needn't register it, but never got a written statement on
the matter.
   The senior Rowan shot Benjamin Smith, 19, of suburban Chevy
Chase, Md., on the night of June 14 after he caught Smith and three
other youths taking an unauthorized swim in his pool.
   If convicted on the misdemeanor weapon and ammunition charges,
Rowan faces a possible maximum penalty of two years in prison and a
$2,000 fine.
</TEXT>
