<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hispanics     09-13 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hispanics,350</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: For release 8 a.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Republican Task Force Issues Recommendations on Developing
Hispanic Talent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republicans today released a set of
recommendations to encourage full development of Hispanic talent,
including a trade policy with Mexico that benefits businesses on
both sides of the border and expanded education initiatives to
lower the illiteracy and dropout rates.
   The Senate Republican Conference task force on Hispanic affairs
said in issuing its recommendations that four advisory committees
had examined Hispanic education and literacy, economic development,
employment, and health.
   ``By taking a fresh look at these and additional issues on the
threshold of the 1990s, we intend to re-energize and refocus
attention on the needs and potential of Hispanic Americans,'' the
report said.
   ``We do not see this potential as different from other
Americans. Rather, we want to ensure that Hispanic Americans have
access to the opportunities and support systems already available
to most Americans for many generations,'' said the committee, led
by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
   The task force's recommendations include:
   _Expanding national and local initiatives to reduce illiteracy
and combat a high Hispanic student dropout rate.
   _Advocate programs at the federal, state and local levels and in
the private sector that provide managerial skills assistance to
small minority businesses.
   _Pursue an aggressive trade policy with Mexico to benefit
businesses on both sides of the border.
   _Improve the recruitment of qualified Hispanics into managerial
and professional positions in the private and public sector.
   _Promote health and disease prevention efforts, with an emphasis
on fighting AIDS.
   _Support better access to bonding and insurance for small firms.
   The committee said it hoped its efforts would boost the nation's
appreciation for ``one of our rich cultural treasures _ the
American of Hispanic descent.''
   The Senate Republican Conference is the official caucus of
Republican senators.
   In addition to Hatch, other members of the task force are Sens.
William Armstrong of Colorado, John H. Chafee of Rhode Island,
Alfonse M. D'Amato of New York, Pete Domenici of New Mexico, Bob
Dole of Kansas, Phil Gramm of Texas, John McCain of Arizona, Alan
K. Simpson of Wyoming and Pete Wilson of California.
</TEXT>
