<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BurrowingNuke     09-13 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burrowing Nuke,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Pursues Development Of Earth-Burrowing Warheads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department is pursuing the
development of nuclear warheads that would penetrate the earth
before detonating and which could be a more effective weapon
against Soviet underground command centers.
   Pentagon officials said Monday that Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci had authorized development of the so-called ``burrowing
nukes'' that have been under study for years.
   Military scientists are convinced they would be far more
powerful against underground bunkers than other nuclear devices
that explode on the surface, even if they don't pack the same
explosive power.
   The new weapon, which is highly classified and the
responsibility of the Air Force, is formally known as an earth
penetrator.
   The Energy Department disclosed in June 1987 it had begun
preliminary development work on the warhead needed for a burrowing
missile because it expected the Pentagon to request one.
   According to a Defense Department spokeswoman and other Pentagon
sources, that request now has been formally made. The Energy
Department will be expected to step up its work on warhead design
while the Air Force pursues missile development and integration
work.
   Spokeswoman Jan Bodyani said the Pentagon's Defense Acquisition
Board last month recommended approval of an Air Force statement on
the need for the weapon and Carlucci subsequently approved it.
   She said the final authorization was dated Aug. 19 ``and
approves this program as a new start.'' She would not discuss
program details such as funding and anticipated deployment
schedules.
   Another Pentagon official, who insisted on anonymity, said
Carlucci had directed the Air Force to provide cost estimates and
predicted performance data for a more rudimentary version of the
weapon that could be produced by modifying an existing missile or
bomb.
   ``There will almost certainly be an interim earth penetrator,''
this official said. ``But the authorization clears the way for the
broad-based research needed to produce a brand new weapon.''
   The Reagan administration recently has begun spotlighting Soviet
construction of underground bunkers, saying it appears the Russians
are convinced they can protect their leaders while waging a nuclear
war.
   Earlier this spring, the Defense Department reported in its
latest edition of the publication ``Soviet Military Power'' that
such construction had been under way for 40 years and the bunkers
could ``accommodate thousands of people.''
   A burrowing warhead would not have to penetrate more than a few
feet before posing an increased threat to a bunker, but ``it's not
easy'' to develop a warhead that can withstand the shock of
striking and burrowing through the ground, one official said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LaunchDanger     09-13 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Launch Danger,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA, Air Force To Limit Journalists at Shuttle Launch Site</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: News conference scheduled for 2 p.m. EDT; top prospects
uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The viewing area from which reporters and
spectators have watched 25 space shuttle launches at the Kennedy
Space Center will be off-limits to most onlookers when shuttles
start flying again because of safety concerns, officials say.
   The Air Force and NASA on Monday announced the new precautions
at the Cape Canaveral, Fla., space facility, citing studies that
``have shown that the danger to persons on the ground is much
greater than was understood should an accident occur.''
   The restrictions cover the viewing area that overlooks launch
complex 39, where space shuttle Discovery is being prepared for
space.
   A press viewing area 3.5 miles from the launch pads has been
used by media representatives since the shuttle program began.
Invited guests, including astronauts' families, watched from a
nearby VIP area, and Kennedy Space Center workers and their
families also were able to watch from certain areas.
   Under the new plans, most nearby areas will be cleared just
before and during the launch. Details of the plans were to be
explained at a briefing today at the Washington headquarters of the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   The plan drew protests Monday from Rep. Bill Nelson, R-Fla., who
said at the Kennedy Space Center that the House Committee on
Science, Space and Technology had argued against such a change in a
letter sent Friday to President Reagan.
   ``I don't think an iron curtain should be placed about the
Kennedy Space Center when we're getting back into space,'' said
Nelson, a member of the committee and chairman of its subcommittee
on space science and applications.
   ``The press has been very much a part of the manned space flight
program for 29 years and to arbitrarily say that some of that press
has to be excluded is not right,'' Nelson said.
   NASA officials said the new rules were developed after studies
of the Challenger explosion in January 1986 and the loss of an Air
Force Titan 34D the following April.
   Air Force range safety officers monitor each launch and have the
responsibility of blowing up any rocket that strays out of control.
   During the Challenger accident, the solid-fueled rocket booster
engines broke away and were destroyed by the Air Force range safety
officer. A study of this accident, and of the Titan 34D loss, gave
new understanding of the dangers to people near the launch pad, the
announcement said.
   ``Under certain conditions, a solid rocket booster released from
the vehicle as a result of an accident would follow an unknown
ballistic trajectory rather than begin to tumble on course as had
been previously thought,'' the announcement said.
   Also, the statement said, it was learned that if out-of-control
boosters had to be destroyed in flight, ``the boosters fragmented
into thousands of pieces and the explosive properties of unburned
solid motor propellant were greater than originally determined in
laboratory tests.''
   ``Because of this new information,'' the statement said, ``NASA
and the Air Force have determined that the prudent action is to
minimize the population at the close-in viewing areas.''
   Accredited journalists will be able to work in the area ``except
for the hours just before the launch and the launch itself,'' the
statement said.
   During the prohibited period, only ``media with an immediate
need for the facilities at the press site will be allowed.'' The
rest, it said, will view the launch from a site on a causeway. The
alternate site will be equipped with a countdown clock, audio
commentary and video monitors.
   About 3,000 members of the media have requested accreditation
for the first post-Challenger launch, that of Discovery, which is
expected to occur in about two weeks. The exact number that will be
permitted at the press site has not been disclosed.
   The letter to Reagan from the congressional committee, headed by
Rep. Robert A. Roe, D-N.J., said, in part, ``Although we have no
doubt that the new assessments leading to this proposal are well
intended, the calculation of such risks is highly uncertain.''
   It asked the president to intercede and permit continued access
to traditional viewing areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
