<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingWife     09-13 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Wife,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged in Suspected Death of Missing Wife Despite Lack of
Corpse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Rockville man has been charged with
murdering his common-law wife although police said they ``don't
even know where to begin looking for the body'' of the woman who
disappeared in July.
   Gregory Tu, 58, was arrested at a Las Vegas, Nev., hotel on
Saturday, a day after Montgomery County police charged him with
first-degree murder in the suspected death of 42-year-old Lisa Tu.
   Police said scientific and circumstantial evidence led them to
conclude that the woman had been slain at the couple's home in
Rockville.
   ``We don't even know where to begin looking for the body,'' said
Capt. Robert F. McKenna, the county's chief of detectives.
   Police said they interviewed people who spoke of discord in the
couple's marriage. Other factors cited by the police were
allegations that Tu threw out his wife's favorite love seat shortly
after she disappeared, traces of blood found where the love seat
had stood in the home and Tu's departure for Las Vegas before he
was scheduled to take a polygraph test.
   Tu, a marketing employee of a real estate development, told
friends and relatives in July that his wife had gone to San
Francisco to help a friend who was ill. Police said the friend
reported she had not seen the woman and had not been expecting her.
   Lisa Tu' grown son and daughter from an earlier relationship
reported her missing to police on Aug. 10. Tu was questioned by
police on Aug. 13 and 14 about his wife's absence and agreed to
take a lie detector test, but left the state before doing so.
   Detectives said Tu was being held at the Clark County Detention
Center in Las Vegas pending extradition proceedings. The couple had
lived together for about 10 years, police said.
</TEXT>
