<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DukakisNotebook     09-13 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis Notebook,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Speech Gaffe; Glenn on Rambo; Philly Minus A Major Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis never will win an award for
stirring oratory but generally he can be expected to deliver his
speeches, aided by a TelePrompTer, without major gaffes.
   But even the unemotional Dukakis had to step back from the
microphone and laugh at himself after flubbing a line in a speech
on national security Monday at a union hall in Philadelphia.
   The Democratic nominee had just finished railing against Vice
President George Bush for his role in the Iran-Contra affair and
promised that a Dukakis admininstration never would sell arms to a
terrorist nation.
   His text then called for the following line: ``I don't question
George Bush's patriotism.''
   Instead, Dukakis said: ``I don't question George Bush's
terrorism.'' He immediately realized his error and, after taking a
few seconds to laugh along with his audience, delivered the line
from the text.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Ohio Sen. John Glenn also is not high on the list of great
orators in the Democratic Party but he delivered a lively and
emotional defense of Dukakis before the same Philadelphia audience.
   Criticizing Reagan administration budget and trade policies that
Glenn said were responsible for the massive U.S. trade deficit,
Glenn said Reagan had failed to use his ``enormous'' powers to
protect U.S. trade interests.
   ``They've talked like Rambo and they've acted like Bambi,''
Glenn said to the roaring approval of the partisan audience.
   Glenn, the first man to orbit the earth, used his stature as an
American hero to defend Dukakis in the flap over his veto of a 1977
bill that would have required Massachusetts teachers to lead
students in reciting the Pledge of Allegiance.
   Dukakis vetoed the bill after being advised it was
unconstitutional, but Bush and other Republicans have raised the
issue in not-so-subtle attacks on Dukakis' patriotism.
   Glenn, declaring himself to be ``very irritated'' by the GOP
attacks, stood in front of a huge American flag as he denounced the
Republicans.
   ``That Pledge of Allegiance to the flag of the United States is
your pledge, it's my pledge, it's our pledge and it's Michael
Dukakis' pledge,'' Glenn said.
   Glenn also accused the Republicans of ignoring the final six
words of the pledge: ``with liberty and justice for all.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis' visit Monday to Philadelphia was without a major
protest, in stark contrast to an event he held here on Labor Day as
part of his fall campaign kickoff.
   A small group of anti-abortion protesters gathered outside the
union hall where Dukakis delivered a speech on national security
and a handful also met the Democratic nominee outside a
Philadelphia television studio.
   The relative calm came just a week after a Dukakis event in a
nearby neighborhood was disrupted by about 100 anti-abortion
protesters whose chants drowned out most of Dukakis' remarks to
residents of a narrow street where he held an outdoor meeting.
   The advance man who arranged the Labor Day event has since been
fired by the Dukakis campaign.
</TEXT>
