<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SriLanka     09-13 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Shuts Down Businesses, Transportation; 14 Injured In Bus
Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>ASSOCIATED PRESS WRITER</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 14 people were injured Monday
when Sinhalese militants attacked a bus in Colombo during a
national general strike called by anti-government Sinhalese, police
reported.
   They said strike enforcers hurled a bomb at the bus, one of the
few state-transport vehicles operating, and several of the victims
were hospitalized.
   The driver of another bus was stabbed for defying the strike
call and a bus was set afire, according to police.
   Police and army patrols were deployed throughout the capital.
   A few shops and banks opened Monday morning but were shuttered
by noon.
   The Sinhalese People's Liberation Front called the strike to
protest the death of lawyer Vijedasa Liyanarachchi while in police
custody.
   Liyanarachchi, 35, died on Sept. 3, nine days after he was
arrested in southern Sri Lanka and accused of being linked to
several assassinations. The front said an autopsy report indicated
he died from more than 100 internal injuries caused by a blunt
instrument.
   The government has ordered a public inquiry into the death.
   The government has blamed the Liberation Front for killing more
than 500 people, including members of the ruling United National
Party, security personnel and supporters of an India-mediated
accord aimed at ending the 5-year-old civil war between Sihnalese
and Tamils.
   Liberation Front leaders claim the July 1987 agreement gives too
many concessions to Tamils who comprise 18 percent of the island's
16 million people.
   Tamil separatists have been fighting for a homeland in northern
and eastern Sri Lanka. Most Tamils are Hindus and they accuse the
Buddhist Sinhalese majority of discrimination.
</TEXT>
