<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0211EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DecapitationTrial     09-13 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Decapitation Trial,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins for Preacher Accused in Handyman's Decapitation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEANNE WAXMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parishioners who once admired their
minister of nearly two decades expressed mixed emotions as he went
on trial on charges he decapitated a handyman in an attempt to
assume a new identity.
   The Criminal Court trial of the Rev. David Terry began Monday
with jury selection, which is expected to take most of the week. He
is charged with first-degree murder and arson, and faces the death
penalty.
   James C. Matheny's decapitated body was found in a rolled-up
carpet in the burned-out remains of the Emmanuel Church of Christ
Pentecostal Oneness where Terry, 43, preached.
   ``Two days before this happened we would have given him our last
dime,'' said Marsha Brown, 30, who with others in the congregation
has been attending weekly services in a borrowed building in nearby
Gallatin. ``I don't feel personally betrayed. More let down than
anything else.''
   ``It's just a lot of mixed feelings about him (Terry) right
now,'' said Teresa Matheny, the victim's ex-wife. ``I hope he can
tell the truth so that he will have a chance of getting forgiveness
from God.''
   Mrs. Matheny said she and the victim were close to a
reconciliation when his body was found June 15, 1987.
   The congregation, once closely knit, was stunned by the slaying
and the church's burning.
   Some parishioners, though, have stuck by Terry. The congregation
numbers about 40. About 20 members have left since the slaying,
Mrs. Brown said.
   ``I think as far as the evidence is concerned I believe he's
guilty,'' said Marlane McClanahan, 35, who has not been attending
services held by the current pastor, the Rev. Wayne Cole. ``I'm sad
for him (Terry). I guess I'm a little bitter, but you have to keep
the love of God no matter what.''
   ``He was a friend,'' Virginia Howard, 63, another member of the
congregation, said of Terry. ``We had known him since he was a boy.
Our children and he grew up together. There wasn't anything ever
bad about the boy. He just did good things. We're amazed that
someone we've known and never knew anything bad against is guilty
of this.''
   Police say Terry tried to fake his own death by putting his belt
and other clothing on the headless body, which also was missing
part of the right arm and two spots where Matheny had tattoos.
   Court documents allege that Matheny, 32, was killed in Terry's
attempt to assume a new identity and disappear with $50,000 in
church funds. A driver's license with Terry's photograph but issued
in the name of a man dead since 1951 was later recovered with other
false identification issued in the same name.
   Matheny's head and arm were cut off with butcherlike precision,
police said. Terry once earned extra money as a supermarket butcher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
