<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     09-13 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Port Workers Strike; Students Clash With Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees of the port at the Pacific
end of the Panama Canal stopped most operations in a strike to
demand payment of bonuses, and students protesting the delays
clashed with police, sources said.
   Luis Asprilla, secretary general of the Workers' Association,
said the strike by most of the port's 800 employees paralyzed cargo
and fueling operations Monday and stopped food and water supplies
to ships.
   He said the strike would continue indefinitely.
   Panama Canal operations were not affected.
   Asprilla said workers were demanding the government pay
one-third of annual bonuses.
   About 20,000 government employees held a demonstration last
Thursday to demand payment of similar annual bonuses.
   The government, financially strapped in part by U.S. economic
sanctions, has said it will make the payments soon but does not
have sufficient funds now.
   In a related incident, a group of high school students
protesting the late payments clashed with police outside a school
Monday, witnesses said.
   A leader of the parents' association of the school, the National
Institute, said 20 students were struck by police. Police denied
the report.
   The Education Ministry closed the school indefinitely.
   Last week, a cash shortage forced the Cabinet to cut the pay of
Gen. Manuel Noriega and other top officials from 12.5 percent to 30
percent. A government communique said the cuts would save about
$230,000 a month.
   Panama's once-thriving economy has been hard-hit by several
months of political protests demanding Noriega's ouster, U.S.
sanctions imposed to force the general to leave, and a period when
banks were closed or handled only limited operations. Business
sources say the economy is about half what it was in early 1987.
   Earlier this year, the government had trouble meeting its
payroll.
   Noriega, who as commander of the Defense Forces is the power
behind the civilian government, is charged with drug trafficking in
the United States.
   He denies the charges and accuses the United States of trying to
undermine the Panamanian government as part of a plan to avoid
turning the Panama Canal over to the Central American country under
treaties signed in 1977.
</TEXT>
