<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Chile     09-13 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Censor Only TV Propaganda Allowed Pinochet Opponents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities banned a television broadcast
by the opposition because it contained a report on torture of
dissidents, political activists said.
   The banned 15-minute, late-night segment is the only televised
political program allowed to opponents of President Augusto
Pinochet, the sole candidate in a presidential referendum next
month that could extend his rule for eight years.
   Also Monday, six people wounded during street violence Sunday
were reported in serious condition with gunshot wounds. All were
from Cerro Navia, a northwestern working-class suburb of Santiago,
where Gen. Pinochet's motorcade was stoned by angry protesters on
Sunday's 15th anniversary of the military coup in which he seized
power.
   National police responded by using tear gas and water cannon to
disperse demonstrators who hurled stones and set up barricades of
burning tires.
   About 50 people were wounded and 400 arrested, police said.
   The government-controlled National Television Council said the
opposition program was rejected Monday night because ``it did not
abide by the electoral law,'' which grants the government and
opposition 15 minutes each of free time on national television to
carry their message to voters in an Oct. 5 presidential referendum.
   The free nightly broadcasts, from 10:45 p.m. to 11:15 p.m., are
the only television advertisements allowed to the opposition. The
government has ample access to the television, which it controls.
The programs started one week ago.
   A coalition of 16 parties opposing the re-election of Pinochet
said the program was censored because it included an interview with
a judge, Rene Garcia, who told about the torture of political
dissidents by security agents.
   ``We reject the attempt by government officials to determine
what Chileans can and can not see on television,'' the coalition
said in a statement. ``Our struggle in the upcoming referendum
includes the promotion of a complete freedom of expresion and
rejection of any kind of censorship.''
   The government's 15-minute program was broadcast normally Monday
night. In addition, the government has maintained for months a
series of ads urging voters to support Pinochet in the referendum.
   The law prohibits political advertisement on television, but the
government claims it is not breaking the law. It says its ads do
not constitute ``political propaganda,'' but an information to
citizens on its works and achievements.
   The National Television Council that censored the opposition
program includes Education Minister Juan Guzman and several other
government officials.
   The council's secretary, Alfredo Lustig, appeared on state
television to say that the opposition program was barred because
the comments by Judge Garcia had not been authorized by the court
in which he serves.
   The opposition called the council's decision ``illegal and
unconstitutional.''
   Genaro Ariagada, secretary general of the opposition coalition,
denied the censored program broke the law.
   ``The only one that has broken the law here is the National
Television Council,'' Arriagada said. ``This an abuse that every
decent Chilean citizen must reject.''
   When the time came for the opposition program to be broadcast, a
sign appeared on the screen saying it had been suspended because it
``did not abide by the law.''
   Within minutes, residents in a number of Santiago neighborhoods
started banging empty pots from inside their homes, a traditional
form of protest.
   In the Oct. 5 referendum, voters will vote ``yes'' or ``no'' on
Pinochet, the single candidate nominated by the nation's military
commanders, including Pinochet himself as commander of the army.
   About 7.2 million voters are registered for the Oct. 5 poll. If
approved by voters, Pinochet will start a new eight-year term next
March. If rejected, an open election will be held within a year,
with Pinochet remaining in power until then.
   Pinochet toppled the elected government of President Salvador
Allende and took power Sept. 11, 1973. Allende, a Marxist, died in
the takeover.
</TEXT>
