<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     09-13 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Service Battling 2-Cent Stamp Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Postal Service is cracking down on a scam
by people who are selling mailers on the wrong information that
first-class letters can be mailed for just two cents.
   The Postal Service has filed civil 370 complaints against
individuals and companies in the last several months, mostly
halting mail deliveries to those operating the scam.
   Postal Inspector Billy Posey said Monday that the agency is
prepared to file criminal charges in cases of repeat offenders.
   Posey said that under the scam, potential buyers are told they
can cut mailing costs. Those responding are sent a copy of a
section of the federal code that was repealed in 1970 which dealt
with business-reply mail, then available for two cents.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Meese Spokesman Announces Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick Korten, former Attorney General Edwin
Meese III's spokesman for his last few months in office, is leaving
the Justice Department next week.
   Korten will be replaced at Justice by Loye Miller, the director
of public affairs for the Department of Education under departing
Education Secretary William Bennett.
   Korten, a staunch defender of Meese, said he will write at the
Heritage Foundation, a conservative Washington think tank where
Meese now works, and hopes eventually to resume working
broadcasting.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Congress Provides Money For Whooping Cranes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation on its way to President Reagan
would have the government buy the last privately held land on a
Texas island that is a wintering ground for the world's only
surviving flock of whooping cranes that breeds in the wild.
   The Interior Department appropriations bill, passed last week by
Congress, provides $5.5 million for the purchase of 5,017 acres at
the southern tip of Matagorda Island, officials say.
   The purchase will be the government's third and final
acquisition from the Texas Nature Conservancy, bringing the federal
property on the Gulf Coast barrier island to 11,502 acres.
   Because of growing flocks, the whooping cranes have had to
search for new wintering grounds away from their traditional winter
home on nearby Aransas National Wildlife Refuge.
</TEXT>
