<HEAD>Bus Crash Kills Six, Injures 14</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: UPDATES throughout with at least 6 deaths, details, CORRECTS
that bus did not go into river.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EMBUDO, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greyhound bus plunged off a highway over
the Rio Embudo late Monday after hitting a rock slide, killing at
least six passengers and injuring 14, authorities said.
   The bus traveling from Denver to Albuquerque went off New Mexico
68 near the point where the river feeds into the Rio Grande, about
50 miles north of Santa Fe, State Police spokeswoman Lupita Carrion
said in Santa Fe.
   The accident less than a mile north of the Embudo Post Office
was reported at 10:41 p.m., Ms. Carrion said.
   ``There are some fatalities,'' she said. ``At this point,
they've mentioned six.'' However, Espanola Hospital administrator
Grant Nelson said he had been told there were six to eight deaths.
   ``The bus hit a rock slide,'' Ms. Carrion said. ``It did not go
into either river. The front of the bus was torn away and some of
the passengers may have been thrown out of the bus and landed in
the Rio Embudo.
   ``They did request search and rescue for, I guess, a river
search,'' she said, indicating that bodies may have gone into the
river and may have washed into the Rio Grande.
   Fourteen passengers were brought to the emergency room of
Espanola Hospital, nearly 20 miles southwest of Embudo, with minor
to serious injuries, Nelson said.
