<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0409EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Kurds     09-13 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Kurds,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Says Evidence Of Iraqi Chemical Weapon `Compelling'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government, citing evidence from the
United States, pressed for a U.N. investigation of charges that
Iraq used chemical weapons against ethnic Kurds.
   ``We now consider the weight of evidence of the use of chemical
weapons to be compelling,'' said a Foreign Office spokesman who, in
accordance with British practice, demanded anonymity.
   The United States, Britain, West Germany and Japan asked U.N.
Secretary- General Javier Perez de Cuellar on Monday to send a team
to Iraq to investigate the allegations that poison gas was used
against the Kurds, The New York Times reported in today's editions.
   In a story from Washington, the newspaper cited unidentified
diplomatic sources as saying the request from the four allies
reflects a growing irritation with the Iraqi government for
ignoring U.N. protests over prior use of chemical weapons during
Iraq's 8-year war with Iran.
   The British Foreign Office said it toughened its stand Monday
partly because of U.S. State Department evidence of such attacks,
which led the Senate on Friday to vote for tough economic sanctions
against Iraq.
   The measure still must be approved by the House and signed by
President Reagan.
   Last week the Foreign Office summoned the Iraqi ambassador and
expressed ``grave concern'' about the alleged attacks, but at the
time British officials maintained there was no firm evidence the
charges were true.
   ``There is now compelling evidence to trigger action,'' said the
Foreign Office spokesman.
   He said that in terms of a recent U.N. resolution the next step
was an independent investigation by Perez de Cuellar before a
decision on sanctions.
   Iraqi Ambassador Mohammed Sadiq al-Mashat has reiterated his
government's denials of the charges and told Britain to stop
interfering in Iraq's internal affairs.
   British official sources have acknowledged a reluctance by
Britain and other Western European countries to accuse Iraq for
fear, they said, of upsetting the delicate cease-fire in the
8-year-old war between Iran and Iraq.
   The Foreign Office maintained Monday it had changed its mind
also because of other evidence, including reports from Western
journalists in Turkey, where thousands of Iraqi Kurds, many
suffering chemical injuries, have fled.
   In a Kurdish refugee camp near Silopi, Turkey, near the Iraqi
border, refugees on Monday showed reporters a 13-year-old boy with
severe burns on his face and neck that they said were caused by
poison gas attacks.
   The Kurds claim Iraq used the chemical weapons as part of a
bloody offensive against the Kurds, an ethnic group in northern
Iraq that is seeking autonomy.
   About 60,000 Kurds recently fled Iraq to Turkey, citing poison
gas attacks.
   In Cairo, meanwhile, Egypt criticized the Senate sanctions,
which a Foreign Ministry official contended were groundless. The
official cited a Turkish Anatolia News Agency report claiming there
was ``no case proving Iraq used these banned weapons.
   Turkey said Friday no evidence of the use of chemical weapons
was found while screening sick and injured refugees.
</TEXT>
