<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved lower against the Japanese yen,
while stock prices edged up in lackluster trading in Tokyo today.
   The dollar closed at 133.07 yen, down 0.35 yen from Monday's
close of 133.42 yen. After opening at 133.23 yen, the U.S. currency
declined further, but stayed within a fairly narrow range of
132.95-133.25 yen. Spot trading was a moderate $4.7 billion.
   Dealers said many investors stayed on the sidelines, waiting for
the scheduled release of July U.S. trade figures on Wednesday. But
dollar-selling sentiment continued to dominate the market, they
said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues added 37.42 points or 0.13 percent, closing at
27,794.16. The index rose shortly after the market opened, lost
steam, but then managed to recover in the afternoon.
   ``Steels attracted investors in the early morning and led the
Nikkei to rise, but the market lacked the energy to maintain the
trend,'' said a dealer with Daiwa Securities in Tokyo.
   ``The market was not strong enough to keep the trading active
all day long. But investors were at least eager to buy reasonably
priced issues,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 850 million shares.
</TEXT>
