<HEAD>Bus Crashes in Northern New Mexico, Five Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with State Police now saying 5
dead, sted 6, number of passengers aboard bus, breakdown on deaths;
picks up 10th graf, ``Vern Wittner ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EMBUDO, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greyhound bus smashed into a rock slide
over a river in northern New Mexico, killing five people and and
injuring 14 passengers, authorities said today.
   The bus with 20 passengers and a driver aboard went off New
Mexico 68 over the Rio Embudo late Monday about 50 miles north of
Santa Fe near the point where the river meets the Rio Grande, State
Police spokeswoman Lupita Carrion said in Santa Fe.
   The driver and four passengers died, 14 passengers were injured
and two passengers escaped unharmed, Ms. Carrion said.
   The bus had been bound for Albuquerque from Denver when the
accident occurred less than a mile north of the Embudo Post Office,
the spokeswoman said.
   ``The bus hit a rock slide,'' which tore away the front of the
bus, she said. ``It did not go into either river.''
   The accident was first reported at 10:41 p.m., Ms. Carrion said.
   The 14 injured were taken to the emergency room of Espanola
Hospital, nearly 20 miles southwest of Embudo, said hospital
administrator Grant Nelson.
   Vern Wittner, transportation supervisor for Greyhound in
Albuquerque, said he was busy helping with rescue efforts and could
not discuss the accident.
   He referred all inquiries to Greyhound public relations in
Dallas. A call to the Dallas office reached a recording that said
the office was closed.
</TEXT>
