<DOCNO> AP880913-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0508EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Fires-Rebirth     09-13 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fires-Rebirth,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yellowstone's Rebirth Already Under Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With Sierra Fire, Bjt
^By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAMMOTH HOT SPRINGS, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blades of grass and wildflowers
are sprouting through much of the blackened earth at Yellowstone
National Park, heralding a dynamic rebirth in the wake of the
fires, park researchers say.
   The vegetation was spotted around Grant Village, which was
besieged by flames last month, said John Varley, Yellowstone's
chief of research.
   In other areas of the park, scorched pine cones from lodgepole
pines, Yellowstone's predominant conifer, are slowly opening to
spill their seeds to the earth, he said Monday.
   However, it is hard to say how quickly the burned areas will
rebound from the devastating summer of 1988, Varley said.
   In the 16 years since U.S. Forest Service and National Park
Service officials adopted a ``let-it-burn'' policy for most
naturally caused fires, there have been approximately 140 wildfires
in Yellowstone that seared some 33,000 acres, said the researcher.
But those fires didn't fully prepare researchers for this summer's
blazes, so predicting how the forests will rebound is not easy, he
added.
   ``We have a considerable body of knowledge on the rate at which
these things recover,'' said Varley. ``We're pretty confident that
they would come back well.''
   To help make those projections, a team of scientists and
researchers will meet next month to study the aftermath, Varley
said.
   The fires have created a huge laboratory for Varley and his
colleagues that will show them Yellowstone's regenerative
capabilities. It also will show tourists the devastation of fires.
   ``It is not dead,'' stressed Varley. ``There are some tops of
things that are certainly killed. But again, on the basis of the 16
years, that experience that we've had with fire and the research
thereof, we know that there will be a lot of sprouting. We know
that most of the living organisms are underneath the surface of the
soil and still are alive and well.''
   The grasses and flowers that have reappeared around Grant
Village, said Varley, have done so without rainfall.
   ``These plants are remarkably resilient to fire,'' he said.
``Most of the species have insurance policies, so to speak, because
they've been putting up with fire for thousands of years. Some of
the strategies are truly remarkable.''
   One example, he said, is the lodgepole pine. Its cones are
covered by resins that are melted away by fire, causing ``that cone
to open up slowly after the fire passes.''
   ``And so in many of these areas, in places that totally look
like moonscapes, then these seeds are being broadcasted out over
the forest floor right now, and that's the next generation that
will be coming up,'' Varley said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Hungary     09-13 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Hungary,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seoul Announces Breakthrough In Relations With Communist Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today it has
agreed with Hungary to open permanent missions, the first
diplomatic relations between South Korea and a communist nation.
   The move to normalize relations stopped short of full diplomatic
recognition, but South Korean officials said they expected the two
nations to establish diplomatic ties in the near future.
   The Seoul government is hoping the Olympic Games, which begin in
Seoul on Saturday, will play a major role in helping to open
relations with communist nations.
   Foreign Minister Choi Kwang-soo went on national television to
announce the two governments had agreed to open missions in their
capitals of Seoul and Budapest to oversee trade, scientific and
cultural relations and consular affairs.
   The two governments agreed to start negotiations on establishing
full diplomatic relations, a ministry statement said.
   ``Both governments expressed their determination to bring their
negotiations to a success as soon as possible,'' it said.
   South Korea has no relations with communist nations because of
its bitter rivalry with communist North Korea. The North has
opposed any ties between communist nations and South Korea.
   President Roh Tae-woo, who took office in February, has worked
to establish relations with communist nations to try to reduce
tension with North Korea and to boost trade.
   Roh wants to establish relations with the North's main allies,
China and the Soviet Union, to reduce their support for any North
Korean threat to the South.
   ``The exchange of missions is very significant in that South
Korea has secured a bridgehead for South Korea's advance into the
East European bloc,'' said a senior official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   China, the Soviet Union and most other communist nations ignored
a North Korean call to boycott the Olympics. The Seoul government
hopes the participation of communist nations in the Olympics will
play a major role in developing relations.
   North Korea said it will boycott the Olympics because its demand
to be a co-host of the Games was turned down by the International
Olympic Committee on the grounds that they are awarded to a single
city.
   North Korea invaded the South in 1950 and sparked the bloody,
three-year Korean War. The two sides technically remain at war
since no peace treaty was signed and the North has staged a series
of attacks on the South over the years.
   South Korea and Hungary agreed last year to establish trade
offices in the first such move between Seoul and a communist nation.
   The Seoul government is anxious to develop trade with communist
nations to open new markets and reduce its dependence on the United
States as its main export market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PilgrimManagement     09-13 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pilgrim Management,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC: Management Ready to Operate Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Managers at Pilgrim nuclear power plant, shut down
since 1986 under a government order, can handle a restart under
careful supervision, federal regulators concluded.
   A Nuclear Regulatory Commission inspection at Pilgrim recently
concluded ``with high confidence'' that Boston Edison Co.
management controls, programs and personnel are ready to support
safe startup and operation of the plant, an NRC official said
Monday.
   The commission ordered the closing because of technical and
management problems.
   An inspection conducted Aug. 8-24 found no ``fundamental flaws''
that would inhibit reactor or public safety during plant operation,
said Samuel J. Collins, the NRC's deputy director of the reactor
projects division.
   Inspectors reached their conclusions after carefully monitoring
managers' performance and qualifications, said Collin.
   He said the problem of how to decide if managers could do a good
job of running a nuclear power plant by judging their performance
at an idled facility was partly solved by using a simulator.
   The NRC is still evaluating whether the plant should be allowed
to restart.
   Collins noted that intense supervision would be necessary under
actual operating conditions. ``We intend to stay very close to that
station during any proposed restart program,'' he said.
   Boston Edison has proposed a four-month supervisory plan for the
restart process, said utility spokeswoman Elaine Robinson.
   ``It's a very careful, well-considered approach to the restart
process. There will be very intensive NRC oversight, but it also
provides for additional senior management oversight,'' she said.
   The inspection consisted of interviews with licensee personnel,
plant tours, observations of plant activities, and selective
examinations of procedures, records and documents. Inspectors also
observed plant activities on all shifts.
   Most of the senior management is new since 1986, but many
department heads remained in place, Ms. Robinson said.
   The previous management was often unstable, fixing a problem in
one area but then neglecting to maintain the improvement, Collins
said.
   ``The team they have now appears to be committed to the station
and they have a pretty good track record in the industry,'' Collins
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
