<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DelawarePrimary     09-13 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delaware Primary,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recount Ordered in Delaware Primary Senate Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recount was set for Wednesday in the
Democratic Senate primary after election officials discovered they
miscounted the returns, giving the wrong man the victory.
   Unofficial results Monday showed Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo the winner by
a slim 88-vote margin over civic activist Samuel S. Beard for the
Democratic nomination to challenge Republican U.S. Sen. William V.
Roth Jr. in November's election.
   Nearly 48 hours earlier, Beard was declared the victor in
Saturday's primary. But on Monday the unofficial statewide tally
showed Woo the winner with 20,221 votes to Beard's 20,133.
   At Beard's request, the New Castle County Board of Elections
voted unanimously for a recount. The second tally was scheduled to
begin Wednesday morning, and both candidates expressed anger over
the delay.
   The delay was due to the need to collect voting machines from
around the state, said William Burke, deputy administrative
director for the Department of Elections for New Castle County, one
of three counties in Delaware.
   Woo's win came after Beard lost 2,800 votes when a computer
keypunch error was discovered.
   Meanwhile, Woo became angry late Monday night when one of his
staffers discovered the doors to the Department of Elections for
New Castle County were wide open.
   Woo was at the election department's office and could not be
reached for comment. But his wife, Katy, said they believed the
keys to voting machines were kept in the office.
   Attorney General Charles M. Oberly III said he was contacted by
Woo about the unlocked doors and ordered Wilmington police to guard
the door overnight.
   Election officials learned early Monday that a computer keypunch
operator's error had recorded 2,800 votes too many for Beard,
according to Paul T. Hart, administrative director of the county
elections department.
   The discrepancy came in a district in New Castle County where
there are about 280 registered Democrats. In that district, Beard's
total was tallied at 2,828 votes when he actually received only 28
votes, officials said.
   Woo, a 51-year-old physics professor at the University of
Delaware, became the nation's highest ranking Chinese-American in
state office after being elected lieutenant governor four years ago
in his first bid for elected office.
   His opponent in that election, Battle Robinson, requested and
received a statewide recount. Woo won by 429 votes.
   Beard had been heavily outspent by Woo, a native of Shanghai,
China, who enjoyed the financial backing of Chinese-Americans from
across the nation.
   Beard, 49, had support from most Democratic organization leaders
and labor. He has served as chairman for job creation commissions
under the last four presidents.

</TEXT>
