<1ST_LINE>u a PM-KidnapCase     09-13 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kidnap Case,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aunt Ends Alleged Kidnapping With .38-Caliber</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The kidnapping of a 6-year-old girl ended with the
suspect lying in the bottom of ditch and the victim's aunt standing
over him with a cocked .38-caliber pistol, authorities said.
   The aunt rescued the young victim and captured the assailant
Monday when she went looking for them, and, by chance, found them
on Lookout Mountain south of Golden near Buffalo Bill's grave,
police said.
   ``I wasn't going to shoot him or anything,'' Marla, identified
only by her first name, told The Denver Post, which described the
incident in today's editions. ``I was scared as he was.
   ``When I saw (my niece) Audrey, I didn't say anything,'' she
said. ``I just pulled the gun out and I cocked it and told him to
get out.''
   Donald Dale Lewis, 26, was being held without bail in the Denver
City Jail for investigation of first-degree kidnapping,
first-degree sexual assault and sexual assault to a child.
   Lewis, who police say is on parole for sexually assaulting a
2-year-old, was being held at gunpoint by the victim's 27-year-old
aunt when police arrived and took him into custody.
   Some last names were not contained in the Post's story because
the newspaper has a policy of not naming sexual assault victims.
   Police said the little girl was playing on the sidewalk in north
Denver with a 5-year-old cousin just before 1 p.m. Monday when a
man grabbed her, dragged her into a van and sped away. The girl's
mother and a different aunt chased the van on foot for a couple of
blocks, then called police.
   Marla said her two sisters came to her house about 1:30 p.m. to
tell her the girl had been kidnapped.
   ``I said, `We'll go look for her,''' the slightly built woman
recalled. ``I had just got out of the shower, and I went and got my
gun and I got my bullets.''
   Because of the ruckus that had been raised at the scene, Marla
figured the kidnapper would be heading out of town.
   ``I told her (the mother) we'd go to this one place, so we drove
up to Lookout Mountain.''
   While the girl's mother was calling her own mother in Elk City,
Okla., from a pay telephone atop the mountain, Marla and the other
aunt saw a van matching the description of the kidnapper's vehicle.
Marla jumped back in her car to follow it while the other aunt
stayed to tell the mother what was happening.
   Soon the van pulled over and the driver waved her by, she said.
   ``But, I got out of the car and had the gun in my pocket. And I
walked up to the car and I saw (the girl) there, and that's when I
pulled the gun out and I told him to get out of the car and told
him to get in front of the van and lie down.
   ``He lay down in the ditch in front of the van.''
   She then told her niece to get out of the van and into her car
and lock the doors. She told passers-by to call the police.
   ``I just held him there until the police came. When the police
came I just walked over to the car and hugged (the girl).''
   Marla recalled that when police arrived, she had to tell them
she didn't know how to uncock the pistol. The officer had her put
the gun on the ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
