<HEAD>Jumbo Jet Returns To Pittsburgh Airport After Engine Fails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British Airways jumbo jet carrying 77 people
made an emergency landing shortly after taking off from Greater
Pittsburgh International Airport when one of its three engines
failed, authorities said.
   The L-1011 took off about 6:45 p.m. Monday, circled the airport
and landed about eight minutes later after it blew a turbine, said
Mark Chamovitz, airport operations manager.
   No injuries were reported, he said.
   Sixty-one passengers and 16 crew members were on the aircraft,
said Sandy Gardiner, a British Airways spokesman in New York. The
airline planned to book all passengers on other flights, he added.
   The flight originated at Dulles Airport in Washington, D.C., and
was scheduled to fly to Philadelphia and London, Gardiner said.
