<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InventionConvention     09-13 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Invention Convention,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Annual Show To Stress High-tech, Not Wacky World of Inventors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The craziest new gadgets may get the
most attention at the second annual Invention Convention this
weekend, but organizers hope the show dispells the notion that
inventors are wacky.
   ``We're trying to stress high tech this year,'' spokeswoman Suzy
Mallery said Monday. ``It seems everybody pictures inventors as
some kind of long-haired weirdos. And we're trying to change that.''
   ``We've got some high-tech stuff that will blow your mind,'' Ms.
Mallery said.
   A magnetic car that travels 200 mph, a flying boat, an automatic
squeeze-handle screw driver and a sound-emitting chair that is
supposed to provide the equivalent of eight hours of sleep in 20
minutes are among the 300 inventions that will be on exhibit.
   Another thing organizers hope to change with the displays are
the relatively small number of Americans marketing their creations,
said Steve Gnass, a Beverly Hills marketing consultant who runs the
convention.
   ``We think the convention is rekindling America's creative
spirit,'' Gnass said. ``Inventors are the underpinning of our
economic future. Politics have never really done anything
revolutionary for people. It's been technology that's always put us
ahead, advanced civilization.''
   Half of the U.S. patents issued last year went to foreigners,
Gnass said.
   Some 20,000 people are expected to attend the four-day affair at
the Pasadena Center, Ms. Mallery said.
   The convention starts with seminars and panels Thursday and
exhibitions are open to the public Saturady and Sunday.
   Also on tap are more than 50 seminars for would-be inventors.
Panel speakers will include Yoshiro Nakamats, inventor of the
computer floppy disc, and Jack Ryan, who dreamed up the Barbie Doll.
</TEXT>
