<HEAD>Dollar Little Changed, Gold Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up slightly against major
currencies today in quiet trading before the release of U.S. trade
figures Wednesday.
   Gold prices firmed following their sharp fall Monday.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the U.S. currency would most
likely trade in a narrow range before the release of the U.S. July
trade figures.
   A Rome-based dealer with a major Italian commercial bank said he
expected a $12.75 billion trade deficit, wider than June's $12.54
billion gap.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar dropped 0.35 yen to close at 133.07 and dealers said the
market was moving slowly while awaiting the trade figures.
   Later, in London, the dollar was quoted at 133.15 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8455 West German marks, up from 1.8453
   _1.5565 Swiss francs, up from 1.5535
   _6.2807 French francs, up from 6.2775
   _2.0822 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0817
   _1,379.50 Italian lire, up from 1,378.50
   _1.2365 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2395
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6985, compared with $1.6958
late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $420.50 a troy ounce, up
from a $419.25 bid late Monday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $420.80.
   One London dealer said gold appeared hemmed in a tight range for
the near future because it found strong support between $417 and
$420 an ounce.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $420.40, up from $418 late Monday.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $3.11 to close at a bid of $422.69.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.43 a troy
ounce, up from Monday's $6.41.
