<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Hijacking     09-13 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Hijacking,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Criticizes Soldiers Who Killed Hijacked Passengers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers who stormed a hijacked plane in Leningrad
in March shot a passenger in the back and didn't take precautions
to prevent injuring innocent people, a government newspaper
reported.
   Izvestia's article Monday represented a rare public criticism of
the country's security forces, and raised new questions about the
bungled attempt to end the March 8 hijacking.
   ``Our forces are not prepared to act in extreme situations,''
said an article published Monday in the state-run daily Izvestia.
   A family of 11 Siberian jazz musicians known as the Ovechkins
hijacked a Tu-154 plane carrying 76 people on a flight from the
Siberian city of Irkutsk to Leningrad. They demanded that the
Aeroflot Soviet jetliner fly to London or Bonn, West Germany.
   Ground controllers tricked the family into thinking the plane
was landing in Finland, but it actually touched down at an airfield
near Leningrad. A special anti-terrorist squad of soldiers stormed
the plane after the Ovechkins set off a homemade bomb, starting a
fire, Soviet press reports said.
   The soldiers killed a stewardess and three passengers in the
amubush, during which four of the Ovechkins committed suicide after
killing their mother at her request, the official news agency Tass
reported.
   In the disorderly evacuation of passengers, some were forced to
jump onto the tarmac and 35 people were injured, news reports said.
   The Izvestia article, quoting witnesses who testifieed at the
trial of two members of the Ovechkin family that began last week,
called into question the assault squad's actions.
   ``I fell onto the ground, crouched, my hands were twisted behind
me, I was placed with my face to the concrete and shot in the
back,'' said a passenger identified only as Maizel, a Leningrad
student. He implied that the soldiers mistook him for one of the
hijackers.
   ``Then they ... moved me forward several meters (yards) and put
my face down and made me lie with my arms behind my head,'' Maizel
added.
   He said the soldiers beat him on his legs and tried to hit his
face and head, but he shielded himself.
   The prosecutor's office is investigating this incident and other
actions of the rescue squad.
   Two of the surviving Ovechkins, 28-year-old Olga and her
17-year-old brother, Igor, went on trial Sept. 6 in Irkutsk. They
are charged with ``seizing an airliner with a view to flying abroad
with use of arms that resulted in the death of people and other
grave consequences,'' Tass said.
   It said Olga Ovechkin testified that she tried to prevent her
brothers from hijacking the plane.
</TEXT>
