<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO Exercises,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Ship Runs Aground During Maneuver</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BODOE, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS Boulder landing craft ran aground
today off central Norway during a NATO exercise, spewing about 880
gallons of diesel oil into the Norwegian Sea, the Allied Press and
Information Center said.
   No one was reported injured in the accident northeast of Froeya
island. It occurred at 2 a.m during the nine-nation Teamwork '88
land and sea maneuver involving 45,000 soldiers, the center said.
   A Norwegian tug was steaming to the scene to help free the ship.
   Late Sunday, the 8,400-ton British logistics landing vessel Sir
Geraint ran aground in the Hemnesfjorden but later returned to duty.
   On Sunday, the British HMS Penelope and the Canadian support
ship HMCS Poreserver collided during a refueling operation. The
Penelope was sailing back to Rosyth, Scotland for inspection.
   No injuries were reported on either vessel, said a Defense
Ministry spokesman in London.
