<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FireSurvivors     09-13 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fire Survivors,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Watch, Pack And Wait As Fire Creeps Closer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Sierra Fire, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE WILDWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rose Boyer loaded her station wagon
with family pictures and memorabilia and her husband, Bud, sprayed
water on the dry grass around their home while a mountain blaze
flickered just up the hillside.
   ``We stayed last night, and I want to stay, but a fire is one of
the worst of my fears,'' she said late Monday night.
   At least 15 homes have been lost in the affluent residential
area and the fire continued to burn on the edge of the community,
about 60 miles northeast of Sacramento, on Monday evening.
   The out-of-control mountain blaze has forced the evacuation of
at least 8,000 people. At least 142 structures, including nearly
100 homes, were destroyed, according to officials who early today
estimated the blaze had burned more than 20,000 acres.
   Around the Boyers' home, separated by a 30-foot street and just
one row of homes from the closest burning trees, about a third of
the homes were still occupied by residents who said they wouldn't
leave until the last moment.
   But Boyer, 48, said one sleepless night was all he and his
46-year-old wife could take.
   ``We stayed last night, but we didn't sleep at all, didn't even
try. We stayed with the house all day,'' he said. ``It seems the
fire came up, backed down and now it's back up again, only closer.''
   For Harry Derrick, 64, and his wife, Jean, 63, the fire that
brushed through this Sierra foothill community was a stunning
shock, but not a new experience.
   ``I'm going to think positively. We went through it before and
we will again,'' Mrs. Derrick said, recalling being evacuated from
a 1971 fire that came near their home in the Los Angeles suburb of
Chatsworth.
   The Derricks moved into their new retirement home here just a
month ago. ``I can't believe it,'' Mrs. Derrick said. ``I don't
even have the drapes up yet. The paint isn't even dry. This is just
terrible.''
   For some residents, the fire made a quick entrance into their
community.
   ``All of a sudden it was here,'' said John Bridges, 30. ``It
swept right past us, even burned the brush under the deck, but the
house didn't catch. I can't image all the things we would have
lost,'' he said.
   Bridges and a friend, Matt Waldrom, 28, said after the fire
brushed past Bridges' home Sunday night they joined about six other
residents to help three professional firefighters.
   ``I couldn't believe those guys,'' Waldrom said. ``They told us
exactly what to do and we saved maybe a half dozen homes, and they
told us, `Watch out. It's coming.'''
   ``It was half a mile away, and two minutes later it was 100
yards away, and we got behind a building and it blew right by us.
I've never seen anything like it.''
   ``It was terrible,'' Bridges added, ``but it was probably the
most satisfying weekend of my life. We saved some homes, and I even
saved my brand new truck.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
