<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Politics 3rdLd-Writethru   09-13 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Politics, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0532,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Kidnapped In Beirut</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with defense minister released. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian militiamen kidnapped Defense
Minister Adel Osseiran on Beirut's dividing Green Line today, but
freed him after the army threatened to move against them, police
said.
   Osseiran, a Shiite Moslem, was released in Christian east Beirut
this afternoon and was on his way to the western Moslem sector of
the capital, a police spokesman said. The spokesman cannot be named
under standing regulation.
   The warning by army commander Gen. Michel Aoun, a Christian,
came an hour after gunmen of the Lebanese Forces, the Christians'
main militia, seized Osseiran, 83, near Beirut's dividing Green
Line and took him to their seaside headquarters, police reported.
   The Lebanese Forces command denied it was holding Osseiran. It
said in a statement that the militia's security apparatus has been
``put on alert with orders to search every corner of east Beirut
for Osseiran.''
   But the police spokesman said the militia command had initially
offered to swap Osseiran for Christian parliament member Farid
Serhal, who it said had been kidnapped in west Beirut on Thursday.
   The Lebanese Forces are the Christians' main militia.
   The police spokesman said Aoun has long been at odds with the
Lebanese Forces over their growing dominance of a ``state within
the state'' in east Beirut and the Christian heartland north of the
capital that has eroded the authority of Lebanon's divided
government.
   ``The general simply cannot tolerate the abduction of his own
chief, the defense minister, in an area that is supposed to be
under direct army control,'' the spokesman said.
   The Lebanese Forces have claimed that Serhal, a Maronite
Catholic, was kidnapped by pro-Syrian militiamen of Druse warlord
Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party at a checkpoint south
of Beirut last Thursday as he was driving to Jezzine.
   The Christians claimed he was was being kept at the Bristol
Hotel in west Beirut ``against his will.''
   The Bristol acknowledged that Serhal has been staying there
``incommunicado'' since Thursday.
   Osseiran's kidnapping heightened tension between Christians and
Moslems amid a political deadlock in efforts to elect a new
president. The political wrangling has raised fears it could
rekindle Lebanon's 13-year-old civil war.
   Police said Osseiran's kidnappers made the demand for Serhal's
return in a telephone call to the office of acting Prime Minister
Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, in west Beirut.
   The spokesman said the Christian militiamen stopped Osseiran's
black limousine at a Lebanese Forces checkpoint on the east side of
the Green Line.
   ``Two militiamen entered the car and drove with the defense
minister to the Lebanese Forces headquarters,'' the spokesman added.
   Osseiran was kidnapped a few hundred yards from a sit-in by
Serhal's supporters to demand his return.
   ``Return Deputy Serhal!'' the protesters chanted as the sit-in
blocked traffic across the nearby Museum Crossing, which links the
two sections of Beirut.
   Serhal was among Christian legislators who boycotted a
parliamentary session called Aug. 18 to elect a new president
because they opposed the candidacy of Suleiman Franjieh, a former
president who is backed by Syria.
   The session foundered because not enough legislators turned up
to form the required quorum. Franjieh, president from 1970 to 1976,
was the only serious candidate.
   Franjieh's followers accused the Lebanese Forces of forecefully
preventing deputies from showing up at the session.
   Osseiran's son, Ali, was kidnapped in west Beirut on June 17,
1987 with American journalist Charles Glass and their driver. Ali
Osseiran and the driver were freed that June 24, and Glass escaped
Aug. 17, 1987.
</TEXT>
