<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Moore     09-13 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Moore,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Ambassador to Ireland Dead at 77</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John D.J. Moore, who was ambassador to Ireland
during the Nixon administration and a W.R. Grace & Co. executive,
has died at age 77.
   Moore had been diagnosed as having bone cancer six months ago,
but remained active until about a week ago when ``he took a turn
for the worse,'' said Fred Bona, a W.R. Grace spokesman. He died
Monday at his Manhattan home.
   A 1935 graduate of Yale University Law School, Moore practiced
law in New York City and was assistant corporation counsel under
Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia and an assistant district attorney.
   He was with W.R. Grace, a diversified chemical company, from
1946 to 1969, serving in Peru, Washington and as a vice president
at the New York headquarters.
   Vice President Richard Nixon had Moore accompany him to South
America in 1958 and to the Soviet Union in 1959. When he became
president in 1969, Nixon appointed Moore ambassador to Ireland.
Moore served six years.
   As ambassador, Moore negotiated an aviation agreement that
gained the United States landing rights for U.S. airlines in
Dublin. He also established a professorship of American studies at
the National University of Ireland.
   In 1976, he rejoined Grace as a member of its board. Upon his
retirement at age 75, he became a director emeritus and a
consultant to the company.
</TEXT>
