<DOCNO> AP880913-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0840EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Olympics-Ads     09-13 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Olympics-Ads,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Asking Advertisers To Give Up Part of Screen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC officials have asked Olympic advertisers to
allow silent live coverage of certain events to continue during
commercials in a corner of the television screen, according to a
report published today.
   NBC Sports executive producer Michael Weisman confirmed that the
plan had been presented to certain advertisers and said some have
indicated interest, the Daily News reported.
   Under the plan, unprecedented in Olympic coverage, NBC would
superimpose a silent picture in the lower-righthand corner of the
television screen during commercials in sports such as basketball,
volleyball, cycling and long-distance track events. The sport would
occupy one-quarter of the television screen.
   NBC is hoping to avoid the harsh viewer criticism ABC was
subjected to during this year's Winter Olympics, when goals were
scored during commercial breaks of hockey telecasts. NBC has
experimented with the technique during telecasts of major-league
baseball games.
   ``Some of these athletes have worked a lifetime to get to the
Olympics,'' said Weisman, speaking from Seoul, where the Olympics
begin later this week. ``It would be a shame if a great performance
wasn't seen by the home folks because we were in a commercial
break.''
   Advertisers are paying NBC up to $330,000 for a 30-second
commercial.
   Weisman said advertisers should consider the ``good-will'' value
of consenting to the proposal.
   ``Viewers will appreciate the gesture and so will the
athletes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
