<HEAD>Mother Of Abandoned Newborn Wants Daughter Returned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE WORTH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old mother accused of putting
her newborn baby inside a brown paper bag and dumping her on the
sidewalk says she wants her daughter back.
   The Lake Worth teen, whose name was not being released, turned
herself in Monday and faced child-abuse charges for allegedly
abandoning the baby outside an apartment complex after giving birth
Saturday, said police Detective Susan Pults.
   The baby was placed in the custody of the state health
department and was reported in good condition Monday at St. Mary's
Hospital in West Palm Beach, said hospital spokesman Don Chester.
   Meanwhile, more than 20 families contacted the health department
Monday and offered to adopt or care for the 6-pound, 2-ounce girl.
   The mother told police she panicked after giving birth about
noon Saturday and dumped the baby ``some place where she was sure
it would be found,'' said Pults. The baby was found about an hour
later by an 88-year-old woman.
   The mother feared ``she would be thrown out of her house if she
came home with a baby,'' police said.
   A judge will decide whether to return the infant to her teen
mother, award custody to her grandparents or put the baby up for
adoption, said HRS spokesman Cam Freedlund.
   Police learned the mother's identity after someone called and
told them her name, Pults said.
   The father of the infant was identified, but was not charged,
she said.
   Following the mother's arrest, she was taken to the Juvenile
Detention Center in West Palm Beach and was later released into her
parents' custody, police said.
