<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci-China,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Says China Military Sales Talks Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks are ``moving forward'' on sales of U.S.
military goods to mainland China, Defense Decretary Frank Carlucci
said today.
   ``We are moving forward on a number of programs with the
Chinese. Avionics upgrades for their fighter aircraft and radar
programs, some torpoedo programs. We're discussing some other
programs with them, all within the constraints of our normal
technology transfer program,'' Carlucci said on NBC's ``Today''
program.
   Asked if that means the transfer of military technology to China
will occur, Carlucci responded:
   ``The technology transfer is moving forward, yes.''
   Transfer of some technology to China had been held up in the
past because of concern about sales of weapons to Iran, although
those sales were denied by the Chinese.
   Carlucci, who returned Sunday from a five-day trip to China for
discussions with defense officials there, said that after
discussing the problem with the Chinese he is ``quite satisfied
that they will do nothing to destabilize'' the Middle East.
   But he declined to expound, saying the Chinese prefer that
details not be discussed in public.
   Carlucci said a decision was also reached in principle to allow
the Chinese to launch three American satellites, ``but there is no
technology transfer involved.''
