<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0852EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Ehrlichman-Malek     09-13 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ehrlichman-Malek,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nixon Adviser Calls Bush Aide's Resignation Unfair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House adviser John D. Ehrlichman
said today that Frederic V. Malek took ``a bum rap'' in resigning
from the Republican National Committee because of alleged
anti-Semitism while he worked for President Nixon.
   In searching out what a White House memo described as a possible
``Jewish cabal'' in the Bureau of Labor Statistics in 1971, Malek
was simply carrying out orders from a Nixon who was simply
``venting spleen,'' Ehrlichman said on the CBS-TV ``This Morning''
program.
   Malek had been named deputy GOP chairman by Republican
presidential nominee George Bush, but resigned Sunday when The
Washington Post reported he had compiled a list of senior Jewish
officials in the Bureau of Labor Statistics on Nixon's orders.
   Nixon thought the Labor Department agency was reporting
unemployment statistics with an unfavorable slant. Two Jewish
officials subsequently were demoted.
   ``When all of the facts are looked at I think its a bum rap,''
said Ehrlichman, who was Nixon's chief domestic policy adviser.
   Ehrlichman said the phrase ``Jewish cabal'' written in the
margin of a memorandum was ``straight, vintage Richard Nixon.''
   ``This thing, `Jewish cabal' and all of that, is kind of pure
Nixon venting spleen,'' Ehrlichman said. ``Most people on the staff
really didn't pay any attention to that. They didn't do anything
about it. And those things kind of blew over as kind of rhetorical
excess.''
   Ehrlichman said it was ``extremely unfair'' to Malek, who ``is
the farthest thing from a bigot of anybody I know.''
   ``If you recognize it for what it is, which is a fellow back 17
years ago doing something the president of the United States
instructed him to do and he had no discretion in doing, I think it
ought to just go away,'' he said.
   Malek said in a statement Sunday that he resigned to keep the
Bush campaign focused on the issues. He admitted compiling data for
former White House chief of staff H.R. Haldeman, but denied he had
a role in any demotions.
   Bush strongly defended Malek and denied that he was prejudiced.
</TEXT>
