<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RacialRemark     09-13 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Racial Remark,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Refuses To Give Professor His Job Back Immediately</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 4th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge refused to lift the suspension
of a Georgia Southwestern College professor, saying academic
freedom was no excuse to make a racial remark.
   ``If academic freedom or tenure gives one the right to use
expressions in public that are patently offensive to a particular
group ... then quite possibly the boundaries of proper conduct
should be redrawn,'' said U.S. District Judge Duross Fitzpatrick.
   Fitzpatrick also said in Monday's rejection of a suit by Allen
Towery that issuing an injunction in favor of the professor could
inflame racial feelings at the college.
   Towery, a tenured associate professor of English, was suspended
with pay in March after calling freshman Ginevra Dennis of Atlanta
a ``black bitch.''
   He admitted making the remark, but said Miss Dennis had provoked
him when the two argued over her request to withdraw from his class
with a passing grade.
   Towery said Monday evening of Fitzpatrick's ruling, ``Who could
be happy with this? There's not really anything else I can say.''
   Miss Dennis said she was relieved. ``I thought he might be able
to return, even though he had been suspended.''
   She said she still believes Towery should have been fired.
   After a hearing in June, a faculty committee recommended that
Towery be allowed to teach again during fall quarter. Georgia
Southwestern President William H. Capitan overruled the committee
last month and suspended Towery without pay for the quarter.
   Towery, 50, then filed a lawsuit charging his suspension without
pay was a violation of due process and that his career, reputation
and finances have suffered. The suit asked $250,000 in damages.
   Towery argued in a hearing his constitutional right of due
process had been violated when Capitan overruled the committee.
Capitan said he based his decision in part on evidence not
presented to the committee.
   Capitan testified that his work to relieve racial tensions on
campus would be difficult if the professor returned to the
classroom this month.
   In his ruling, the judge said that Towery ``showed a lack of
discipline when he used a particularly egregious expression in the
presence of a young black woman, whatever the provocation.''
</TEXT>
