<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InsiderTrading     09-13 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insider Trading,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hamburger Chain Founder's Son Ordered to Pay $10,500 in
Insider-Trading Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of the founder of the Carl's Jr.
hamburger chain was ordered to repay $10,500 as part of a federal
insider-trading suit against him and more than a dozen other
relatives and company officers.
   Carl Leo Karcher was ordered to give up the amount he avoided in
losses by acting on inside information to sell debt securities in
Carl Karcher Enterprises Inc. in 1984.
   U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie, who ordered the payment
Monday, also issued a permanent injunction barring Karcher from
future insider trades. However, the judge declined to impose triple
damages requested by the Securities and Exchange Commission, which
had filed the civil suit in April after trading irregularities were
uncovered in random computer checks.
   The case continues against the other defendants, including
Carl's Jr. founder Carl N. Karcher and his brother, Donald, who is
president and chief operating officer of Karcher Enterprises.
   Carl N. Karcher, who appears in folksy commercials for the
hamburger chain with 450 outlets in California, Nevada, Arizona and
Oregon, is a prominent social benefactor in Orange County.
   The SEC contends that the brothers told relatives in advance of
an unfavorable earnings report on the chain in October 1984. The
relatives are accused of using that information to sell securities,
avoiding losses totaling $300,000.
   If they are found guilty and triple damages are applied against
them they could face more than $1 million in penalties.
   The brothers aren't accused of making trades themselves.
   Carl Leo Karcher maintained he didn't know he had broken any
laws by selling Karcher debentures in October 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
