<HEAD>Space Shuttle Meeting Starts To Set Launch Date</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `Space shuttle...', and penultimate graf to
UPDATE with meeting under way. Meeting is closed; no briefing or
announcement expected this cycle.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The launch team here is ready to see
Discovery off in about two weeks in the first space shuttle mission
since the Challenger tragedy, NASA says.
   Launch Director Bob Sieck and his team held a launch readiness
review Monday, and concluded there were no ``show stoppers'' that
would bar a launch the last week of this month, NASA said.
   Space shuttle officials from around the country began a two-day
meeting today to assess preparations for the mission and set a firm
launch date.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has been
considering a date between Sept. 26 and 29. An announcement is
expected Wednesday.
   The purpose of today's meeting ``is to have all project
managers, both NASA and contractors, to say if they are ready or
not,'' said Rear Adm. Richard Truly, director of the shuttle at
NASA headquarters in Washington.
   ``Then we'll set a date,'' Truly said. ``It will be in the last
week in September, unless there is a hiccup.''
   Among those taking part in the meetings are two of the
astronauts who will fly aboard Discovery, commander Rick Hauck and
mission specialist Mike Lounge.
   The shuttle has been grounded since Challenger exploded Jan. 28,
1986, killing the crew of seven.
</TEXT>
