<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-RamsteinCrash     09-13 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Ramstein Crash,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll In Air Disaster Rises To 61</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAINZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from the Ramstein air
show disaster climbed to 61 today when a 43-year-old West German
man died of his injuries, a government official said.
   Bernd Horion, a spokesman for Rhineland Palatinate state, said
the man died at a Ludwigshafen clinic early today, more than two
weeks after the world's worst air show catastrophe. He did not
identify the man.
   Of the 155 victims still hospitalized, 14 are in critical
condition, Horion said.
   On Aug. 28, an Italian air force stunt team jet fighter collided
with two other Italian planes and crashed into spectators at the
U.S. Air Force base at Ramstein in southwestern Germany.
   The latest death brings the toll to: 54 West Germans, a U.S.
soldier and her 9-year-old son, one French citizen, one Dutch
citizen and the three Italian pilots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
