<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UnitedPlane     09-13 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-United Plane,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United DC-10 Skids, Nose Wheel Snaps In Mud At Stapleton</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines officials are still uncertain
about what caused Flight 225 to skid off a runway and its nose gear
to collapse, the second such accident in recent months involving a
DC-10's landing gear.
   United said there were 197 passengers and 10 crew members on
board the flight, which originated in Hartford, Conn., and made
stops in Detroit and Chicago. No one was seriously injured.
   The nose gear broke when the plane went off the runway during
landing at Stapleton International Airport at 1:50 p.m.
   In May, the nose gear on an American Airlines DC-10 collapsed
when it ran off the end of a runway at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport. Six people were injured in that accident,
which prompted a special Federal Aviation Administration
investigation of all DC-10 landing gear braking systems.
   That investigation is incomplete.
   In Monday's accident, a pilot said he lost control of the
steering on the 13-year-old plane just as it landed, said Lt. Jerry
Stout of the Denver Fire Department. United officials declined to
speculate on the cause.
   Many passengers were shaken after the rough landing _ one
passenger suffered a minor ankle injury during the evacuation _ but
they praised the actions of the crew.
   ``People were really flipping out, but the (flight attendants)
were incredibly under control,'' said passenger Frank Lampe, of
Boulder, Colo.
   The Rev. Jeffrey Loebl, a Jesuit priest from Milwaukee, said the
plane landed ``on a wing and a prayer.''
   ``I was afraid, but all God needs is a good simple act of trust
and he can do the rest,'' he said. ``And there were a lot of people
besides me praying.''
   ``When we got on the bus to take us back to the terminal, we all
cheered,'' Loebl said. ``Once for the crew, because they were
great, and once just because we made it.''
   Passenger Jennifer Bandt said she knows what caused the accident.
   ``The plane got sick,'' said the 3-year-old, who had bumps and
scrapes like many of the other passengers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
