<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Housing     09-13 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Housing,590</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped with 11 a.m. EDT signing ceremony</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signing Anti-Discrimination Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House is turning on some
election-year, Rose Garden charm to celebrate President Reagan's
signing of a bill that strengthens the government's power to combat
housing discrimination.
   Some 100 congressional leaders, Cabinet officers and other
administration
   officials were scheduled to gather today at the White House to
witness the presidential signing ceremony.
   The effort is seen as a boon to the White House aspirations of
Vice President George Bush, whose staff was described as helping
forge a compromise on the measure.
   But members of both parties, however, had rushed to become
co-sponsors of the measure after the president signaled his
willingness to sign it into law.
   The original fair housing law, passed in 1968 after the
assassination of Martin Luther King, Jr., gave the federal
government only a mediation role in settling housing disputes.
   Under the new law, the secretary of housing and urban
development is empowered to go to court to seek stiff fines against
property owners accused of discrimination.
   The bill received final congressional approval in early August,
before Reagan left on his traditional three-week summer vacation.
However, the legislation's transfer to the White House was delayed
so that a signing ceremony could be held after Reagan's return to
Washington last week.
   The measure gives the federal government its first significant
powers to combate housing discrimination.
   The handicapped and families with children under 18 would be
protected for the first time from housing discrimination. The
current law covered discrimination against racial minorities and
legislation signed into law in 1974 barred discrimination on the
basis of sex.
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., a chief sponsor, hailed the new
legislation as giving the government ``a tough remedy'' against
housing discrimination.
   Specter credited Bush's staff with being ``very active'' in
negotiating compromise language that helped bring the bill to the
floor.
   Other primary sponsors of the bill included Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., and Rep. Hamilton Fish, R-N.Y.
   Opponents of the measure, such as Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho.,
had criticized the measure as ``unfair housing bill,'' contending
it intruded on property rights and increased costs due to
accessibility requirements for the handicapped and disabled.
   Other major provisions of the bill include:
   _The secretary of housing and urban development would try to win
a conciliation agreement after a complaint is filed. If that effort
fails, the secretary or any party could take the case to an
independent administrative law judge in HUD or to U.S. District
Court.
   _If the administrative judge finds that someone has engaged or
is about to engage in a discriminatory practice, he shall order
appropriate relief, which may include actual damages, an injunction
or civil penalties.
   _The maximum fines would be $10,000 for a first violation,
$25,000 for a second violation in a five-year period and $50,000
for two or more violations within a seven-year period.
   _New buildings with four or more units must be constructed to
they are readily accessible to the handicapped. Doors must be wide
enough to accommodate wheelchairs; switches and outlets must be in
accessible locations; bathroom walls must be reinforced to allow
later installation of grab bars. This would apply to dwellings set
for occupancy 30 months after the law's enactment.
   _Children could be barred from housing intended for the elderly.
Such housing is defined as a community where at least 80 percent of
the dwellings are occupied by at least one person age 55 or older,
and significant facilities and services are provided; or those
occupied solely by people age 62 and older.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Gorbachev     09-13 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Leader Gets Second Day Of Complaints From Siberians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the second day in a row, Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev faced complaints today from Siberians angry about
housing, food shortages and medical care.
   After Gorbachev told workers at a synthetic fiber factory that
the ruling Politburo he heads was asked to turn special attention
to a shortage of kindergartens, a voice rang out:
   ``We have kindergartens. We don't have housing, and the medical
facilities are bad,'' the Tass news agency quoted one worker as
shouting to Gorbachev at the Khimvolokno plant in the Siberian city
of Krasnoyarsk.
   On Monday, Gorbachev heard similar complaints when he stopped in
a tiny village, Yemelyanovo, on his way to Kransoyarsk from the
airport to which he had flown from Moscow.
   ``We have no hot water. You do what you can to wash,'' one man
shouted at the 57-year-old Communist Party chief.
   Usually, Soviet citizens politely praise Gorbachev and his
policies or ask mild questions when he stops for chats as he tours
the vast country. But Gorbachev came back from a six-week vacation
to a street-side discussion in Yemelyanovo and at the Krasnoyarsk
factory filled with complaints about food and living conditions.
   The evening television news program Vremya led its Monday
evening program with a report of about 20 minutes on Gorbachev's
trip to the city about 2,000 miles east of Moscow. It included the
acrimonious exchange in Yemeleyanovo.
   As a crowd pressed closer and closer to Gorbachev and his wife,
Raisa, shouting complaints and questions, the general secretary cut
in: ``OK, comrades, I got caught your drift.''
   The Soviet leader blamed local and national officials for
failing to develop social services in Krasnoyarsk, and reiterated
that he is committed to providing each Soviet family with a
separate apartment by the year 2000.
   But some in the crowd were not satisfied.
   ``There will never be that,'' said one man, apparently referring
to the planned individual housing.
   Another man doubted the discussion would be covered by the
officially controlled media.
   ``Mikhail Sergeyevich, will everything be shown on television or
will half be cut out?''
   ``All of it will be shown,'' the Soviet leader responded.
   One of the most vocal of the crowd members, a blond-haired man
in his 20s, began the complaints by shouting about poor management
of a local grain storage facility.
   Gorbachev asked for support for his reform policies as residents
complained about long lines for meat, sausage and other foods, as
well as a lack of hot water.
   ``The most important thing is that you believe in our politics
and in the leadership that is still being formed. It's still being
formed at the regional and provincial levels,'' Gorbachev said.
   He told the group that he was not interested in blind faith, but
in reasoned trust for his policies and the people implementing them.
   ``We're on the right path, comrades,'' he said. ``No need to get
lost. We're on the right path.''
   Today, Gorbachev stopped at Khimvolokno, which Tass said was a
factory key to improving the supply and quality of consumer goods.
The plant is now under reconstruction because it, as well as
associated facilities, are old.
   ``Social development has chronically lagged: housing, schools
and hospitals. Now we must together restore that which we lost
during those long years,'' Tass quoted Gorbachev as saying.
   Tass said Gorbachev would stay in the Krasnoyarsk region, which
occupies one-tenth of the Soviet Union, until the end of the week.
   Krasnoyarsk also is the site of a Soviet radar station that the
United States says is an obstacle to arms control negotiations.
Gorbachev did not discuss the radar site in comments distributed by
the Tass news agency and shown on Soviet television.
   He had been out of public view since July 30, when he met with
the West German foreign minister. Soviet officials said he had been
on vacation.
</TEXT>
