<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0519 09-13 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0519,0896</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS obits on Palmieri, moved as a0543, and Moore, a0548</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Edd Bailey</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edd Bailey, 83, who worked his way from
carman's helper to president of the Union Pacific Railroad, died
Sunday in Cheyenne, Wyo.
   In 1922, Bailey took a job as a helper in the railroad's
car-repair shop in Cheyenne. He later worked as a freight yard
blacksmith, loaded mail cars and served as a brakeman, conductor,
special police agent and trainmaster.
   By 1945, Bailey had become superintendent of the railroad's
Nebraska and Wyoming divisions. He was appointed vice president in
charge of operations in 1957 and seven years later became the
executive officer of the railroad's transportation division. In
1965, he was named president of the railroad. Bailey retired in
1971 and served on the board of directors of the parent Union
Pacific Corp. until 1974.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Moore</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John D.J. Moore, a one-time New York City
official who was ambassador to Ireland in the Nixon administration
and director emeritus of W.R. Grace & Co., died Monday of bone
cancer. He was 77.
   Moore practiced law in New York City and was assistant
corporation counsel under Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia and an assistant
district attorney. He was with Grace, a diversified chemical
company, from 1946 to 1969 as corporate vice president, serving in
Peru, Washington and the New York headquarters.
   Nixon appointed him ambassador to Ireland in 1969 and he served
six years, the longest tenure of any ambassador appointed to
Ireland. In 1976, Moore rejoined Grace and upon his retirement
became a director emeritus and a consultant to the company.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Dorothy Gerber</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dorothy Scott Gerber, widow of the Gerber
Products Co. founder, died Sunday at 84.
   Mrs. Gerber played a key role in the early introduction of
Gerber baby food in 1928. It was through her urging that her
husband, Daniel F. Gerber, first pureed peas for their daughter,
Sally, at what then was known as the Fremont Canning Co., which was
owned by the Gerber family.
   After the company was established, Mrs. Gerber wrote a
nationally syndicated column, ``Bringing Up Baby,'' in which the
mother of five offered child-rearing hints. The column appeared in
newspapers and magazines for many years.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John White</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Sylvester White, a television actor who
portrayed the assistant principal Michael Woodman on the late 1970s
comedy series ``Welcome Back, Kotter,'' died Sunday at 68.
   White also appeared in such programs as ``Kojak,'' and
``Baretta,'' and appeared in the TV films ``Hustling,'' ``The
Law,'' ``The Gun'' and ``The Marcus-Nelson Murders.'' White also
was an author who penned ``Bugs,'' and ``Veronica,'' both one-act
plays. He also wrote the play ``Bananas.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Margaret McFarland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORGAN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret B. McFarland, the child psychologist
children's television show host Fred Rogers described as ``the most
major influence in my professional life,'' died Monday after a long
illness. She was 83.
   Highly regarded and recognized in the fields of child
development, education and psychology, Miss McFarland co-founded
the Arsenal Family and Children's Center with Dr. Benjamin Spock
and Erik Erikson in 1953 and served as its director until 1971.
   She also was a consultant for Rogers' television show, ``Mister
Rogers' Neighborhood.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Alan Bible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Nevada Sen. Alan Harvey Bible, a
man consumer advocate Ralph Nader once called one of the Senate's
most productive members, died Monday at 78 from complications of a
respiratory illness.
   Bible was a major force in Nevada politics for 40 years, elected
as Storey County district attorney in 1938 and then becoming state
attorney general in 1942.
   He served 20 years in the Senate before retiring in 1974.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Charlie Palmieri</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charlie Palmieri, a popular salsa pianist who as
a band leader helped create new forms of Latin jazz, died Monday,
apparently of a heart attack. He was in his early 60s.
   Born in Puerto Rico and reared in the Bronx, Palmieri played
with Latin dance orchestras and hotel bands, including those led by
Tito Puente and Mongo Santamaria. In the 1950s, he led various
groups, and in 1959, he introduced the band Charanga Duboney. In
1961, he became musical director of the Allegre All-Stars, who
merged mambos with jazz solos.
   Palmieri also played in all-star ``piano summits'' with his
brother, pianist Eddie Palmieri.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John D.J. Moore</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John D.J. Moore, who was ambassador to Ireland
during the Nixon administration and a W.R. Grace & Co. executive,
died Monday at age 77 of bone cancer.
   Vice President Richard Nixon had Moore accompany him to South
America in 1958 and to the Soviet Union in 1959. When he became
president in 1969, Nixon appointed Moore ambassador to Ireland.
Moore served six years.
   As ambassador, Moore negotiated an aviation agreement that
gained the United States landing rights for U.S. airlines in
Dublin. He also established a professorship of American studies at
the National University of Ireland.
   He was with W.R. Grace from 1946 to 1969, serving in Peru,
Washington and as a vice president in New York. In 1976, he
rejoined Grace as a member of its board until his retirement two
years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
