<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--BARTBribes     09-13 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--BART Bribes,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manager Pleads Guilty to Kickbacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bay Area Rapid Transit District manager
could face 33 years in prison and a $1 million fine after pleading
guilty to accepting kickbacks over a three-year period from
undercover FBI agents.
   Arnold Flores, 45, who entered the plea Monday on four felony
charges, also could have to return nearly $16,000 in kickbacks.
Sentencing is scheduled on Dec. 12.
   It was the first guilty plea to result from the FBI's
investigation of corruption in contracts involving the three-county
commuter train system. The three-year probe was made public last
month.
   Charges are pending against two other midlevel managers and a
private contractor. Transit system officials say they are
investigating about 20 other managers.
   The FBI says it set up five companies as fronts to do
maintenance for BART and offer kickbacks to managers in exchange
for preferential treatment on contracts.
</TEXT>
