<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0565 09-13 0846</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0565,850</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 3rd graf to show speech delivered bgng ``Americans at...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush today promised a new era
of individual ``economic empowerment'' and urged voters to reject
Democrat Michael Dukakis' vision of ``an America shackled to the
mistakes of the past.''
   The vice president criticized ``prophets of pessimism'' who he
accused of ignoring the fruits of eight years of President Reagan's
economic policies _ lower interest rates and inflation and creation
of nearly 18 million jobs since 1982.
   ``Americans at every income level are certifiably better off
than they were in 1981,'' Bush told the Executives' Club of
Chicago. ``So the next time somebody tells you that America is
declining, tell 'em to put away the 1980 calendar. This is 1988.
America is a rising nation again.''
   The GOP nominee offered a ``flexible freeze'' on government
spending without any tax increases and _ borrowing a phrase from
former Democratic presidential contender Jesse Jackson _ ``economic
empowerment'' for the individual rather than government controls.
   ``The strength of our economy comes from the people, not from
the government, from the creativity and initiative of the
individual, not from official directives, five-year plans and
so-called industrial policies,'' he said.
   ``Let's remember that today, when the prophets of pessimism are
again heard in the land. The jobs, say the pessimists, they're not
good enough. The trends, say the pessimists, they're worrisome. The
international competition, say the pessimists, it's too tough,''
Bush said.
   He accused Dukakis of espousing a big government philosophy that
will lead to a growing bureaucracy, less competitive industry ``and
an America shackled to the mistakes of the past.''
   Bush said Dukakis ``is on a magical mystery tour,'' promising to
create a fund to rebuild America with a helping hand from
Washington.
   But the vice president said this helping hand is reaching right
for the voters' wallets.
   ``What will pay for that helping hand? Your money. And who is
being helped? Not you,'' Bush said.
   ``This isn't a helping hand,'' he said. ``This is the same old
heavy hand of government.''
   Bush set the tone for today's speech during appearances SMonday
at a Hispanic-owned food plant in Secaucus, N.J., and a rally at an
Alton, Ill., shopping center.
   Touring the Goya Foods plant, Bush told 100 employees that
Hispanic workers ``have been some of the biggest winners in
America's economic comeback,'' with their jobs increasing at three
times the rate of the entire U.S. labor force.
   At the shopping center, Bush attacked the Democratic
presidential nominee for suggesting that the vice president was
emulating the late Joseph R. McCarthy, the inquisitorial
anti-communist senator who questioned the patriotism of many
Americans in the 1950s.
   At the same time, Bush suggested that he was a friend of the
people and implied that Dukakis wasn't.
   ``He suggested that when I said he's a card-carrying member of
the American Civil Liberties Union, that that was McCarthyism,''
Bush told a crowd of about 7,000 supporters.
   Dukakis actually used the term in reference to Bush's attack on
him for refusing to require teachers to lead their classes in the
Pledge of Allegiance.
   Bush referred to an Aug. 17 New York Magazine article that
quoted Dukakis saying he was a card-carrying member of the ACLU.
   ``He said that, not me,'' Bush said heatedly. ``I am for the
people. He's that. He says he's that.
   ``I am the vice president of the United States of America, a
partner in an administration that has turned this economy around,
that has put America back to work, that has strengthened our
national security and that has enhanced the peace.''
   Earlier Monday, the Bush campaign announced the resignations of
five members of his American Nationalities Coalition, an ethnic
outreach panel made up of volunteer advisers. A newspaper,
Washington Jewish Week, reported last week that a handful of the
group's 88 members had ties to anti-Semitic, Nazi or other fascist
organizations, or were blocking the prosecution of suspected Nazi
war criminals.
   Bush told reporters in Alton that the campaign conducted a
review of allegations made in the newspaper and ``we were unable to
substantiate any of them.''
   `Nonetheless,'' he said, ``these individuals have done the right
thing by removing themselves from the controversy and any further
use by political opponents.''
   He said the five had left voluntarily, and added with visible
annoyance that the campaign: ``We're getting into a very peculiar
deal where some people are accusing people. I don't like it a bit.''
   Those who resigned were Philip Guarino, Laszlo Pastor, Florian
Galdau, Ignatius Bilinsky and Bohdon Fedorak.
   The resignations follow the departure last week of coalition
member Jerome Brentar, who had been an active supprter of John
Demjanjuk, the former Ohio autoworker who was extradited and
convicted in Israel of being a Nazi war criminal.
   On Sunday, Frederic V. Malek resigned as the Bush-appointed
deputy chairman of the Republican National Committee after
acknowledging a newspaper report that while serving in the Nixon
administration, he tallied the number of Jews in a federal agency.
</TEXT>
