<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ireland-Bunker     09-13 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ireland-Bunker,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs, Grenades And Other Arms Found In Londonderry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police uncovered an arsenal
of bombs, plastic explosives, grenades and other arms in an
uninhabited house in a Roman Catholic neighborhood of Londonderry,
a spokesman said today.
   ``This was one of the most deadly arsenals of weapons and
bomb-making material ever found in the city,'' said the police
spokesman, who refused to be identified. ``We are concerned about
the possible consequences of such an arsenal of death being stored
in a densely populated area.''
   Londonderry is the province's second largest city.
   He declined to say if police know who owned the cache. No
arrests were made during the search.
   The police spokesman said the arms cache was discovered less
than a mile from the apartment where an Irish Republican Army bomb
killed two civilians on Aug. 31.
   The IRA is fighting to oust the British from Northern Ireland
and unite the province with the Irish Republic.
   Police in the Irish Republic, meanwhile, said that on Monday
night they discovered a hidden underground bunker near the border
containing 79 pounds of bomb-making materials.
   A Dublin police spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the bunker was found in a routine search of land near the town
of Dundalk, about a half mile from the border with Northern Ireland.
   He said 18 two-pound packs of nitro-benzine and fertilizer mix
were found in the bunker, which was buried under six inches of
earth and sealed by steel doors. He said it was not known who owned
the bunker.
   Such material has been used in bombs made by the IRA, the
domestic British agency Press Association said.
</TEXT>
