<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-MailStrike     09-13 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Mail Strike,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Employees Return To Work After Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postal employees began returning to work today
after nearly two weeks of strikes, but officials said it would take
as many weeks to deliver a backlog of 150 million letters and
packages.
   The strike ended Monday night after the Union of Communication
Workers reached an agreement with post office officials. The two
sides said they established a framework for further talks on
differences over pay bonuses, overtime compensation and the hiring
of temporary staff.
   The union, which represents the 140,000 post office employees
involved in the dispute, said it hoped all workers would be back at
work by Thursday.
   About 1,700 workers returned to post offices by mid-morning
today while more than 98,000 other strikers continued negotiations,
Garner said.
   She said workers are on their jobs at Tonbridge and Sevenoaks,
both southeast of London, and in other small offices around the
country.
   Public mailboxes that were sealed during the dispute will be
opened gradually, she said.
   Post office officials said international mail and first-class
letters and parcels will receive priority as the backlog of mail is
cleared over the next two weeks.
   About half of Britain's 1,500 post offices were closed during
the strike, and only one of the 82 major mail sorting centers _ in
Belfast, Northern Ireland _ remained open during the strike.
   Post Office spokeswoman Jane Garner said the agreement condones
the ``use of temporary staff, reasonable levels of overtime (pay)
... and some diversions of mail to offices which can best handle
it.''
   The post office wants to pay bonuses to new workers in London
and southeast England, where the cost of living is high and
recruiting employees is difficult.
   The union, which demanded that the bonuses be paid to all
employees or not at all, called a series of strikes that began with
a 24-hour work stoppage Aug. 31.
</TEXT>
