<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru   09-13 0855</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Offers Expanded Role for Soviet Trade In Exchange For
Reforms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 17 grafs new with Dukakis speech; picks up pvs 6th graf
bgng, He began; SUBS pvs 10th graf bgng, ``I think,'' to delete
reference to Quayle; deletes last 2 grafs to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis said today he would welcome an
expanded Soviet role in world trade if the Kremlin makes
long-awaited progress in guaranteeing human rights, ending regional
conflicts and halting weapons shipments to terrorist nations.
   The Democratic nominee, promising a hard-line approach on
U.S.-Soviet relations, also questioned whether Republican
candidates George Bush and Dan Quayle are tough enough to deal with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``George Bush has been around Washington a long time but if he
couldn't stand up to the Ayatollah or say `no' to (Panamanian
leader Gen. Manuel Antonio) Noriega, how will he measure up to
Gorbachev?'' Dukakis asked.
   ``And if he truly believes that J. Danforth Quayle is qualified
to be one heartbeat away from the presidency, how can we trust his
judgment when America's future is on the line?''
   Dukakis said Quayle paled in comparison to the three vice
presidents who have become president since World War II.
   ``Dan Quayle is no Gerald Ford,'' he said. ``He's no Lyndon
Johnson. And he sure ain't Harry Truman. Can we stake our future on
the hope that he is a match for Mikhail Gorbachev?''
   Dukakis told the Chicago Council on Foreign Relations that the
next president ``must understand the obstacles that exist to an
improved relationship with the Soviet Union, but he must not be put
off by them.''
   He added: ``We must act, not react, if we are to regain and
maintain the initiative in world affairs. Yes, it would be naive to
take Gorbachev at his word, but it would be dangerous to allow his
words to go unanswered and untested in the court of public opinion
around the world.''
   Dukakis said Soviet actions have fallen short of Gorbachev's
words in reforming Soviet society.
   He called on Gorbachev to reduce the Soviet advantage in
conventional forces in Europe and promised a Democratic
administration's cooperation in negotiating further cutbacks in
nuclear weapons.
   Dukakis urged the Soviets not only to help end conflicts in the
Middle East and Nicaragua but to support trade unions and
alternative political parties in Eastern bloc nations.
   ``We must constantly remind the Soviets of the regional conflict
they created in Eastern Europe, a conflict that has resulted in
totalitarian rule over six proud nations for more than 40 years,''
he said.
   While Gorbachev has publicly promised to help curb terrorism,
the Massachusetts governor assailed the Soviets for supplying
military and economic aid to Syria, Libya and the Palestinian
Liberation Organization, and providing nuclear missiles to other
countries.
   ``As president, I will work with our allies to persuade Mr.
Gorbachev that if he wants to join the international economic
community he must first get out of the business of exporting these
weapons to volatile regions of the world,'' Dukakis said.
   He also accused Gorbachev of failing to deliver on his promise
to improve human rights in the Soviet Union. ``It is not enough to
pretend that rights exist when they do not exist,'' Dukakis said.
   ``We, in America, should stand ready to respond to progress with
progress,'' Dukakis said. ``But we must be ready to meet
stubborness with determination, deception with the truth and
aggression with the full power of a strong and united democratic
alliance.''
   It was Dukakis' first major policy speech on Soviet-American
affairs, and was part of a three-day campaign effort to counter
Bush's charges that Dukakis was weak on defense and naive on
foreign policy.
   He began the counteroffensive Monday with an overview of his
views on national security in Philadelphia and later by touring a
General Electric plant outside Cincinnati. He reiterated his
support for the Stealth bomber, whose engines are made at the
plant, but nonetheless was periodically interrupted by booing Bush
supporters.
   ``It was a good audience,'' Dukakis said after the Cincinnati
event, during which he did not acknowledge his detractors. ``It was
fun. That's democracy.''
   From Chicago, Dukakis was heading to Michigan to visit a plant
where the M-1 tank was designed. The Democratic nominee supports
the tank program.
   Dukakis attacked Bush's judgment in light of the resignation of
five Bush campaign officials amid published reports of their past
ties with pro-Nazi and anti-Semitic organizations.
   ``I think it raises continuing questions about Mr. Bush's
judgment,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis, whose own polls show uneasiness among critical swing
voters with Bush's selection of Quayle, also criticized the
Republican senator in his Philadelphia speech. He called Bush a
failed leader in the war on drugs and derided Bush's promise to
appoint Quayle as his point man in the drug fight.
   ``We're going to put someone who is tough and aggressive and
experienced in charge of the war against drugs,'' Dukakis said
after praising his running mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen. Dukakis
spoke at a gathering of about 250 people in a Philadelphia union
hall.
</TEXT>
