<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru a0552 09-13 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0552,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Rejects Government-Run Elections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with hunger strike and details
of meeting between opposition and election commission. PICKS up 9th
graf, `Gen. Saw ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders today rejected
elections that would be organized by the country's one-party
government and repeated their call for an interim government to
supervise the vote.
   About 75 students and others, including two Buddhist monks, went
on a 48-hour fast for democracy, reviving a tactic used decades ago
in the struggle for greater freedom from British colonial rule.
   Tens of thousands of people marched in the capital demanding the
interim government. They included striking government employees,
uniformed students and about 3,000 uniformed doctors, nurses and
staff members of militry and other hospitals.
   The demonstrations were smaller than those the day before.
   After weeks of political turmoil, many people in this city of
3.5 million have begun eating rice porridge or gruel instead of
pure rice because prices have skyrocketed due to growing shortages.
   Strikes by transportation workers and a lack of fuel have
restricted supplies from the countryside, and there has been
hoarding by worried residents. A 4.4-pound bag of rice that cost
the equivalent of $1.70 a month ago now costs $5.80.
   Gasoline was selling at $16 a gallon on the black market,
compared to $1 a year ago, a Western diplomat said.
   Opposition leaders Aung Gyi, Aung San Suu Kyi and former Defense
Minister Tin Oo said in their meeting with the government-appointed
election commission that they will not support or take part in the
elections and will continue pressing for an interim government.
   The Burma Socialist Program Party, which came to power in a 1962
military coup, announced Saturday it will end 26 years of one-party
rule and hold elections as early as the end of October.
   They told the commission that polling could not be conducted in
the country's rapidly deteriorating security situation, Aung Gyi
said later.
   Aung Gyi said he told election commission chairman Ba Htay, a
retired financial commissioner under a pre-1962 civilian government:
   ``After 26 years of this rule, most people in the country do not
know you and will not have confidence. More so, people do not trust
any government-appointed commission.''
   Like the other four elderly commission members, Ba Htay is
regarded as politically neutral.
   The three opposition leaders were later joined by a fourth
anti-government figure, former Prime Minister Nu, in a meeting with
student rebel leaders. The students asked them to immediately form
an interim government, but were told that was not possible without
cooperation from the current government.
   On Monday, Aung Gyi, Aung San Suu Kyi, and Tin Oo signed their
first joint statement, a letter to President Maung Maung demanding
the interim government. Photographs of them eating together and
signing the statement received prominent display in private and
government-run newspapers Tuesday, buoying the opposition movement.
   This morning, the group of hunger strikers sat on the road in
front of City Hall, where several anti-government demonstrators
were shot dead by security forces Aug. 8. They began fasting at 9
a.m., looked after by doctors and other sympathizers.
   Gen. Saw Maung, defense minister and armed forces chief of
staff, called for citizens and the military to cooperate in holding
the proposed government-organized general elections.
   The last multi-party elections in Burma were held Feb. 6, 1960,
when former Prime Minister Nu's Clean Anti-Fascist People's Freedom
League won a landslide victory over an army-backed party.
   Gen. Ne Win led the March 1962 coup that toppled Nu, who uses
only one name. The military crushed dissent and pursued rigid
policies that made Burma, once one of Asia's richest countries, one
of the world's poorest nations.
   In September 1987, students stages riots against the
government's economic policies, followed by widespread protests in
March and in June. After Ne Win resigned July 23, the party chose
hardliner Sein Lwin to succeed him. After only 17 days in office,
Sein Lwin was succeded on Aug. 19 by Maung Maung, the first
civilian leader since Nu.
</TEXT>
