<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Botha     09-13 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Botha,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha's Visit to Malawi Completes First Summit Trip To Black
Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha announced
today that South Africa will donate 3,000 tons of corn to feed
refugees in Malawi, as he completed his first summit trip into
black Africa in his 10 years in power.
   Botha's announcement followed private talks in Mzuzu, Malawi,
with the country's long-serving president, Hastings Kamuzu Banda.
Malawi is the only African state maintaining full diplomatic ties
with South Africa, where whites dominate the government.
   On Monday, Botha had a 90-minute private talk in northwestern
Mozambique with President Joaquim Chissano, whose Marxist
government has accused South Africa of supporting an 11-year-old
rebel insurgency.
   Botha gave assurances to Mozambique that this support had ceased
and invited Chissano to South Africa to continue talks on increased
cooperation.
   The refugees who are to receive the gift of corn in Malawi are
residents of Mozambique who have fled the fighting there.
   In Mzuzu, Botha and Banda issued a joint statement reaffirming
the friendly relations between South Africa and Malawi. Both also
said South Africa would negotiate a rescheduling of Malawi's debt
``on terms agreeable to both parties.''
   Banda, believed to be almost 90, has ruled Malawi in
authoritarian style since independence from Britain in 1964.
Opposition political parties are banned, and Banda maintains
personal control over most government ministries.
   In Mozambique, Botha and Chissano agreed to work at reviving the
1984 Nkomati Accord, in which South Africa pledged to withdraw
support from guerrillas in return for controls on African National
Congress exiles based in Mozambique.
   Mozambique repeatedly has accused South Africa of breaking the
agreement.
   Chissano spoke of mutual hopes to end regional conflicts and
said, ``We are ready to take this process as far as possible.''
   Mozambique in the past has accused Malawi of allowing the
Mozambican rebels to operate from its territory. Relations between
the two countries have improved since Malawi agreed last year to
deploy troops in Mozambique to help protect a railroad line against
sabotage.
</TEXT>
