<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0533,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PTL Tries in Court to Get Money from Bakkers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5-7th grafs pvs, bgng `Baker lawyer...', with 4 grafs to
UPDATE with testimony today, note that Bakkers again not in court
today. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Meanwhile, bankruptcy...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By G.G. RIGSBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim and Tammy Bakker and a former aide
took money out of PTL and were indifferent to the ministry's
financial woes, a PTL attorney says.
   In a U.S. Bankruptcy Court hearing expected to last all week,
PTL representatives are trying to regain $52 million they contend
the Bakkers and former aide David Taggart took through
mismanagement of funds, cash advances on PTL credit cards and
unjustified compensation, benefits and fees.
   As the trial began Monday, PTL attorney Brad Leggett said the
Bakkers and Taggart were uninterested in money problems ``while
taking money out at times faster than it was coming in.''
   Peter Bailey, an accountant and financial director at PTL from
June 1979 through July 1987, testified he routinely warned Bakker
of financial troubles.
   Bailey testified today that he was continually frustrated by a
``lack of financial integrity'' on the part of Bakker and other
ministry executives. Memos regarding cost reductions and a limit of
expenditures were either ignored or inadequately addressed, he
charged.
   Bakker lawyer Ryan Hovis told Judge Rufus Reynolds, who is
hearing the case without a jury, that the continuing financial
crisis PTL experienced under Bakker's leadership was not unusual.
   ``Every ministry of this type in the nation had the same type of
financial crisis,'' he said.
   The Bakkers and Taggart were not in court Monday or today, but
Hovis told reporters he plans to call them as witnesses when it is
time to present their case.
   Meanwhile, bankruptcy trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton filed papers
in court saying he couldn't meet Monday's deadline to recommend a
buyer for the ministry's assets. He asked for an extension until
Sept. 27 to continue negotiations.
   In court Monday, PTL lawyers maintained that the Bakkers took
huge personal bonuses while bills weren't being paid, and used
money that was raised to build hotels as general operating funds.
   Entered into court records were numerous memos from Bailey to
Bakker recommending such things as cutting expenses, reducing
payroll and using competitive bidding for construction jobs.
   Bailey said some staff members were hesitant to approach Bakker
with information about financial problems. ``He (Bakker) was out
there planning and building, and he had a saying _ he didn't want
to hear any bad news,'' Bailey said.
   PTL lawyers used internal documents to detail the ministry's
problems from 1984-1987. They cited bonuses given to the Bakkers
and Taggart at the same time the ministry was having serious
financial problems.
</TEXT>
