<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TeenStress 2ndLd-Writethru   09-13 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teen Stress, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0480,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third of American Adults Know Teen-Ager Who Attempted Suicide</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New figures and quotes in top 6 grafs, pickup 5th graf prv,
``Entitled xxx; adds 3 grafs new material at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third of American adults questioned in a
recent survey said they personally know a teen-ager who either
committed suicide or tried to, according to a report released today.
   A separate study of high-achieving teen-agers, meanwhile,
disclosed that 30 percent said they have considered suicide and 45
percent know someone who has tried it, or succeeded.
   The national survey of 1,000 adults, questioned by the National
Association of Private Psychiatric Hospitals, found that 27 percent
of those questioned said they knew a teen-ager who had tried to
kill themselves and 17 percent knew a teen-ager who had killed
themselves.
   Charles Riter of Riter Research, the Annapolis, Md. company that
conducted the survey, said there was overlapping and that a net of
32 percent of those questioned knew a teen-ager in one of the two
categories.
   John E. Meeks, a child psychiatrist and a professor at George
Washington University School of Medicine in Washington, said the
study was ``reassuring'' in the sense it showed adults realize that
modern teen-agers face severe problems.
   ``Teen-agers frequently worry that adults don't take their
problems seriously,'' Meeks said at a news conference.
   Entitled ``Teen-agers at Risk: an Adult Perspective,'' the
survey also found that 72.4 percent of those interviewed think
teen-agers today face far more serious problems than they did at
the same age.
   The survey commissioned by the Washington-based organization
also found that adults focused on three major areas of concern when
asked about 10 specific problems facing adolescents: drug abuse,
alcohol abuse and peer pressure.
   Slightly more than 87 percent said drug abuse was an
``overwhelming'' concern, alcohol abuse was second and peer
pressure third.
   Unwanted pregnancy ranked fourth with 70.8 percent.
   A cluster appeared around the next five areas: Child abuse, 56
percent; crime among teen-agers, 54 percent; depression 53 percent;
conflict with parents 53 percent; and suicide 53 percent.
   The 10th greatest concern was runaway behavior at 44.5 percent.
   Notwithstanding the concern expressed for America's youth, 47
percent of those questioned agreed that when a teen-ager is
admitted to a psychiatric hospital ``it puts a cloud over this
person's head for the rest of his@her life.''
   And 86.3 percent agreed to some degree that ``families find it
difficult to admit that their children need professional
psychiatric help.''
   Of those questioned, 17.1 percent had teen-age children and 31.5
percent had children under 12. Grandparents represented 30.7
percent of the sample.
   The survey of high-achieving teen-agers was conducted by polling
youths listed in the directory ``Who's Who Among American High
School Students.''
   Four percent of the 2,024 respondents said they had actually
attempted suicide.
   It was the fourth year for that study. During that period the
share who said they knew someone who has tried suicide rose from 40
percent to 45 percent; those considering it were up from 28 percent
to 30 percent, and those who tried edged up from 3 percent to 4
percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
