<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Stowaway     09-13 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stowaway,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stowaway's Parents Say She Was Sexually Abused on U.S. Navy Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irish teen-ager who stowed away on a U.S.
Navy destroyer was sexually abused and supplied with drugs while
detained against her will on the ship for 10 days, an attorney for
the girl's parents said.
   John and Christine Twomey, parents of Suzanne Twomey, wrote
Margaret Heckler, U.S. ambassador to Ireland, that they plan legal
action against the United States for alleged conduct that ``may
have amounted to kidnapping.''
   Navy spokesmen Lt. Cmdr. John Lloyd said Monday, ``We don't have
anything to substantiate a charge of kidnapping.'' But he declined
to comment on the drug or sex abuse allegations.
   Miss Twomey, 17, was found aboard the destroyer Conyngham on
July 22, a day before it reached its home port, Norfolk. The girl
apparently had slipped aboard on July 12 while the ship was in
Cork, Ireland, and was concealed by several crewmen, officials said.
   Four Conyngham sailors face October courts-martial on charges of
aiding and harboring an alien. Four others face an administrative
hearing on less serious charges.
   Raymond O'Neill, an attorney in Cork for the Twomeys, wrote Ms.
Heckler that the teen-ager's stay aboard the Conyngham was
``unlawful, against her will, involuntary and might have amounted
to kidnapping.''
   ``It appears that during the course of her unlawful detention
Ms. Twomey was, on a number of occasions, supplied with narcotics
and, in addition, was repeatedly sexually abused,'' O'Neill said.
   The Virginian-Pilot and The Ledger-Star of Norfolk quoted an
unidentified Navy official as saying that Miss Twomey apparently
intended to ride on the ship, because she boarded it herself with a
bag containing clothes, books and a radio or cassette player.
   Irish officials have said that Miss Twomey has run away from
home several times, once to Spain. She is now under the care of
Irish health officials, who said they applied for custody ``in the
interests of the girl herself and after consultation with her
parents and the police.''
</TEXT>
