<HEAD>Gunman Surrenders After Keeping Police At Bay For 10 Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALUMET CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police launched stun grenades into a
home, then stormed it early today to end a 10-hour stand-off with a
gunman who had sprayed the neighborhood with hundreds of rounds of
ammunition.
   Police said Walter Kumpel, 56, was not holding hostages but he
refused to surrender, despite numerous pleas from police who took
cover to escape the barrage of fire. No one was injured, but dozens
of nearby residents were evacuated.
   Officers found Kumpel barricaded in a back bedroom clutching two
handguns. The man did not fire on the officers, police said.
   Authorities said Kumpel and his wife had been having marital
problems in recent weeks. ``He was acting erratic. ... He was
threatening to kill himself and his family,'' said Police Chief
Steven Rhoads.
   The ordeal in this south suburb of Chicago started about 4:10
p.m. when neighbors called to say the man was threatening to kill
himself and others, police said. Officers were able to get the
man's wife and daughter away from the home before the man started
firing, police said.
   Authorities said they waited for 10 hours before entering the
home because they feared the house was booby trapped, a fear they
later said was unfounded.
