<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Rape,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins in Gang Rape Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ruled that only limited
discussion will be allowed in the jury's presence about the sexual
history of a 19-year-old woman whose complaint of a gang rape led
to the indictment of 10 men on charges ranging from kidnapping to
sexual assault.
   After lengthy pre-trial motions by defense attorneys, jury
selection finally began late Monday and continued today in the
sexual assault trial of Orlando Garza, 23, the first of several
scheduled as a result of the woman's allegations.
   State District Judge Ricardo Garcia granted a prosecution motion
to block references to the woman's sexual history in the presence
of the jury without first determining whether such discussion would
be admissible evidence.
   Defense attorney Albert Pena protested that prior sexual
behavior ``touches on the very basis of the defense of consent.''
   Pena told the jury pool they would have to ignore the extensive
media coverage the case has attracted since the 19-year-old woman
said she was abducted and gang raped March 26.
   The woman told authorities she was abducted while walking home
from a relative's house and raped over four hours by as many as 20
men. She said the attack began at a ranch north of town where a
cockfight was being held, and that her attackers urged men at the
cockfight to join in. Some did, despite her pleas of help, she said.
   Ten men were indicted on various kidnapping or sexual assault
charges. A 14-year-old youth also has been charged.
   Garza, of San Diego, also faces a later trial on a charge of
aggravated kidnapping.
   The judge denied motions by the defense to replace the jury
panel. The defense had tried to show that an inordinate number of
the potential jurors were relatives of one of the prosecutors and
residents of areas the county where the prosecutor's family has a
``historical political stronghold.''
</TEXT>
