<2ND_LINE>PM-Matta Trial,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Honduras Drug Lord on Trial for Escape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The escape trial of a reputed drug lord
whose recapture touched off riots in Honduras was headed into its
final stages after just one hour of testimony.
   With extra security guards posted outside U.S. District Court,
closing arguments were scheduled today in the trial of Juan Ramon
Matta, 43, who faces charges of escaping from the Federal Prison
Camp at Eglin Air Force Base in 1971. His trial opened Monday.
   Matta was serving a three-year sentence at the air base in the
Florida Panhandle for illegally entering the United States. He
allegedly slipped out the back door of a chapel at the
minimum-security prison during church services.
   Evidence was covered in only an hour of testimony after a
12-member jury was selected Monday. Defense lawyer Martin Stolar
produced evidence that shortly before he left the prison, Matta had
been told his mother was ill.
   Stolar had also challenged the escape charge on grounds Matta
was illegally seized, but his argument was rejected by U.S.
District Judge Roger Vinson.
   Honduran police captured Matta on April 5, using helicopters to
raid his home. Police then put him on a flight to the Dominican
Republic, which in turn put him on a flight for New York City,
where U.S. marshals arrested him.
   His return to the United States touched off rioting in
Tegucigalpa, Honduras, by students, leftists and others who
contended the extradition was barred by the Honduran constitution.
Several protesters were killed and the U.S. Consulate was burned.
   At the time of his arrest in April, Matta had been living openly
in Tegucigalpa, Honduras, since 1986 when he escaped from a
Colombian prison, where he had been held on charges involving the
Medellin drug cartel.
   Authorities said Matta also was wanted for questioning in the
1985 slaying of U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration Agent Enrique
Salazar in Mexico.
</TEXT>
