<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Cuba, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0486,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Ambassador, Another Diplomat Expelled Following Shooting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with ambassador leaving, PICKS
up 15th graf, `Press Association ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain expelled the Cuban ambassador and another
envoy today after the junior diplomat wounded one man when he fired
a gun at people he believed were following him.
   With a wry smile and a wave, Ambassador Oscar Fernandez-Mell was
driven from his official residence in north London to catch a
flight to Prague, Czechoslovakia, within the 24-hour expulsion
deadline set by British officials.
   The ambassador, accompanied by his wife and 12-year-old son,
picked up another diplomat, believed to be the gunman, Third
Secretary Carlos Manuel Medina Perez, at the embassy en route to
Heathrow Airport.
   Police said anti-terrorist squad detectives had traced one man
who was slightly injured in the Monday afternoon shooting and added
they were satisfied he ``was not posing a threat to anyone.''
   In a statement, Scotland Yard police headquarters said it would
not release the identify of the injured man, adding the police
inquiry into the shooting was closed.
   Speculation grew about the group that Medina Perez, described as
a commercial attache in the diplomatic list, claimed was stalking
him.
   The British radio reports quoted the Cuban Foreign Ministry as
saying on Havana radio that the expulsion was ``arbitrary and
unjust'' and that Medina Perez was being followed by a Cuban exile
who had tried to get the diplomat to defect.
   The Daily Mail said he believed he was being trailed by an
assassination squad. The Daily Express the group were members of
Britain's MI5 counter-intelligence agency, ``who watch Cuban
diplomats round the clock.''
   It added that Medina Perez said he opened fire in panic because
he thought the group were agents of the government of South Africa,
which supports pro-Western guerrillas who oppose the Cuban-backed
Marxist government of Angola.
   The government acknowledged a shooting incident on Monday but
provided few details.
   In London, a Cuban Embassy spokesman in a radio interview said
the British retaliation was ``excessive,''
   The Foreign Office in a statement retorted, ``We have reacted
appropriately to a totally unacceptable and outrageous action on
the streets of London.''
   The Foreign Office said Medina Perez told police he fired
because he was afraid for his safety. The Foreign Office said he
was released from police custody after he claimed diplomatic
immunity.
   Foreign Office Minister Timothy Eggar summoned Fernandez-Mell to
the Foreign Office after the shooting and told the ambassador that
he and Medina Perez, who also held the embassy post of commercial
attache, were being expelled.
   In a later statement, Eggar called the expulsions ``an
indication of how strongly we feel ... We are not prepared to have
this kind of behavior in the streets of London.''
   The Daily Mail reported said Medina Perez barricaded himself in
the official Cuban apartment after the incident. It said two police
officers negotiated with Medina Perez from an adjacent balcony.
   Press Association said Medina Perez fired up to five shots at a
car with four people inside. It quoted an unidentified witness as
saying she saw the four run away, one holding a blood-soaked
handkerchief to his head.
   British authorities refused comment on the news reports.
   In a nation where ordinary police do not carry guns, weapons
possession by diplomats is a grave issue. It became particularly
sensitive after a gunman fired from the Libyan Embassy during a
protest demonstration in April 1984, killing a British policewoman.
After a police siege, the embassy was shut and diplomatic ties cut.
   On Sunday, Vietnamese Third Secretary Khang Than Nhan left
London, expelled by Britain after the Vietnamese ambassador turned
in a gun he said Khang waved Sept. 4 during a demonstration by
British-based Vietnamese refugees.
   The Vietnamese ambassador first handed over a toy gun but later
returned with a real one and apologized, the Foreign Office said.
</TEXT>
