<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush-Jews 3rdLd-Writethru a0564 09-13 0868</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Jews, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0564,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sixth Member of Bush's Ethnic Coalition Resigns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with sixth resignation, Reagan comments;
picks up pvs 2nd graf bgng, ``We are resigning; SUBS pvs 14th graf
bgng, The resignations, to make 2nd reference to Malek.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sixth member of an ethnic coalition
supporting Republican George Bush's presidential candidacy resigned
today as President Reagan declared that ``there isn't one iota of
discrimination'' among the group's members.
   Bush campaign spokesman Mark Goodin said the resignation of Radi
Slavoff as national co-chairman of Bulgarians for Bush was accepted
today.
   Slavoff quit the campaign after the Philadelphia Inquirer
identified him over the weekend as former head of the Bulgarian
National Front, which the paper said was formed after World War II
by members of the Nazi-aligned Bulgarian Legion.
   Reagan told reporters at the White House he believed five other
ethnic advisers resigned Monday ``because they didn't want to harm
the campaign.''
   The president was not asked specifically about the resignation
of Frederic V. Malek, a key Bush operative and deputy chairman of
the Republican National Committee who was named in a published
report about possibly anti-Semitic activities during the Nixon
administration.
   Asked whether he thought the Bush campaign suffered from an
appearance of anti-Semitism among some of the vice president's
supporters, Reagan replied, ``No.''
   Asked to elaborate, he said, ``Because I know him (Bush) and I
know the people involved and there isn't an iota of discrimination
in any of them.''
   Reagan commented after a Rose Garden ceremony where he signed
fair housing legislation.
   Bush and the five former officials of the ethnic coalition said
the controversy was politically motivated.
   ``We are resigning today from the `Coalition of American
Nationalities' and removing ourselves from the controversy because
we have been attacked unfairly by George Bush's political
opponents,'' the five said in a statement Monday issued by Bush
spokesman Mark Goodin. The statement did not name the opponents.
   In announcing the resignations, Goodin said the Bush campaign
conducted a review of the allegations and found nothing to
substantiate the reports.
   ``The charges appear to be politically inspired by individuals
who wish to divert public attention from the issues of the
campaign,'' Goodin said. ``Nonetheless, we believe these
individuals have done the right thing by removing themselves from
the controversy.''
   Asked about the resignations during a campaign stop in Illinois,
Bush told reporters, ``Nobody's giving in. These people left of
their own volition. We're not accusing anybody of anything.''
   The vice president added, ``We're getting into a very peculiar
deal where some people are accusing people. I don't like it a bit.''
   The controversy arose after publication last week of an article
in Washington Jewish Week, which said the Bush campaign committee
included Florian Galdau, described as the New York chief of the
Iron Guard, Romania's anti-Semitic, pro-Nazi movement, and Philip
Guarino, a Roman Catholic priest listed as member of an illegal,
neo-fascist Italian group.
   Galdau, honorary chairman of the committee, and Guarino, the
coalition's vice chairman, were among the five who resigned. Laszlo
Pasztor, described in the article as a Hungarian-American who
served in Hungary's pro-Nazi, anti-Semitic Arrowcross as a youth,
also resigned.
   The other two committee members to step down were Ignatius
Bilinsky and Bohdan Fedorak. Their alleged activities were not
immediately known.
   In the statement, the former coalition members said, ``these
Sasso-like attacks are aimed at neutralizing the strong support
which George Bush has and will continue to have in the ethnic
community.''
   John Sasso, a top aide to Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis,
was forced to resign last year after he circulated the so-called
``attack video'' against former Democratic candidate Sen. Joe Biden
of Delaware. Sasso rejoined the Dukakis campaign during the Labor
Day weekend.
   On Monday, Dukakis attacked Bush's judgment after the additional
resignations.
   ``I think it raises continuing questions about Mr. Bush's
judgment,'' Dukakis said, also raising as an issue Bush's selection
of Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle as his running mate.
   The resignations came one day after Malek, a Bush appointee to
the Republican National Committee, stepped down after a published
report said that while Malek served in the Nixon administration he
compiled a list of Jewish employees in top posts at the Bureau of
Labor Statistics.
   John D. Ehrlichman, a former White House aide to President
Nixon, said Malek's resignation was politically ``exactly the right
thing to do,'' but that Malek was the victim of a ``bum rap''
because he was only following Nixon's orders.
   Ehrlichman, interviewed on CBS-TV's ``This Morning'' show, said
Nixon's order to determine whether a ``Jewish cabal'' existed at
the Labor Department agency was ``pure Nixon venting spleen'' and
``rhetorical excess'' that his aides usually ignored.
   He said Malek was ``the farthest thing from a bigot of anybody I
know.''
   The decision by the five committee members also comes less than
a week after the coalition's co-chairman Jerome Brentar was
dismissed following the disclosure that he had defended John
Demjanjuk, the one-time Cleveland autoworker convicted in Israel as
a Nazi war criminal. He was also reported to be active in groups
that questioned whether the Holocaust had actually occurred.
   No replacements for the five committee members have been named,
Goodin said.
</TEXT>
