<HEAD>Men Honored By National Women's Political Caucus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton and former Labor
Secretary Bill Brock were among 10 prominent men honored Tuesday as
``Good Guys'' by the bipartisan National Women's Political Caucus.
   Clinton was chosen ``for his leadership in the national campaign
for safe, quality child care,'' the caucus said.
   The Arkansas Democrat, perhaps better known for the
extraordinarily long speech he delivered at the Democratic National
Convention in July, has been heavily involved in congressional
efforts to expand child care services and help welfare mothers.
   Representing the National Governors Association, Clinton has
testified numerous times on behalf of welfare reform bills and a
$2.5 billion initiative designed to improve and expand child care.
   Brock, who left the administration this year to head Sen. Bob
Dole's unsuccessful presidential bid, was cited ``for his
behind-the-scenes support in the battle to maintain afirmative
action programs.''
   The caucus scheduled a Good Guy Awards Dinner on Tuesday night
in honor of Clinton, Brock and eight other ``men who have made
special contributions to women's progress.'' They are:
   _Television producer Gary David Goldberg, creator of ``Family
Ties'' and ``Day to Day,'' for his pivotal role in guaranteeing
on-site child care at Paramount Studies and his support for
parental leave.
   _Rep. Bill Green, R-N.Y., for advocating women's rights and
``his role as a steadfast standard-bearer for Republican
feminists.''
   _Cartoonist Greg Howard, for the comic strip ``Sally Forth,''
``his sensitive yet humorous depiction of the conflicts and
victories of working women.''
   _Novelist John Irving, author of ``The Cider House Rules,'' for
``his searing tale of women who risked their lives when abortions
were illegal ... and his passionate activism for abortion rights.''
   _Retiring Rep. Peter Rodino, D-N.J., for 40 years as ``a premier
statesman'' and leader in the fights for civil rights and the Equal
Rights Amendment.
   _Hicks B. Waldron, Avon chairman and chief executive officer,
for his role in guaranteeing Avon's commitment to training and
advancement of women and minorities for senior management-level
positions.
   _William Wynn, international president of the United Food and
Commercial Workers Union, for leadership in attaining workplace
benefits for women.
   _Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young, for actively recruiting and
supporting women as senior participants in city government.
