<HEAD>Two Children Die In Fire Caused By Drug-Related Firebombing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs UPDATE with police saying one man
arrested, second expected to surrender. Picks up 3rd graf pvs,
`Sgt. Joe...'. Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A firebombing apparently stemming from a $275
drug deal that went sour killed two young sisters who had been left
alone in a locked room and critically injured a third, police said.
   The Sunday evening firebombing had been meant for another man in
the building, authorities said.
   Police announced today that they have arrested one man and were
expecting the surrender of a second later in the day. Lt. George
Hollocher said investigators were seeking warrants charging both
with two counts of first-degree murder, arson and assault.
   Their identities were not released pending formal filing of
charges. Four men who had been with the suspects were being sought
for questioning.
   Sgt. Joe Marcinkiewicz of the bomb and arson squad said
investigators had determined that two Molotov cocktails were thrown
through a first-floor window of the three-story home.
   Firefighters rescued the children, who authorities said had been
left unattended in a locked bedroom. But Erica Butler, 1, and
Ashley Evans, 4, died later of smoke inhalation at Children's
Hospital. Lenora Butler, 5 months, was in critical condition this
morning, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   The children's mother, Cassandra Evans, 18, was not at home at
the time of the firebombing because she and her boyfriend were out
looking for her 16-year-old brother, who was allegedly involved in
the drug deal, Marcinkiewicz said.
   Marcinkiewicz said that shortly after 11 p.m. Sunday, six men
stopped at the home and one of them paid $275 for drugs to the
brother and another 16-year-olds. Instead of giving the man drugs,
the two youths fled with the money, the investigator said.
   He said the car returned about 20 minutes later, and the
firebombs were hurled into the house.
   Several family members said Ms. Evans routinely locked her
children in the bedroom to protect valuables she kept there. Other
adults and children escaped without injury. A total of 15 people
lived in the house, authorities said.
