<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bathhouse     09-13 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bathhouse,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Supreme Court Upholds LA Closure Of Gay Bathhouse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: note content 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California Supreme Court has refused to
hear the appeal of a gay bathhouse that was shut down by a court
order under a new Los Angeles County enforcement policy aimed at
combatting the spread of AIDS.
   The court's action Monday left intact the first such order under
the county's policy, which requires any bathhouse in which anal or
oral sex takes place to be closed as a public nuisance. A previous
policy prohibited anal sex without condoms in bathhouses but did
not seek to close the establishments.
   ``We were attempting to work with bathhouses, have them serve as
education centers,'' said Deputy County Counsel Steven Carnevale.
``We thought they would go away by themselves because they were
losing business. It turned out that they were much larger than
anybody expected.''
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is spread largely through
sexual contact and sharing of infected needles by drug abusers.
   In May, Los Angeles County officials sought to close Mac's
bathhouse after an undercover investigation found numerous
violations. An injunction was issued Aug. 30.
   After a state appeals court refused to intervene, lawyers for
Mac's appealed last week to the state Supreme Court.
   Attorney Barrett Litt argued that the order closing Mac's was
excessive because an order forbidding specific sexual practices
would accomplish the same goal while protecting the privacy rights
of the bathhouse's customers.
   Quoting a number of health experts, Litt said closing gay
bathhouses would not reduce the risk of AIDS and would likely
increase it. Sexual activities at bathhouses were ``safer than in
the general population,'' he said.
   After the violations were found, Mac's required every patron to
sign a copy of the rules, distributed cards stating the risk of
specific types of sexual activities, and started showing ``safe
sex'' videos, Litt said.
   The county still has about 10 bathhouses, which are generally
making good-faith efforts to follow the rules prohibiting sexual
intercourse, Carnevale said. San Francisco closed down its gay
bathhouses.
</TEXT>
