<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WilliamsFiles     09-13 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Williams Files,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Ordered To Return Documents From Wayne Williams Files To FBI</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of documents relating to the slayings
of 29 black children in Atlanta must be returned to the FBI, a
judge has ruled.
   U.S. District Judge Richard C. Freeman instructed city officials
to return files containing 2,300 documents related to the
investigation of the killings in 1979-81.
   The files were released to the public in 1987 along with Atlanta
police files on the case. The federal government then sued Atlanta
Public Safety Commissioner George Napper, charging that he violated
federal law when he released FBI documents along with the police
files.
   Freeman's order, filed Aug. 31, said the issue was whether the
city had acted properly in releasing information the FBI had shared
only on the condition it remain confidential.
   ``The court here is not concerned with whether the investigatory
documents should be released to the public,'' Freeman's order said.
``The question before the court is who owns, and is entitled to
possession of, the documents.''
   Napper had released the police files in response to an order by
Fulton County Superior Court Judge Luther Alverson, who ruled in a
lawsuit filed by several news media organizations.
   Wayne Williams, an Atlanta free-lance photographer, was
convicted in 1982 of two of the 29 murders and was sentenced to
life imprisonment. Police officials later attributed 22 other
slayings to Williams; five cases remain open.
   Williams is appealing his conviction.
</TEXT>
