<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Panama-Duty     09-13 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Duty,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Cuts Length of Panama Duty Tours</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department has ordered a cut in
the required tour length for all military personnel stationed in
Panama as part of an effort to reduce the number of dependents in
the troubled Central American nation, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
   Dan Howard, the department's chief spokesman, said the policy
change would reduce from 36 months to 30 months the required tour
for servicemen accompanied by their families and drop from 24
months to 15 months the tour for those deploying alone.
   The latter reduction is considered the most important. Howard
explained the department also is enforcing a change to its
``concurrent travel'' policy, under which servicemen cannot bring
their families to Panama unless they have already secured housing
on a military reservation.
   Since there is currently a waiting period of up to nine months
for such housing, ``the new tour length should encourage more
soldiers just to go unaccompanied,'' added Maj. Kathy Wood, a
Pentagon spokeswoman.
   Panama is the home of the U.S. Southern Command, the
organization responsible for all U.S. military forces in Central
and South America. About 10,000 American servicemen are stationed
permanently in Panama, and about 2,200 others have been assigned
there on a temporary basis since the spring to upgrade security at
U.S. bases.
   According to Wood, the decision to reduce the tour lengths was
made initially last week by the Army, gaining the approval of Gen.
Carl E. Vuono, the chief of staff, and Army Secretary John O.
Marsh. The Defense Department then reviewed the matter and ordered
similar changes for the Air Force and Navy, which have much smaller
contingents in Panama.
   Over the past six months, the Pentagon has succeeded in reducing
by 50 percent the number of military families living outside U.S.
bases in Panama _ dropping the total still off base to about 1,100.
The effort has taken on more momentum this summer because of what
the United States describes as a deliberate campaign of harassing
Americans assigned to Panama.
   U.S. officials in Panama City said on Aug. 21 that American
personnel had reported at least 240 incidents of harassment by
Panamanian authorities this year, including attempts to extort
bribes for traffic violations and the stoppage of mail.
   The harassment comes at a time when the United States is
continuing to press economic sanctions against Panama in a bid to
oust the country's military leader, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
who has been indicted by two federal grand juries in Florida on
drug-trafficking charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1341EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Quayle 2ndLd-Writethru a0592 09-13 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0592,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says Dukakis Loses His Naval Adviser: `His Rubber Duck'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new graf after pvs 5th graf bgng, ``The governor,''
with Dukakis press secretary's response.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle
ridiculed Michael Dukakis' national security credentials today and
joked that the Democratic nominee ``lost his top naval adviser last
week _ his rubber duck drowned in his bathtub.''
   Quayle accused Dukakis of lacking knowledge of defense and
foreign policy matters even as the Democratic candidate delivered a
major policy speech in Chicago on Soviet-American relations.
   ``It's sad for America to have somebody that doesn't have the
understanding or qualifications in national security to be the
Democratic nominee for president,'' Quayle told an audience at
Bush-Quayle campaign headquarters for Wisconsin.
   He said he had ``a sad story'' to tell about the Dukakis
campaign.
   ``The governor of Massachusetts, he lost his top naval adviser
last week,'' Quayle said. ``His rubber duck drowned in his
bathtub.''
   Dukakis press secretary Dayton Duncan responded, ``Quayle's
trying to call attention to his age.'' Quayle is 41.
   On Monday, Quayle blasted Dukakis' economic program, telling a
Michigan audience that the Democratic candidate's heart ``may be in
the right place but his hand'll be back in your pocket'' with
higher taxes and government spending if he is elected in November.
   Dukakis would end the economic expansion of the Reagan years and
``return us once again to those chilling days of no-growth'' under
Jimmy Carter, Quayle asserted at a speech in Kalamazoo, Mich., and
in campaign stops aimed at blue-collar workers and their employers.
   The Republican vice presidential candidate travels to Bismarck,
N.D., today and Colorado as he continues this week's swing through
the Midwest and West.
   The trip began with a tour of an American Instruments
Corporation plant in Kalamazoo, a city of about 100,000 that has
weathered tough economic times during the decade.
   About half of American Instruments' 75 workers have participated
in training programs through the Job Training Partnership Act,
which Quayle helped write. The 1982 federal law encourages
businesses to train disadvantaged or dislocated workers and place
them in local jobs.
   In remarks to business leaders at the Rotary Club, Quayle
sounded the ``good jobs, good wages'' theme that has become a
standard part of Dukakis' speeches.
   He said stagnation and ``unguided'' economic policies had been
the result of ``the last liberal state governor we plucked from
relative obscurity and put in the White House'' _ a reference to
Carter.
   But during the Republican administration, 17 million new jobs
were created, 12 million of them in occupations with wages
averaging more than $20,000 a year, including 5.5 million with
wages averaging closer to $30,000, Quayle said.
   ``They're good jobs at good wages and that's a record to be
proud of,'' Quayle said.
   The message for those who have not yet ``made it'' because of
past disadvantage or discrimination, Quayle said, is that America
still can be ``the land of opportunity in which free men and women
can prosper through their own efforts and their own hard work.''
   Quayle also toured a Milwaukee plant which makes heavy equipment
for U.S. weapons systems. He drew cheers from the workers when he
got behind the controls of a giant forklift and told the crowd, ``I
want my union card.''
   When someone shouted that he would have to pay his dues, Quayle,
whose campaign has been beset by a series of highly publicized
controversies over his military service and academic record, shot
back: ``I've paid some dues over these last few weeks.''
   Quayle also responded later to comments by Dukakis, who said
Monday that George Bush's ``answer to drug kingpins like (Panama
leader Manuel) Noriega is J. Danforth Quayle.''
   ``The governor obviously doesn't know what he's talking about,''
Quayle told reporters. ``We've conducted a very vigorous war on
drugs ... Quite frankly, contrary to the governor of Massachusetts,
who obviously doesn't believe that tough law enforcement provides a
deterrence, we do.''
</TEXT>
