<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Unemployment-States     09-13 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unemployment-States,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vermont Leads Unemployment List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts has slipped from first place to
10th in the past year among states with the lowest unemployment
rates, while neighboring Vermont emerged as the best job provider
for its residents, according to a government report issued Tuesday.
   With an unemployment rate of just 2.3 percent in July, and just
6,900 of its workers lacking jobs, Vermont replaced New Hampshire
as the state with the lowest joblessness, the Bureau of Labor
Statistics said.
   New Hampshire, whose jobless rate climbed from 2 percent in June
to 2.5 percent in July, had been leading the nation with the lowest
unemployment since last October.
   Massachusetts' unemployment rate, meanwhile, rose from 3.4
percent in June to 3.6 percent in July. It was a full percentage
point higher that the same month a year ago, when it held the title
as the state with the lowest joblessness.
   The number of jobless in Massachusetts climbed by more than
25,000 to 155,600 over the year, despite the addition of nearly
60,000 new jobs in the state, according to the BLS data.
   Following Vermont and New Hampshire with the lowest unemployment
rates in July were Hawaii and Delaware at 3.1 percent each,
Connecticut and North Carolina at 3.2 percent each, Rhode Island at
3.3 percent, Nebraska at 3.4 percent and Minnesota at 3.5 percent.
   Louisiana continued to be the only state with double-digit
joblessness, 10.2 percent in July, down from 10.6 percent a month
earlier.
   Kentucky, New Mexico and West Virginia all had unemployment
rates above 8 percent compared with a nationwide jobless rate of
5.5 percent for the month, the bureau said. All of the figures are
unadjusted for seasonal variations.
   While the jobless rate nationwide declined 0.6 percentage point
over the year, it dropped much more dramatically in several states.
Mississippi, Wyoming, Idaho and Texas all saw their unemployment
rates drop by more than 2 full percentage points in the 12 months.
   Unemployment rates over the year rose in only three states:
Massachusetts, Georgia and Arkansas.
   States with the largest job growth over the year were Nevada, up
6.1 percent; Delaware, up 5 percent; Florida and Maine, both up 4.7
percent, and Washington, up 4.4 percent.
   The bureau said service type employment increased in virtually
all of the states while 80 percent of them also showed gains in
manufacturing, transportation, trade and government jobs.
   Cities with the lowest jobless rate in the country were
Burlington, Vt., at 1.8 percent and Stamford, Conn., at 2 percent.
Flint, Mich., had the highest unemployment rate at 14.9 percent
followed by the McAllen-Edinburg-Mission area of Texas at 14.8
percent.
</TEXT>
