<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Arafat     09-13 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Arafat,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Peace Crusader Meets With Arafat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli peace crusader Abie Nathan could be
criminally prosecuted for holding talks with PLO chief Yasser
Arafat and offering a peace plan that calls for mutual recognition,
Israel radio reported today.
   The meeting prompted a political storm in Israel.
   Right-wing legislators said Nathan should to be tried for
treason, but left-wing politicians praised the meeting as an
important step toward ending the 9-month-old Palestinian uprising
in the occupied lands.
   Israel radio said Nathan recently met with Arafat in Tunis and
presented the PLO leader with a peace plan that includes mutual
recognition between Israel and the PLO, a PLO agreement to a
100-day moratorium on violence, and an end to the Palestinian
uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Nathan's plan also calls for the release of Israeli soldiers
missing or captured in Lebanon in exchange for the Israeli release
of thousands of Palestinians detained since the uprising began Dec.
8, Israel radio said.
   According to the United Nations, more than 260 Palestinians have
been killed in the uprising and five Israelis also have died.
   Nathan said Arafat promised to consider the peace proposals
after he meets Tuesday with socialist members of the European
Parliament in Strasbourg, France, according to Israel radio.
   Nathan, who founded the Voice of Peace radio station in 1973,
could face prosecution and a prison sentence of up to three years
for his visit with the Palestine Liberation Organization leader.
   The meeting violates a 1986 Israeli law barring unauthorized
contacts with members of terrorist groups. Israel views the PLO as
a terrorist group.
   Four Israeli leftists are serving six-month prison terms for
meeting with PLO members in Romania in 1986.
   Nathan hopes to brief Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres on his encounter with the PLO chief when he
returns to Israel, Israel radio said.
   Both Peres, who favors an international Middle East peace
conference, and Shamir, who opposes such a forum, have staunchly
refused to include the PLO in peace negotiations.
   Right-wing legislator Yuval Nehman of the Tehiya Party demanded
that Nathan be arrested on his return to Israel for illegally
meeting with an enemy, the radio said. But two Israeli left-wing
parties _ Mapam and the Progressive List for Peace _ praised Nathan
for making an important step toward peace.
   Left-wing legislator Yair Zaban of Mapam said Nathan was an
Israeli ``patriot'' and urged the PLO to recognize Israel, Israel
radio said.
   Nathan's radio station beams mostly rock music programs from a
ship anchored outside Tel Aviv in the Mediterranean Sea.
   In its heyday a decade ago, the so-called Peace Ship dodged
bullets to broadcast peace messages from Beirut during the 1973
Arab-Israeli war.
   Two years later, the vessel delivered 100,000 flowers to the
people of Egypt as a gesture of peace.
</TEXT>
