<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Shultz-Chemicalweapons     09-13 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Chemical weapons,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Compelling Evidence Iraq Used Chemical Weapons, Shultz Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George Shultz said Tuesday
the United States has ``compelling'' evidence that Iraq has used
chemical weapons against its Kurdish citizens.
   But he said the United Nations should conduct its own probe
before being asked to condemn Iraq for alleged genocide.
   Several members of the Senate Judiciary Committee said, however,
that an immediate Security Council session is imperative to make
the case against Iraq.
   Shultz contended that it is important that the world body
investigate the facts independently.
   ``Not everybody agrees with what we say the facts are,'' Shultz
told the committee. He added that the government of Turkey has said
it can find no evidence among the Kurdish refugees fleeing from
Iraq that chemical weapons were used against them.
   ``What you want is for the United Nations to form a team and go
an see what the facts are,'' Shultz said.
   Shultz commented as senator after senator said the evidence the
United States possesses appears to be solid and should be presented
to the Security Council now, to bring into focus the question of
whether Iraq is subjecting its Kurdish minority to a deliberate
campaign of genocide.
   Shultz said the United States reached the conclusion Iraq is
using chemical weapons against the Kurds based on its own
examination of Kurdish refugees inside Turkey and on ``other
evidence which to me seems to be compelling.''
   ``I feel our evidence is quite convincing ...,'' he said. ``But
we're not in a position to make that public.''
   Shultz noted that the U.N. conducted an earlier investigation
into accusations that Iraq had used chemical weapons in its war
with Iran and concluded such weapons were in fact used.
</TEXT>
