<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Salvador-Nicaragua     09-13 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Nicaragua,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nominee Says Sandinistas Continue Subversion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvadoran presidential candidate Fidel Chavez
Mena said Tuesday the Nicaraguan government continues to support
the leftist guerrilla movement in his homeland.
   Chevez Mena, candidate of the ruling Christian Democratic party
in El Salvador, said the insurgents nonetheless are a far less
potent force than they were earlier in the decade.
   While giving no specifics, Chevez Mena said the leftist
Sandinista government in Managua ``continues to give support in one
way or another'' to the rebels and ``have not concealed their
sympathy'' for the insurgents' program.
   Chevez Mena, a former foreign minister and planning minister,
told reporters the Sandinistas have shown no inclination to abide
by the provisions of the Central American peace plan they signed
last year.
   ``I have to regret how Nicaragua, instead of making their
process more flexible, becomes more radical every day,'' he said.
   He said the peace accord signed by the region's five presidents
``deligitimized'' the rebel forces because it confirmed the need
for democratic solutions to the region's problems.
   One measure of how much the insurgent threat has been reduced,
Chavez Mena said, is that he can travel almost anywhere in the
country ``practically without risk.''
   Chevez Mena expressed confidence that he and his party will
prevail in presidential elections next March.
   In contrast to other contenders, including the rightist ARENA
party, Chavez Mena said he represents the ``great center'' of the
Salvadoran political spectrum that reflects the sentiments of most
of his countrymen.
   He said the ARENA victory in legislative elections last March
was a ``punishment vote'' against the Christian Democrats, based on
the party's inability to move quickly enough to solve economic and
social problems.
   He acknowledged that unemployment and other social problems
remain acute but said the Salvadoran people will take the vote for
president next year more seriously and will give the Christian
Democrats another five-year term in office.
</TEXT>
