<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CampaignAbroad 1stLd-Writethru a0614 09-13 1086</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Abroad, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0614,1131</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Press Comment on the U.S. Presidential Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, ADDS comment from Saudi Arabia.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a sampling of recent foreign press comment on the U.S.
presidential race between Democrat Michael Dukakis and Republican
George Bush:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FRANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Jan Krauze, writing from Washington in Le Monde (independent,
left of center) of Paris, Sept. 12: ``Dukakis is at the top,
Dukakis is at the bottom. Bush is on the ground, Bush is in the
sky. For several months, the two candidates for the American
presidential election have been perched at the two ends of a
see-saw, rising and falling with the polls, while the commentators
flock alternatively in one direction or the other, amplifying these
movements to an extreme with a surprising unanimity. ...
   ``There is really no reason for this game of teeter-totter to
stop. The voters seem to be looking with a gloomy and sceptical eye
at these two candidates scrambling to seduce them, who both present
themselves as representatives of the fair middle, the `main stream'
of opinion, but who are scarcely successful in attracting that
opinion; two men who, failing to convince by their own qualities,
apply themselves, not without success, to denouncing the faults of
their rival and throwing low blows. The seesaw is likely to stay in
movement, with more and more grating.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ARABS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Arab editorialists reacted strongly to what Bush and Dukakis
told a B'Nai B'rith assembly Sept. 7 in Baltimore. Here is some of
what Arab newspaper editorials had to say:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JORDAN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Jordan Times (liberal, pro-government) of Amman, Sept. 10:
``The performance of both ... U.S. presidential contenders before
B'nai B'rith last Wednesday was a misfortune for American
statesmanship. The two gentlemen acted more like gladiators than
responsible leaders of their respective parties.
   ``Their willingness to outbid one another in support of Israel
and its bankrupt policies shocked all of us who watched it with
dismay and disbelief. Mr. Bush assured the Jewish constituency in
the United States, and through them Israel, that under his
administration the United States would neither accept an effective
United Nations role in settling the Arab-Israeli conflict nor
accept a Palestinian state in the West Bank.
   ``His reasoning was unfortunate and untenable. Interpreting U.N.
involvement in the Middle East peace process as tantamount to
imposing a solution on Israel is most regrettable. Calling any
future Palestinian state a `threat' to Israel is also unwarranted.
How can a truncated and demilitarized state pose a threat to
Israel, a country with nuclear capabilities?
   ``By insinuating that such a state would also threaten the
security and stability of Jordan, Mr. Bush went beyond the realm of
reality. ...
   ``Gov. Dukakis sadly attempted to outbid Mr. Bush in support of
Israel. For by asserting that Washington will never accept a
solution to the Arab-Israeli conflict, no matter how just and
legitimate, if it is rejected by Israel, Mr. Dukakis has
permanently mortgaged his country's national interests to Israel. .
..
   ``It is sad to see would-be statesmen so lose sight of all
long-term interests, their own included, in the short-term hunt for
votes.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Al-Rai (pro-government) of Amman, Sept. 10: ``Statements by
both U.S. president candidates ... on the Palestinian issue assures
us of the absence of American truthfulness and sincerity toward the
Palestinian people in particular and the Arab world in general.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EGYPT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Al-Akhbar (state-owned) of Cairo, Sept. 11 _ ``Jews in America
are a minority, they cannot tilt the balance in favor of either
candidate, but their influence is decisive. ...
   ``That is why each candidate seeks to win Israel friendship and
outbids the other for winning the influence of American Jews.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>KUWAIT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Kuwait Times (independent), Sept. 10: ``A good look at the
Bush-Dukakis play-acting would, in our opinion, leave one too
dispirited to comment. What they say is, in the first place, so
obviously self-contradictory as to mean nothing at all. The two
have no fresh ideas, no strategies, no sense of direction and
absolutely no sense of purpose.
   ``It is no exaggeration to say that Bush shows little
understanding of what the Palestine question is and Dukakis reminds
that his sense of the world never went beyond his own navel.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UNITED ARAB EMIRATES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Al-Wehda (conservative), Sept. 10: ``It has become clear that
the future president of the United States intends to distort
reality and insists on overshooting facts and ignoring the
legitimate Palestinian rights.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BAHRAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Gulf Daily News (conservative), Sept. 10: ``While few rules
exist in American political circles whenever the election circus
hits town, this year's presidential contenders have been stronger
in their verbal attacks on the Palestinian situation than in
previous polling pledges.
   ``Television news films screened in the U.S. have, in recent
months, shown a little of the day-to-day violent and ruthless
suppression of the Palestinian people in the occupied territories.
   ``And yet both Bush and Dukakis have, by making biased and
reckless speeches, spelled out a very clear lack of understanding
of an issue at the center of the whole Middle East peace question.
   ``The next man in the White House, whether it be Bush or
Dukakis, will have to tackle the Middle East situation very
differently if he hopes to gain the help and friendship of anyone
other than the Israeli lobby.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SAUDI ARABIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Arab News (English-language, conservative), Sept. 13: ``As the
U.S. presidential campaign heats up, both the Republican and
Democratic candidates have been falling over each other in
professing their unswerving support to the state of Israel. ...
   ``After Republican Bush's assertion against the creation of a
Palestinian state, a willing Dukakis has gone a step further to
declare that he will shift the U.S. embassy from Tel Aviv to
occupied Jerusalem, a move resisted so far by successive Republican
and Democratic administrations. Blinded by his electoral interests
to appease a seemingly all-powerful Jewish lobby, Dukakis, it
appears, has failed to see the grave implications of such a move
for the U.S. policy in the Middle East. ...
   ``Although Dukakis found it easy to shrug off the probable
reaction such a U.S. decision would provoke in the Arab and Moslem
world, any U.S. backing for the usurpation (Israeli annexation) of
the Holy City would set off a chain reaction which could be
disastrous for American economic and strategic interests in the
region.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
