<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--US-Guyana     09-13 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--US-Guyana,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guyana to Get US Trade Preferences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States plans to extend trade
preferences soon to Guyana under the Caribbean Basin Initiative,
President Reagan told Guyanan President Hugh Desmond Hoyte on
Tuesday.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan told Hoyte of
the U.S. plan during a brief meeting at the White House. He said
the products to which the trade preferences will apply will be
announced later.
   The United States has given Guyana, a nation on the northeast
coast of South America, $14 million in food aid since 1986.
   Fitzwater said Reagan ``expressed his gratification at the state
of our relations'' with Guyana during the brief meeting.
   The Caribbean Basin Initiative, an administration program
enacted by Congress during Reagan's first term, is a system of
economic aid to countries of the region through trade preferences
and other forms of assistance.
</TEXT>
