<DOCNO> AP880913-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     09-13 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Campbelltown for community; Campbeltown for boat. Both cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CAMPBELLTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British Royal Navy is hoping the
Boy Scouts and the local PTO can help them out.
   The Royal Navy wants to take back from the town a bell that once
rang aboard the destroyer HMS Campbeltown. The bell was one of 50
returned to the United States by the Royal Navy after World War II.
All were taken from the 50 U.S. Navy destroyers given to the United
Kingdom under a lend-lease program in 1940.
   The Royal Navy plans to commission a new HMS Campbeltown in
March and would like the original bell. British officials have
offered a replica.
   Members of the Campbelltown Fire Co., the bell's caretaker, said
the town should decide.
   At a meeting Monday night, the fire company put the issue to a
committee of representatives from the Boy Scouts, the South
Londonderry Township School Board, the American Legion, the fire
company, fire company auxiliary, Parent-Teacher Organization,
Campbelltown Water Co. and a justice of the peace.
   The new committee will be asked to decide if the issue should be
put to a town vote.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Theodore F. Gratkowski of Easthampton soon will be
turning heads when he drives by. He has Massachusetts' commercial
license plate No. 1.
   Gratkowski won the tags in a special lottery held Tuesday at the
Registry of Motor Vehicles headquarters, but was not present when
his entry was drawn. Massachusetts distributes two license plates
to drivers.
   His application was picked in a ceremony that has become
commonplace since Gov. Michael S. Dukakis ordered the lottery to
put an end to cronyism in the distribution of low-number plates,
both commercial and passenger.
   In the latest drawing, the registry had 14 low-number plates
available and received 1,500 eligible entries. The entries were
placed in the same drum used by the state Lottery.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sixth-grade class of gifted and talented
students has been forced to summon all its energy this week _ just
to concentrate.
   For two weeks, teacher Sharon Arnold's 21 students have been
meeting under a stairwell at Lakewood Elementary School as they
await a portable classroom.
   The students have had to put up with noisy halls between
classes, no air conditioning and poor lighting.
   Penumbra, which means ``a space of partial illumination,'' was
one of the vocabulary words during a morning reading lesson, made
more difficult by burned-out light bulbs.
   ``Now when your parents ask you about your classroom at school,
you can tell them it's a penumbra,'' Ms. Arnold told the students.
``At least you'll have a good vocabulary, no matter where we're
having class.''
</TEXT>
