<DOCNO> AP880913-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1448EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     09-13 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children And Monks Join Protests For Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Burma-Army, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children and monks joined thousands of
striking civil servants who marched through Rangoon on Tuesday to
demand the government resign and be replaced by an interim
administration to supervise multiparty elections.
   Opposition leaders told a new Parliament-appointed election
commission that neither they nor the people will accept elections
organized by the government.
   International telephone and telex lines from Rangoon were cut
off Tuesday, but it was not known if they were deliberately
disrupted, since communications with Burma normally are poor.
   Residents of the capital were hoarding food and cutting down on
rice consumption as transportation strikes pushed up the prices of
essential items. About 75 people _ including two Buddhist monks _
began a two-day pro-democracy hunger strike outside city hall. On
Monday, more than 1,000 children ending a 36-hour fast gathered at
the Rangoon General Hospital shouting ``Give Us Democracy!'' and
``Give Us Interim Government!''
   Tens of thousands of striking government workers, students,
medical personnel, children and monks staged peaceful
demonstrations in Rangoon Tuesday against President Maung Maung and
his ruling Burma Socialist Program Party.
   Opposition leaders Aung Gyi, Aung San Suu Kyi and former Defense
Minister Tin Oo told the election commission they rejected the
government's promise to end 26 years of one-party rule and hold
elections as early as late October.
   The three told the commission that polling could not be held
amidst the country's political turmoil and violence, Aung Gyi said,
and that they will not support or participate in elections
organized by the government. In a letter to Maung Maung on Monday,
the opposition demanded an interim government.
   The three leaders also said it would be unfair to hold the
elections before opposition groups form parties and raise funds to
compete against ruling party candidates, state-run Radio Rangoon
reported.
   Aung Gyi said he told election commission chairman Ba Htay, a
retired financial commissioner under a pre-1962 civilian government:
   ``I know you and I respect your integrity and I am confident you
want to hold a free and fair election, but after 26 years of this
rule, most people in the country do not know you and will not have
confidence. More so, people do not trust any government-appointed
commission.'' Like the other four elderly commission members, Ba
Htay is regarded as politically neutral.
   In this city of 3.5 million, strikes by transportation workers
and a lack of fuel have restricted food deliveries from the
countryside. The resulting shortages and an increase in the price
of staples such as rice have forced residents to eat porridge or
gruel and to hoard food.
   A 4.4-pound bag of rice that cost $1.70 a month ago now costs
$5.80, said a Western diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity.
He said gasoline was selling for $16 a gallon on the black market,
compared to $1 a year ago.
   The last multiparty elections in Burma were held Feb. 6, 1960,
when former Prime Minister U Nu's Clean Anti-Fascist People's
Freedom League won a landslide victory over an army-backed party.
   Gen. Ne Win led the March 1962 coup that toppled U Nu. The
military crushed dissent and pursued rigid policies that made
Burma, once one of Asia's richest countries, one of the world's
poorest nations.
   In September 1987, students staged riots against the
government's economic policies, followed by widespread protests in
March and in June. After Ne Win resigned July 23, the party chose
hardliner Sein Lwin to succeed him. After only 17 days in office
and massive anti-government protests, Sein Lwin was replaced on
Aug. 19 by Maung Maung, the first civilian leader since U Nu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1449EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NautilusInventor 1stLd-Writethru a0640 09-13 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nautilus Inventor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0640,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nautilus Inventor Loses Suit Against `20-20'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 2nd to UPDATE with Jones comment.
Deletes now-outdated last 2 grafs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has thrown out a $4 billion
libel lawsuit brought by the inventor of the Nautilus exercise
machine, who claimed he was defamed in a ``20-20'' news program.
   Nothing in the episode damaged Arthur Jones' reputation, U.S.
District Judge Elizabeth Kovachevich said in a ruling last week.
   Jones said Tuesday from his ranch near Ocala that his attorney
would appeal.
   ``I'm not happy with the judge's ruling ... in a case where
we're patently right and they're patently wrong,'' he said. ``We'll
take it clear to the Supreme Court if we have to.''
   The broadcast concerned Jones' attempts to save 63 baby West
African elephants by flying them from Zimbabwe to his ranch. The
elephants had been slated for slaughter to control the size of the
herd.
   In 1984, ``20-20'' broadcast a segment about Jones' efforts to
save the animals. In a March 1987 follow-up, the ABC show revealed
some elephants were being sold from Jones' ranch.
   Reporter Roger Caras said several elephants had gone to small
circuses, ``a fate worse than death.'' In an on-air exchange with
anchor Barbara Walters, Caras said Jones should have kept the
elephants for good, as had been implied from the beginning.
   Jones was quoted as saying that he did not have control of the
animals at the time they were being sold because he was selling
business assets. But the company buying the assets told ABC it was
not responsible for selling the elephants.
   Two weeks after the segment aired, Jones sued, saying the show
deliberately made him seem dishonest and cruel.
   ``The court finds that a reasonable person would not have
intrepreted the broadcast, in whole or in part, as being
defamatory,'' Ms. Kovachevich wrote. She found that the statements
in the broadcast were either constitutionally protected opinion or
not damaging to Jones' reputation.
</TEXT>
