<DOCNO> AP880913-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MentalIllness     09-13 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mental Illness,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Those Most Mentally Ill Get Worst Care, Groups Contend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most seriously mentally ill patients in
the United States tend to get the worst treatment largely because
so many good psychiatrists leave public hospitals to make more
money in private practice, two advocacy groups contended Tuesday.
   ``The lack of adequate services for the seriously mentally ill
is the major failure of American medicine and social services,''
the Public Citizen Health Research Group and the National Alliance
for the Mentally Ill said in a report.
   Dr. Sidney M. Wolfe, co-founder with Ralph Nader of the Public
Citizen health group, called for ``using the leverage of federal
funding to force'' psychiatrists to devote a certain amount of time
to working in public mental health facilities.
   At a news conference and in a subsequent interview, Wolfe said
medical schools in general are more heavily subsidized by federal
money than other professional schools and that psychiatric training
is the most heavily subsidized of the medical specialities.
   ``It's almost impossible to get competent psychiatrists in
public practice in some states,'' said E. Fuller Torrey, a
psychiatrist and a co-author of the report. He said it would not be
too much to require psychiatrists to devote four or five hours a
month to public practice in return for having their education
subsidized by tax money.
   The report itself said the failure to provide adequate care ``is
particularly striking since we now know that the majority of these
people can be successfully treated and rehabilitated.''
   Expanding on a ranking system first used in 1986, a new survey
by the groups concluded that Rhode Island, Wisconsin, New
Hampshire, Maine, Vermont and Connecticut are the best at providing
services.
   Lowest-rated in the survey were Hawaii, Arizona, the District of
Columbia, Delaware, Wyoming, Idaho and Mississippi.
   But Torrey said being at the top of the list was not much to
crow about. ``When most are giving third- and fourth-class care,
states that are delivering second-class care look pretty good. It's
a little like being the smartest kid in the dumb class at school,''
he said.
   The report said: ``In general, it can be said that hospital care
for the seriously mentally ill in state mental hospitals is
somewhat worse than it was two years ago, while outpatient services
are modestly better.
   ``Rehabilitation services and housing for the seriously mentally
ill remain on the best of days seriously deficient and on the worst
of days abysmal,'' it said.
   ``The reasons for the general deterioration of hospital care
center primarily on staffing deficiencies, especially in nursing
and psychiatry,'' the report said. ``In both cases, the
deficiencies are being exacerbated by the mushrooming of private
psychiatric hospitals which are taking the best staff from the
public sector with the lure of higher wages.''
   It attributed marginal improvement in outpatient services ``to
increased public attention to the sorry plight of the homeless
mentally ill, an issue which has moved from the back alleys and
grates of the city to the front pages of its newspapers.''
   The report said conservative estimates suggest that nearly 2
million people in the United States are seriously mentally ill,
with 8 percent of them hospitalized.
   ``Approximately one-third of homeless individuals are seriously
mentally ill,'' the report said. ``Their visibility on America's
streets is a poignant reminder of the debacle of
deinstitutionalization and failure of federally funded community
mental health centers.''
   Laurie M. Flynn, director of the National Alliance for the
Mentally Ill, noted that her organization is made up of 70,000
families of people suffering from mental illness.
   ``For us the lack of services is a personal and family
tragedy,'' she said.
   The overall state rankings were based on a composite figure
drawn by awarding points ranging from zero to five in each of four
categories: hospital care, outpatient services, rehabilitation and
housing.
   The report relied on questionnaires to state mental health
directors, various government surveys and visits to 35 states and
the District of Columbia. The report said 82 percent of the state
mental health directors returned nine-page questionnaires _ when
guaranteed anonymity _ even though their national organization did
not endorse the survey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
