<HEAD>State-By-State Rankings on Care for Mentally Ill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mental Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are state-by-state rankings on the level
of care provided for the seriously mentally ill as compiled by
Public Citizen Health Research Group and the National Alliance for
the Mentally Ill.
   The rankings were based on a composite figure drawn by assigning
a zero to five-point value in each of four categories: hospital
care, outpatient services, rehabilitation and housing.
   Data collection methods included questionnaires to state mental
health directors and others, various government surveys and visits
to 35 states and the District of Columbia.
   When states have an equal number of points, they were ranked
according to per capita income, with poor states ranked higher on
the assumption that, all other things being equal, wealthy states
should do better than poorer states.
   The number in brackets is the 1986 ranking. The groups said
inclusion of additional data in the 1988 figures could account for
some changes in position rather than actual improvement or
worsening of services.
