<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-MedicaidAbortions     09-13 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medicaid Abortions,350</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, bowing to a veto threat and the
House's will, today retreated from its position that the federal
Medicaid program should fund abortions for poor victims of rape and
incest.
   The Senate voted 47-43 to drop an amendment that would have
liberalized the current policy of federal funds only when abortion
is necessary to save a woman's life.
   In July, the Senate voted 73-19 to expand Medicaid to pay for
abortions in promptly reported cases of rape or incest. States
would have had the option of retaining the current, more limited
policy.
   The abortion controversy had been holding up a massive $140
billion spending bill meant to keep the departments of Labor,
Health and Human Services, and Education in business during fiscal
1989, which starts Oct. 1.
   The bill contains money for college loans, disadvantaged
children, job training and AIDS research and education, among other
things.
   President Reagan has repeatedly said he would veto the entire
Labor-HHS-Education appropriations bill if it came to him with the
Senate abortion provision. The latest threat came in a letter Sept.
7 to congressional leaders.
   The House on Friday refused 216-166 to go along with the Senate
expansion.
   Three hours of often emotional debate preceded today's vote,
with some senators decrying abortion and others maintaining that
poor women in desperate circumstances deserve access to a legal
medical option.
   ``The question is, is a child conceived by rape any less of a
human being than one who is not?'' said Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.
``One atrocity... doesn't justify another. Rape doesn't justify
murder.''
   Sen. Lowell Weicker, R-Conn., countered that it ``defies all
common sense'' not to permit federal payments for ``the most narrow
exceptions under the most extraordinary and dismal of
circumstances.''
   Fourteen states and the District of Columbia pay for Medicaid
abortions, but only receive federal reimbursement for
life-threatening cases. The Senate vote in July was the first time
since 1981 that either chamber had approved more liberal
eligibility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
