<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HousePledge     09-13 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House Pledge,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Opens Session With Pledge Of Allegiance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Representatives, trying to juggle
a political hot potato, broke with tradition Tuesday by opening its
session with recitation of the Pledge of Allegiance.
   Speaker Jim Wright said the pledge, which has become an item of
controversy in the presidential campaign, would be recited on the
House floor at the beginning of each day's session until Congress
adjourns next month.
   But Wright, D-Texas, also lashed out harshly at Republicans who
have sought to make the pledge an issue, saying such efforts are
``childish, immature and mean-spirited as a person can be.''
   Rep. G.V. ``Sonny'' Montgomery, D-Miss., held his hand over his
heart as he led about three dozen lawmakers in reciting the 31-word
pledge. Montgomery's podium was turned sideways from its normal
position so he could see the large U.S. flag that hangs behind the
speaker's chair.
   The pledge was to be led on Wednesday by Rep. Jerry Lewis,
R-Calif., with Democrats and Republicans alternating days through
the end of the session. The members in the chamber Tuesday appeared
to be roughly equally divided between the two parties.
   Rep. John Rowland, R-Conn., who brought the pledge squabble to
the House chamber last week, called it a historic moment and said
he would press to make the recitation a daily fixture. Wright
promised that such a rules change would be considered through
normal channels.
   ``I compliment the speaker for recognizing that the dignity and
integrity of the House would be enhanced by the recitation of the
Pledge of Allegiance at the beginning of each session day,''
Rowland said.
   The pledge has become the centerpiece of an argument, begun in
the presidential campaign, over whether Democrats or Republicans
are more patriotic.
   Republican nominee George Bush began the fight by criticizing
Democrat Michael Dukakis for vetoing a bill in 1977 that would have
penalized teachers for not leading the pledge in Massachusetts
schools. Dukakis, the governor, said he vetoed the bill because it
was unconstitutional, and has labeled Bush's attack a McCarthyite
tactic.
   Wright also repeated his belief that attempting to use the
pledge as a political weapon ``is McCarthyism,'' a reference to the
fervently anti-communist senator who impugned many Americans'
patriotism in the 1950s.
   The pledge, Wright said, is like the daily prayer that opens
House sessions. ``It's a personal matter'' and members are ``free
not to do so'' if they choose. ``I don't think it's up to me to go
around and see whose lips are moving,'' he said.
   Republicans appeared to delight last week when Rowland surprised
the chamber's Democratic leadership and sought a sudden rules
change to make the pledge permanent. The move was defeated on a
226-168 vote, largely along party lines.
   Without mentioning Rowland, Wright today said ``the idea of
trying to use the pledge as a wedge of division among Americans is
what I regard as McCarthyism.''
   He added: ``To suggest that another political party is less
patriotic ... is childish, immature and mean-spirited as a person
can be.''
   Rowland rose after the pledge was recited today to add that he
agreed with Wright that it should ``not be confrontational.''
   Congress formally endorsed the pledge in a 1942 law, and the
words ``under God'' were added in 1954 by a second law. But the
31-word sentence has not been a part of the chamber's own routine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1516EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle     09-13 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Ridicules Dukakis on Defense, Jokes About `Rubber Duck'
Advisers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle ridiculed Michael Dukakis'
national security credentials Tuesday with jokes about the
Democratic nominee's ``rubber duck'' naval adviser and foreign
policy dealings limited to his New Hampshire neighbors.
   At a rally of several hundred supporters in Bismarck, the
Republican vice presidential candidate said Dukakis was
``dangerously naive'' on national security and ``the most
anti-defense candidate on a national level since George McGovern.''
   Earlier, Quayle told backers in the Milwaukee suburb of
Wauwatosa it was ``shocking'' that Dukakis found it necessary to
receive defense briefings last weekend from members of Congress.
   ``He doesn't know enough about national defense,'' said the
Indiana senator. ``He has to stop in and ask members of Congress
that I've been working with for the past 12 years.''
   On a day when Dukakis delivered a major speech on U.S.-Soviet
relations in Chicago, Quayle said the Massachusetts governor
doesn't have ``the understanding or qualifications'' to run for
president.
   ``Want to hear a sad story about the Dukakis campaign?'' Quayle
asked.
   ``The governor of Massachusetts, he lost his top naval adviser
last week. His rubber duck drowned in his bathtub,'' Quayle said to
roars of laughter from his audience at Bush-Quayle campaign
headquarters for Wisconsin.
   Dukakis press secretary Dayton Duncan responded in Chicago that
``Quayle's trying to call attention to his age.'' Quayle is 41.
   Republican nominee George Bush's running mate then headed for
Colorado on a Western campaign swing that focused on jobs, economic
prosperity and a strong defense.
   The Republicans have tried to portray Dukakis as weak on defense
and foreign policy issues, and have criticized his opposition to
the MX and Midgetman nuclear missiles and President Reagan's Star
Wars plan for a space-based missile defense.
   ``You don't learn what you need to know about the national
security of our nation in one weekend cram course,'' said Quayle,
referring to Dukakis' weekend meetings with Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga.,
and Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairmen of the Senate and House Armed
Services committees.
   ``The closest thing he (Dukakis) has to foreign policy
experience is dealing with the governor of New Hampshire,'' Quayle
said.
   He accused Dukakis of having a ``midnight conversion'' on
defense, presumably a reference to a recent, apparent softening in
the governor's opposition to Star Wars.
   ``He didn't just find religion. He found his poll numbers,''
Quayle said.
   He noted that Zbigniew Brzezinski, national security adviser to
former President Carter, had endorsed Bush, who named Brzezinski on
Monday to a 13-member panel of campaign advisers on national
security.
   ``Dr. Brzezinski ... is willing to put his reputation, his
integrity ... to support George Bush,'' Quayle said. ``The reason
he made that decision is because he knows the governor of
Massachusetts. He knows what kind of a president he would be.''
</TEXT>
