<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1517EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PrimariesRdp Bjt   09-13 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primaries Rdp, Bjt,0797</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Primaries Focus on Races for Open Senate Seats in Vermont,
Wisconsin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls close at 7 p.m. EDT in Vermont, 8 in New Hampshire,
8:30 Wisconsin, 9 in Minnesota, 10 in Arizona and Utah; matter
below the dash will stand.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters chose candidates Tuesday to succeed retiring Sens. Robert
Stafford and William Proxmire, with moderate Republican Rep. James
Jeffords facing a conservative in Vermont and former Democratic
Gov. Anthony S. Earl battling a sports team owner in Wisconsin.
   In other highlights of primary voting in six states, New
Hampshire Rep. Judd Gregg was favored over two opponents for the
GOP nomination to succeed retiring Gov. John Sununu.
   And in Arizona, more than a dozen Republican legislators who
voted to impeach or convict Evan Mecham last spring were challenged
by candidates loyal to the ousted governor.
   Jeffords, whose frequent opposition to President Reagan's
policies angered fellow Republicans, faced newcomer Michael Griffes
in the Senate primary. Democrat William Gray, a former U.S.
attorney, had no primary opposition.
   Proxmire's retirement in Wisconsin after 31 years in the Senate
sparked spirited races in both parties. On the Democratic side, the
latest newspaper polls showed Earl and Milwaukee Bucks basketball
team owner Herbert Kohl leading a four-way race that included
former Deputy Attorney General Edward R. Garvey and Secretary of
State Douglas La Follette.
   Kohl, who had never before sought public office, spent nearly
$2.1 million, much of it on TV ads, and drew criticism from his
rivals that he was trying to buy the election.
   Republicans chose between state Sen. Susan Engeleiter, a
moderate, and the more conservative Stephen B. King, former GOP
state chairman.
   In New Hampshire, Gregg, son of a former governor, faced former
Manchester Mayor Robert Shaw and political neophyte William
Lawrence for the Republican nomination for governor. The unopposed
Democratic nominee was lawyer Paul McEachern, a foe of the Seabrook
nuclear power plant who narrowly lost to Sununu in 1986.
   In Gregg's 2nd District, Chuck Douglas, a former state Supreme
Court justice, was locked in a bitter contest with former state
Rep. Betty Tamposi in a six-way GOP race.
   Primaries also were held in:
   _ Minnesota, where Sen. David Durenberger and Democratic
Attorney General Hubert H. ``Skip'' Humphrey III were expected to
breeze past primary challengers for Senate nominations;
   _ Utah, where Democrats Craig Oliver and Robert Stringham sought
the nomination to oppose Republican Rep. Howard Nielson.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Stafford, a Republican, and Proxmire, a Democrat, were among six
senators _ three from each party _ to retire this year. Democrats
now control the Senate by a margin of 54 to 46.
   There was irony in the high-stakes campaign to succeed the
72-year-old Proxmire, who had become famous for his low-budget
campaigns and congressional budget-cutting efforts. In winning
re-election 1982, Proxmire said he spent $145.10, some of it for
postage to return contributions.
   Kohl, a former chain store owner, was by far the leader in
spending, followed by $431,000 by Earl, $360,000 by Garvey and
$15,500 by La Follette, as of Aug. 24, Election Board records
showed.
   In the GOP race, King, 47, a former FBI agent and one-time
chairman of the Republican Party of Wisconsin, sought to pin a
liberal tag on Engeleiter, 36, a veteran of 11 years the
Legislature and the Senate's minority leader.
   King stressed his opposition to a tax increase and abortion and
his support for the death penalty. Engleiter, who said she had the
backing of a broader segment of the party, said she had spent much
of her legislative career fighting against increased taxes.
   King criticized Engeleiter for running for the Senate when she
has two small children at home.
   Motherhood also became an issue in New Hampshire, where Sen.
Gordon Humphrey, who endorsed Douglas for Congress, created an
uproar last week when he said Tamposi shouldn't run because she has
a 22-month-old daughter. Humphrey apologized two days later.
   Douglas won endorsements from nationally known conservatives,
including Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah and Rep. Jack Kemp of New York.
   In Vermont, Griffes called himself the real Republican in the
race to succeed the 75-year-old Stafford, who served as governor
and congressman before entering the Senate in 1971.
   Jeffords' support of Democratic initiatives over the years
angered many of the GOP faithful, including former four-term Gov.
Richard Snelling, who donated $1,000 to the Griffes campaign.
   In 1981, Jeffords was the sole House Republican to vote against
Reagan's tax-cut package; In 1987, he had the second-highest
anti-Reagan voting record among Republicans in the House, as
analyzed by Congressional Quarterly magazine. He opposed the
president on 71 percent of the key votes.
</TEXT>
