<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CubanShooting     09-13 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuban Shooting,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Blames Defector For London Shooting Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Havana Radio on Tuesday blamed a shadowy defector
and British intelligence for an incident in which a Cuban diplomat
in London pulled out a gun and fired shots at people he said were
menacing him.
   Britain ordered Cuba's ambassador, Oscar Fernandez-Mell, and the
Cuban embassy's third secretary, Carlos Manuel Medina Perez, to
leave the country Monday in the wake of the shooting.
   A statement by the the British Foreign Office expelling the two
Cubans said the government ``would not tolerate the use of firearms
by diplomats.''
   The Foreign Office said Medina Perez told police he fired
because he was afraid for his safety. It said he was released from
police custody after he claimed diplomatic immunity.
   Government-operated Havana Radio blamed Cuban defector
Florentino Aspillaga Lombard for the shooting, saying he tried to
strong-arm Medina Perez into defecting.
   In a broadcast monitored in Miami, the radio station said
Aspillaga defected from the Cuban embassy in Prague,
Czechoslovakia, in June 1987 ``to put himself at the service of the
U.S. Central Intelligence Agency.''
   Aspillaga, along with three men and a woman, approached Medina
Perez and tried to persuade him to defect, the government radio
said.
   ``The traitor (Aspillaga) threatened Medina Perez to make him
desert,'' said Havana Radio. ``In response, Carlos Medina Perez
drew the gun he was carrying and fired against the traitor, and the
whole group ran away.''
   The Cuban radio said ``it is absolutely impossible that a man
totally in the hands of the CIA and under strict security measures
could travel to Great Britain and carry on this type of action
against a Cuban diplomat without the cooperation of the British
Intelligence Service and British authorities.''
   The radio called Perez's expulsion ``deeply unfair and
arbitary,'' saying it was aimed at hiding cooperation between
British intelligence and the CIA in the affair.
   Police said detectives had traced one man who was slightly
injured in the shooting and were satisfied he ``was not posing a
threat to anyone.'' Scotland Yard police headquarters said it would
not release the man's identity, adding the police inquiry into the
shooting was closed.
</TEXT>
