<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hispanics     09-13 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hispanics,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Task Force Calls for Developing Hispanic Talent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republicans proposed a series of
education, employment and health initiatives Tuesday aimed at
ensuring that Hispanics ``have access to the opportunities and
support systems'' already available to most Americans.
   But the Democratic chairman of the Congressional Hispanic
Caucus, Rep. Albert Bustamante of Texas, said there was ``not
really any substance to that report'' and that its findings were an
``election year-type of rhetoric.''
   ``They need a primer on understanding the issues because they
always vote wrong on the issues. I'm happy to see they've at least
put a position out there,'' he said, calling the 1980s ``really and
truly a disaster for Hispanics.''
   But another Hispanic leader, Rita Di Martino of Staten Island,
N.Y., board chairman of the the National Council of La Raza and New
York state Republican Party vice chairman, said the report dealt
meaningfully with the issues affecting Hispanics, the nation's
fastest-growing population group.
   ``We have some very important people on this (task force). This
is a first. This is historic,'' said Ms. Di Martino, a member of
the task force's bipartisan advisory committee.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the panel, said many of
the recommendations could be accomplished with legislation, while
the executive branch would be encouraged to take action with
through executive orders.
   He said the task force had already backed efforts to provide $6
million to fund national and local Hispanic literacy programs.
   Bustamante challenged the Senate Republicans to do more, and
back up their promises with discretionary funds for programs and
minority contracts benefiting Hispanics.
   The report said education is the most critical issue in the
Hispanic community. Unless literacy and dropout rates are turned
around, it said, young Hispanics will not be able to find jobs as
the United States evolves from a manufacturing to a technology and
service-based economy with greater needs for workers with higher
skills.
   Studies show Hispanics are the least educated major population
group in the country, the study said.
   The task force's recommendations include:
   _Expanding national and local initiatives to reduce illiteracy
and combat a high Hispanic student dropout rate.
   _Advocating programs at the federal, state and local levels and
in the private sector that provide managerial skills assistance to
small minority businesses.
   _Pursuing an aggressive trade policy with Mexico to benefit
businesses on both sides of the border.
   _Improving the recruitment of qualified Hispanics into
managerial and professional positions in the private and public
sector.
   _Promoting health and disease prevention efforts, with an
emphasis on fighting AIDS, and increasing the number of health care
professionals serving the Hispanic community and increasing
Hispanic input in health care policy issues.
   _Supporting better access to bonding and insurance for small
businesses.
</TEXT>
