<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BiaggiRace     09-13 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biaggi Race,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biaggi: Striving for Defeat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mario Biaggi's campaigns for Congress have been
pretty dull affairs the last couple of decades; he's won every one
by a landslide. This year, Biaggi hopes for something new. He hopes
to lose.
   At least he says he hopes to lose. Nothing comes at face value
in Bronx politics, a world where tempers run hot, bad blood runs
deep and rap sheets serve as the nearest thing to a score card.
   What is certain is that the race for Biaggi's seat is one of the
oddest in years, even by Bronx standards. A month ago, convicted of
corruption, Biaggi quit his office. Now, he just might win it back.
   ``What we've got there are pretty unique circumstances,'' said
Raymond Smock, historian of the House of Representatives. Without
checking, he said, the last case of an unwilling winner to spring
to mind occurred in 1788.
   Of course, Biaggi has yet to win, and his opponents in the
Democratic primary predict he won't. ``People have a lot of
affection for him,'' said state Assemblyman Eliot Engel. ``But
they're not going to vote for him.''
   Some will. Biaggi's focus on constituent services made him
immensely popular in his district, which takes in much of the north
Bronx and Yonkers. He won each of his last six races with at least
90 percent of the vote.
   Indeed, his career came to an end at the jury box rather than
the ballot box. Twice in the past year he was convicted of federal
corruption charges, and he was facing expulsion from the House when
he tearfully quit last month.
   In addition to resigning his seat, ``I am withdrawing as a
candidate for re-election,'' he said at the time. ``I will not
campaign. I will not run.''
   But neither of his opponents in the primary Thursday is remotely
as well known as Biaggi; even a strong sympathy vote conceivably
could win him the nomination. And because Democrats outnumber
Republicans 3-1 in the district, the Democratic nominee generally
wins the seat. In any case, there is only one candidate on the
Republican line: Mario Biaggi.
   The issue goes beyond Biaggi. The Bronx Democratic organization
has been shaken by recent corruption convictions of party leaders.
If Biaggi won and declined to serve, the organization could
reassert itself by naming its own candidate to run in a special
election, which are held without primaries.
   Borough President Fernando Ferrer, who presents himself as a
reformer, was concerned enough this week to warn voters away from
Biaggi. ``We in the Bronx have worked hard to recover our lost
respect,'' he said. ``Let's not lose an opportunity to better the
Bronx by throwing away a vote.''
   One issue is why Biaggi remained on the ballot at all. He did
not contest his opponents' court challenge of his nominating
petitions, hoping, said his lawyer, to be thrown off the ballot.
   But the state Board of Election already had ruled the petitions
valid, and without evidence otherwise, the court upheld it.
Biaggi's federal prosecutor expressed a dim view of the suggestion
that he move out of state as a ploy to disqualify himself. And with
no other legal reason for the court to remove him from the ballot,
he stayed on.
   A victory by one of the challengers would make the matter moot.
Engel, a state assemblyman since 1977, has won all the key
endorsements. Also running is a former assemblyman, Vincent
Marchiselli, who has sought to link Engel to the discredited party
organization.
   The fight has been hostile, though traditional issues have
hardly figured in it. The race itself is the issue: Marchiselli
charged that Engel sought secretly to keep Biaggi on the ballot so
Biaggi and Marchiselli would split the Italian-American vote.
Engel, meanwhile, charged that politicians who want the seat were
conducting a ``whispering campaign'' to win votes for Biaggi so the
party would designate them to run in a special election.
   Biaggi, who faces sentencing for his latest conviction next
month, is keeping quiet. He declined to be interviewed, and a
spokesman, Bob Blancato, would refer only to the resignation
statement saying he would not campaign.
   ``At the juncture where we are, that stands,'' Blancato said.
``After Thursday, there may be a need for a new statement.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
