<DOCNO> AP880913-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FairnessDoctrine     09-13 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fairness Doctrine,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appellate Court Hears Arguments Over Fairness Doctrine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appellate court heard arguments Tuesday
that the Federal Communications Commission decision to abolish the
fairness doctrine for broadcasters both hurt and advanced the cause
of free speech.
   The requirement that television and radio stations present
opposing viewpoints on controversial questions was a ``prevalent
deterrent to broadcasters to air public issues,'' FCC general
counsel Diane S. Killory told a panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals here.
   ``Elimination of the doctrine would best further the public's
interest in recieving robust debate on controversial issues,'' she
told the three-judge panel, which is reviewing last year's 4-0 FCC
vote abolishing the fairness standard.
   The FCC found that because there were so many sources of
information, the 38-year-old fairness doctrine was no longer needed
to ensure the dissemination of all points of view in the debate on
a public issue, she said.
   Enforcement of the fairness doctrine prompted many broadcasters
to avoid controversial issues so they would not be required to air
all sides to a question and the result was bland speech, she said.
   But Andrew Schwartzman, executive director of the Media Access
Project, accused the FCC of ignoring abundant evidence that many
broadcast outlets had not presented alternate points of view on
controversial subjects.
   ``There was a blatant predisposition to reach this result, the
FCC has flip-flopped,'' he told Circuit Judges Patricia Wald,
Kenneth Starr and Stephen Williams.
   ``Why shouldn't an agency that now says we're concerned about
core First Amendment values get credit for that?'' Starr asked.
   ``It's one thing for the FCC to say it's sensitive to First
Amendment concerns,'' Schwartzman said. But he accused the agency
of conducting a ``one-sided and narrow review.''
   If it found that the regulation had a chilling effect on free
speech, ``the commission is free to tinker with the adminstration
of the fairness doctrine,'' he said. ``It's very convenient outcome
for the FCC to say `there is a very chilling effect, we have to
throw out the whole thing.'''
   But Killory argued that stricter enforcment ``would require the
FCC to get into the editorial judgment of broadcasters.''
   The fairness doctrine requires broadcast stations to present the
opposing viewpoint on a controversial issue in the event that the
other side had purchased advertising to promote its arguments.
   The doctrine's constitutionality was upheld by the Supreme Court
in 1969, but in 1984 the high court said it would review that
decision if presented with new evidence that enforcement was no
longer necessary.
   The next year, the FCC concluded the doctrine no longer served
the public interest but said it would continue its enforcement
because of uncertainty over whetherit was legally binding.
   In 1986, the federal appeals court here found that the fairness
doctrine was not codified as part of the 1959 Communications Act.
   Meredith Corp. then challenged the constitutionality of the
fairness doctrine after the FCC found that a station it owned in
Syracuse, N.Y., had filed to present opposing views about the
construction of a nuclear power plant.
   The appeals court ordered the FCC to consider Meredith's
constitutional challenge, a review that resulted in the Aug. 4,
1987 vote to abolish the doctrine.
   Floyd Abrams, a prominent First Amendment lawyer who represents
Meredith, urged the panel to ``defer to old-fashioned commission
expertise'' which found that ``the public is receiving information
not because of the fairness doctrine but in spite of the fairness
doctrine.''
   Communications attorney Timothy Dyk predicted ``the case will
turn on a constitutional issue. I think this is a case for the
Supreme Court.''
   Organizations supporting the CC included the National
Association of Broadcasters, the Reporters Committee for the
Freedom of the Press and the American Newspaper Publishers
Association.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Cuba     09-13 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Cuba,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Says Envoy Fired At Stalking CIA Man</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cuban Embassy charged Tuesday that its
commercial attache, who was expelled along with the ambassador,
opened fire on a CIA operative who had tried to get him to defect.
   The commercial attache, Third Secretary Carlos Manuel Medina
Perez, and the ambassador, Oscar Fernandez-Mell, left London
Tuesday on a scheduled flight for Prague, en route to the Cuban
capital, Havana.
   In a statement read on the embassy steps, First Secretary
Roberto De Armas charged that the Central Intelligence Agency
operative was a former Cuban diplomat who defected in June _
Florentino Azpillaga Lombard.
   De Armas claimed British and U.S. secret services had worked
together during the incident. The British Foreign Office was
enraged by the shooting because of its strict ban on diplomats
carrying arms.
   ``The traitor in a menacing way instructed Senor Medina Perez to
defect,'' said De Armas. ``In reply to this he took out the gun he
was carrying, fired it and the group ran away.''
   London police said in a statement that anti-terrorist squad
detectives ``traced and interviewed'' a man slighted injured in the
Monday afternoon shooting and ``we are wholly satisfied he was not
posing a threat to anyone.''
   ``We will not be releasing his details,'' the statement from
Scotland Yard police headquarters added. ``Following the action of
the Foreign Office, the inquiry is now closed.'' Officials at
Scotland Yard refused to elaborate.
   The Foreign Office told ambassador Fernandez-Mell he must take
responsibility for Medina Perez being armed, but the ambassador
told reporters at the airport that he found his swift ousting
``very strange.''
   The British domestic new agency, Press Association, said police
sources confirmed that the wounded man ``was a security officer''
and part of a team keeping the diplomat under surveillance.
   Witnesses have said that Medina Perez, who opened fire outside
his apartment in west London, shot at a group of three men and a
woman who fled in a car. He was stopped by police, claimed
diplomatic immunity and then told the Foreign Office he fired
because he was in fear of his life.
   The Foreign Office refused to comment on the reports that the
communist diplomat was under British or U.S. security surveillance.
   ``We have reacted appropriately to a totally unacceptable and
outrageous action on the streets of London,'' said a spokesman, who
according to British civil service practice, declined to be
identified.
   Havana Radio, in a broadcast monitored in Miami, said Aspillaga
defected from the Cuban Embassy in Prague, Czechoslovakia, in June
1987 ``to put himself at the service of the U.S. Central
Intelligence Agency.''
   The radio called the expulsion of Medina Perez ``deeply unfair
and arbitary,'' saying it had absolutely nothing to do with the
incident.
   Since a policewoman was shot and killed by a gunman firing from
the Libyan embassy at demonstrators in April 1984, the Foreign
Office has taken a harsh attitude towards violations of its blanket
ban on embassies having guns.
   The Cubans were expelled within days of a Vietnamese diplomat
being ordered out for brandishing a gun at demonstrators outside
his embassy.
   In normal circumstances, British policeman are not armed, a fact
which heightens official anger at gun-toting diplomats.
   In his statement, Cuban diplomat De Armas said the alleged CIA
operative could not have entered Britain without collusion between
the U.S. and British authorities. He demanded to know what had
happened to the wounded man and why the British authorities refused
to identify him.
   ``It is possible now that both the British authorities as well
as the British and American secret services will find themselves in
an embarrassing situation when they explain what really happened,''
said De Armas.
   The expulsions mean Cuba has 12 diplomats left in London.
Britain has five diplomats in Havana.
</TEXT>
