<DOCNO> AP880913-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1630EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Radon Bjt   09-13 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radon, Bjt,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania Officials To Certify Radon Testers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Pennsylvania, where the seriousness of
radon contamination first came to light when a man set off
radiation alarms at a nuclear plant, the state is moving to
regulate companies that test homes for the deadly gas.
   The steps are the outgrowth of nearly four years experience with
radon, an odorless, colorless gas the Environmental Protection
Agency has now linked to 20,000 lung cancer deaths a year
nationwide. The EPA said Monday every home in the country should be
tested for radon because contamination is wider spread than
previously believed.
   Radon is a radioactive gas, trace amounts of which are produced
in the decay of uranium in soil and rocks. The gas is present in
the outdoors normally at about 0.5 percent of the EPA's 4 picocurie
``action level.'' Homes tend to concentrate radon indoors.
   Radon kills people by leaving its radioactive decay products in
the lungs, irradiating the tissues for a lifetime.
   Pennsylvania will require companies testing for the gas to pass
a state-approved course in radon detection, demonstrate at least a
year of professional experience and agree to provide radon-testing
data to the government, said Jason J. Gaertner, a state Department
of Environmental Resources official.
   After Sept. 21, ``it will be illegal to provide radon services
in the state unless they are certified,'' he said Tuesday.
   ``It's simply a health issue which needs to be investigated
house by house,'' Gaertner said. ``The problem levels are
sprodadic, but in being sporadic, they're spread across the entire
country. There aren't really bad areas, there are problem homes.''
   Gaertner, who works in the DER's Bureau of Radiation Protection,
said his office received ``a tremendous number'' of calls Tuesday
because of the EPA report.
   ``What we are really telling them is the same message we have
been giving the public for a year now,'' Gaertner said. ``That
message, based on DER data from the past, is that problem homes can
occur anywhere in the state, but most people after testing don't
have a problem.''
   In neighboring West Virginia, the state Health Department said
it had received more than 50 calls by mid-day Tuesday from
residents concerned about the effects of radon gas.
   ``What the people are mainly concerned about is how they can get
the radon kits to have their homes tested,'' said Rod Kovack, a
radiological technician for the Health Department. ``We've been
furnishing them with a list of places where they can obtain the
kits and along with that list, we've sent a couple of pamphlets
that the EPA has put out for concerned homeowners.''
   The Pennsylvania department plans to publish guidelines for
contractors and homeowners on specific remediation techniques for
homes with unacceptable radon levels, Gaertner said. A companion
booklet will offer tips on selecting contractors, along with a list
of state-certified contractors, he said.
   ``This will help the public in that the industry will be
regulated,'' he said. ``We haven't seen severe problems, but you
want to make sure problems don't occur, that the firms have proper
training and that they are following the proper methods for
remediation.''
   Of the 429 Pennsylvania homes tested in the national survey
released Monday, 37 percent had more than 4 picocuries of
radioactivity per liter of air, the level used by the EPA as the
trigger for more sophisticated tests that determine if remediation
is needed. The highest level was 114 in Perry County.
   Those readings contrast to levels in the thousands of picocuries
found previously in the uranium-rich Reading Prong geological
formation of eastern Pennsylvania, northern New Jersey and New
York, Gaertner said.
   Those earlier findings were accurate but rare, he said.
   ``What it did was present a distorted picture of the radon
situation,'' he said. ``The highest reading we have encountered
outside the Reading Prong is no more than 800. And now, we do a
statistically random study and the highest reading is 114.''
   On Dec. 14, 1984, Stanley Watras, a field engineer for a
subcontractor building Philadelphia Electric Co.'s Limerick nuclear
plant, tripped radiation alarms as he went to work.
   Investigators discovered his home atop the Reading Prong had
radon levels 675 times the acceptable state guidelines. He and his
family were evacuated.
   The discovery awoke scientists and officials to the severity of
radon contamination in some areas and led to the creation of the
radiation bureau in Gilbertsville, about a two miles from Watras'
home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1643EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Radon-HomeTesting     09-13 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radon-Home Testing,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Guidelines in Self-testing for Radon in Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Radon Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers planning to test their homes for
radon in the wake of the report by the federal Environmental
Protection Agency can get some free help through state agencies and
the EPA.
   Stephen Page of the EPA's Radon Program said homeowners or
renters should get a copy of the ``Citizen's Guide to Radon''
available through state agencies or an area EPA office. The guide
outlines steps consumers should take when using one of the several
commercially available home testing kits.
   Before purchasing a home kit, Page said, people should check
with a list of 216 companies that have passed the EPA's proficiency
test. Also, it is important to carefully follow kit instructions
because even a slight deviation can easily alter the results, he
said.
   If the reading is 4 picocuries or higher, Page suggests a
follow-up test.
   Bill Belanger, the EPA's regional radiation representative for
Pennsylvania, said homeowners also can buy, for $400, a continuous
radon monitor that uses electronic detectors to count the
disintegration of radon particles.
   Once the level is known, several steps can be taken to alleviate
the problem.
   One method, called sub-slab ventilation, is used in homes with
the highest levels and costs $800 to $1,500. It involves poking a
hole in the basement floor and inserting a polyvinylchloride pipe
that leads to the attic or the outside where a fan carries away the
gas. This can reduce the radon level by as much as 99 percent, Page
said.
   Two other relatively easy methods are sealing the sump pump or
ventilating crawl spaces.
   A third method, caulking any cracks in the basement floor,
should almost always be used in conjunction with another method, he
added.
   Jason J. Gaertner, a A Pennsylvania Department of Environmental
Resources official in Gilbertsville, the state's central office for
radon issues, said Pennsylvania is one of two states with a radon
certification program for companies providing radon services _
kits, staff visits, remediation and supplies. Companies are now
applying for certification, and by the winter, the DER should have
published a list of certified firms.
</TEXT>
