<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Medicaid-Abortions     09-13 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medicaid-Abortions,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Drops Effort to Fund Abortions for Rape, Incest Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate surrendered to political reality
Tuesday and gave up its fight to permit federally funded abortions
for poor victims of rape and incest.
   Facing strong House opposition, a White House veto threat and
the prospect of a $140 billion social spending bill held hostage to
the abortion controversy, the chamber agreed by voice vote to scrap
its position.
   The vote came after two roll calls in which members first
refused, 46-44, and then agreed, 47-43, to kill a motion to insist
on allowing federal Medicaid payments for abortions in promptly
reported rape and incest cases.
   Abortion was the only area of disagreement between the two
chambers in the huge spending bill for the departments of Labor,
Health and Human Services and Education.
   The House rejected the Senate view last Friday, voting 216-166
to continue the current policy of federal funds only when an
abortion is needed to save a woman's life.
   Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., chairman of the subcommittee that
handled the spending bill, pleaded with his colleagues to accept
defeat and help enact the overall measure.
   ``We're talking about a House that we're 50 votes short in.
We're talking about a president that's going to veto the bill.
We're talking about a clock that's ticking,'' Chiles said. ``You
can stand on principle forever and you'll have nothing, if you
don't know when you have to close that gap.'''
   The Senate voted 73-19 in July to expand Medicaid to pay for
abortions in rape or incest cases that are promptly reported.
States would have had the option of retaining the current, more
limited policy.
   The abortion provision was part of the $140 billion
Labor-HHS-Education measure for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1.
The bill contains money for medical research, job training, college
loans and programs for disadvantaged children, among many other
items.
   In a Sept. 7 letter to congressional leaders, President Reagan
reiterated his intention to veto the entire package if it came to
him with the Senate's abortion provision.
   ``The Senate language would permit the use of federal funds for
the salughter of unborn children, depriving the innocent of the
most basic of civil rights _ the right to life,'' Reagan wrote. ``I
urge the Congress to vote to protect the lives of America's unborn
children.''
   The rhetoric on the Senate floor Tuesday was equally intense.
   Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., a social worker, said she vividly
recalls the coat-hanger abortions suffered by poor women without
access to the high-priced society doctors willing to perform
underground abortions.
   ``Abortion is a legal medical procedure that is now available to
women who are well-off. Denying it to poor women is discrimination,
pure and simple,'' she said. Mikulski also said that making a woman
bear the child of her attacker is ``grotesque and inhumane.''
   But Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., argued that a child conceived by
rape is not ``any less of a human being than one who is not ... One
atrocity ... doesn't justify another. Rape doesn't justify murder.''
   Sen. Lowell Weicker, R-Conn., who launched the crusade for wider
federal abortion coverage, excoriated the administration for
pressing Congress to the wall on the issue.
   ``They're going to use their last gasp and their last piece of
political capital'' to deny abortions to rape and incest victims,
Weicker charged. ``What a legacy for an outgoing president.''
   Weicker, who is up for re-election this year, acknowledged in
advance that he was beaten on the floor vote. But he added, ``I
think it's important that the record be established ... so people
understand how they can respond on Election Day.''
   The National Right-to-Life Committee termed the Senate and House
votes ``a sharp setback for the pro-abortion movement groups'' and
said the administration's support had been ``extremely helpful.''
   Fourteen states and the District of Columbia pay for Medicaid
abortions but only receive federal reimbursement in
life-threatening cases. The Senate vote in July was the first time
since 1981 that either chamber of Congress had approved more
liberal eligibility.
</TEXT>
