<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFiresRdp     09-13 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires Rdp,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cool Weather Continues In Yellowstone</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Sierra Fires Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Marines sent to
help battle forest fires that have charred nearly 1 million acres
of Yellowstone National Park arrived Tuesday as the wet weather
that has helped quiet flames began to lift.
   The Marines will help bolster sagging firefighter numbers in the
park and provide relief for fire crews that have been on fire lines
for some time, said Bob Valen of the National Park Service.
   ``We knew we were losing our crews,'' he said. ``Some of them
have been out there way past the usual 21-day assignement. Some
need to get back to college. So we're rotating a lot of crews out.''
   About 550 Marines flew into West Yellowstone, Mont., from Camp
Pendleton, Calif., to help the estimated 7,200 firefighters still
in the park battling fires that have plagued northwestern Wyoming
since early July.
   However, Marines will have received only two days of training
before they are placed on fire lines and will have to be
accompanied by seasoned firefighters, Valen said, putting
additional pressure on fire personnel.
   In all, 1,200 Marines are being sent, with 1,400 Army soldiers
due from Fort Lewis, Wash., to double the number of military
personnel assigned to the fires.
   By Tuesday, the fires had blackened 939,270 acres of the 2.2
million-acre park. Fires in the national forests and parks
surrounding Yellowstone in Wyoming, Montana and Idaho bring the
total burned acreage to 1.4 million acres.
   Fires also burned Tuesday in northern California, where 8,000
people were evacuated from communities in an area northeast of
Sacramento; Oregon, Washington and Utah, which had its last big
fire almost under control at 8500 acres. Washington state's biggest
fire, in Colville National Forest, was declared contained at 20,126
acres.
   Controversy has surrounded the Yellowstone fires because of the
Park Service's ``let burn'' policy, of not fighting most fires that
start naturally. In past years such fires have remained small, but
critics blame the policy for letting fires get out of control in
this unusually dry summer.
   President Reagan said Tuesday he had not been aware of the
policy, but said Interior Secretary Donald Hodel told him ``we were
withdrawing this policy.''
   Colorado Gov. Roy Romer said Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis would join him, Wyoming Gov. Mike Sullivan, Montana
Gov. Ted Schwinden and Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus on Thursday to
survey fire damage in Yellowstone and discuss policy.
   Romer said Dukakis was changing his campaign schedule for the
meeting. Dukakis' campaign headquarters in Boston had no immediate
comment about any Yellowstone appearance, said a media assistant,
Tripp Jones.
   Rain that had fallen on parts of Yellowstone since Saturday
tapered off Tuesday, but had continued longer than expected. The
forecast called for partial clearing by Wednesday and for
temperatures to rise to the low 70s by Thursday.
   But the weather remained cool enough Tuesday that officials
began distributing cold-weather gear donated by residents of
communities around Wyoming to firefighters.
   Few firefighters had been prepared for the cold, wet weather
that limited fire activity and the Salvation Army and other
organizations started collecting coats and other clothing to send
to fire camps.
   Firefighters continued to take advantage of the cool weather to
strengthen fire lines in anticipation of the warmer, drier weather.
   ``The fires are still a threat, we are not out of it yet,'' said
fire information officer Sonya Capek. ``We know there is some more
fire time left in the season, but hopefully it won't be as
intense.''
   Along the north side of the park in Montana, school resumed
Tuesday in Gardiner, the park's northern entrance, after being
closed Monday, but an evacuation plan was ready in case fires
advanced, said Janet McBride of the Gallatin National Forest.
   Near Cooke City and Silver Gate just outside the park's
northeast tip, rehabilitation work has already begun along fire
lines flanking the 81,400-acre Storm Creek fire, which threatened
the towns for several days last week.
   Information officer Ted Coffman said crews were smoothing dirt
over bulldozed lines, repairing creek drainages and planting some
fire lines.
</TEXT>
