<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gorbachev     09-13 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Blames Local Officials for Siberian City's Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev got an earful of complaints
about housing and food problems in Siberia for the second day in a
row Tuesday, and then tore into local officials for mismanagement.
   ``I felt that it's already impossible to talk to the people,''
the Soviet leader said in a meeting with local officials in the
city of Krasnoyarsk.
   ``Wherever I was, on the street in a factory, or here, the
people are simply at your throat. And I think they're right.''
   His comments were included in an hourlong report about his visit
on the Soviet television evening news program ``Vremya.'' The visit
has received heavy TV coverage, emphasizing the importance of his
message.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass said KGB chief Viktor
Chebrikov, also a member of the ruling Communist Party Politburo,
discussed housing and other problems of everyday life on Tuesday
with workers in the Far East port of Vladivostok.
   The public appearances by both men seemed to be part of a
Kremlin effort to show concern about poor living conditions.
   Gorbachev has made the issue of improving the daily lives of
average Soviets a key element of his policy of perestroika, or
restructuring of Soviet society. He has said he is not satisfied
with the efforts made so far.
   The Politburo has called for building enough new housing to give
every family its own apartment by the year 2000.
   Local officials tried to explain their approaches to solving the
region's problems, but were clearly embarrassed by Gorbachev's
criticism.
   One Krasnoyarsk official told Gorbachev that Krasnoyarsk
residents receive the government's recommended yearly allotment of
154 pounds of meat, but the Soviet leader retorted that people
laugh at such standards.
   He said Chinese and Japanese eat much less meat, ``but everyone
who goes there says everything is on the shelf to buy. That's the
story. People are laughing at these scientifically based norms.''
   Soviet citizens shown on televised reports of Gorbachev's
frequent visits around the country usually praise his policies, or
ask uncritical questions.
   But Gorbachev ran into loud complaints about life in Krasnoyarsk
upon flying to the Siberian city, about 2,000 miles east of Moscow,
following a six-week vacation.
   He said the slow rate of development in the huge Krasnoyarsk
region was a constant topic of concern in Moscow. The region
encompasses one-tenth of the entire Soviet Union, produces half of
its coal and 20 percent of its forest products.
   Gorbachev said the government has invested billions of rubles in
the area and is getting little in return.
   He told workers at the Khimvolokno synthetic fiber factory in
Krasnoyarsk that the Politburo was giving special attention to a
shortage of kindergartens.
   Tass quoted one worker as shooting back: ``We have
kindergartens! We don't have housing, and the medical facilities
are bad.''
   Gorbachev heard similar complaints Monday when he stopped in
Yemelyanovo village on his way to Kransoyarsk from the airport
after arriving from Moscow.
   ``We have no hot water! You do what you can to wash!,'' one man
shouted at the 57-year-old Communist Party chief.
   ``I'll tell you right off, comrades, that we cannot count on
successful perestroika if the people ... (have) got so many
problems piling up to form a single big problem, that of inadequate
social amenities,'' Gorbachev said.
   He spoke frequently about environmental problems, criticizing
``gigantomania'' _ the propensity to build huge factories and power
stations regardless of their impact on the environment.
   Too often projects ``carried out under the flag of Communism
threaten nature, and the interests of the people are considered
last,'' he said.
   Tass said that on Chebrikov's visit to Vladivostok, workers at
the Dalvostok ship repair yard complained about work and living
conditions, medical care, shortages of consumer goods and cultural
amenities.
</TEXT>
