<HEAD>Miss America No. 1 in TV Heart</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 1 graf at end to UPDATE with highest rating yet for Fox.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There she is, No. 1 in the weekly Nielsen
ratings, Miss America on NBC.
   NBC estimates that between 50 and 55 million viewers watched all
or part of ``The Miss American Pageant'' on Saturday night. It was
the highest-ranked pageant since 1982's was No. 1.
   This year's pageant rated 22.3 with a 44 share, an improvement
over last year's, which had a rating of 20.4 and a 42 share,
according to the A.C. Nielsen Co. The highest-rated pageant was in
1986 when it got a 23.0 rating and a 44 share.
   Each rating point represents 886,000 homes with televisions. The
share is a percentage of sets in use.
   The other two networks ran college football games against the
pageant that ended up ranked 59th and 60th, respectively.
   The two NBC shows that preceded Miss America on Saturday ranked
second and third in the weekly ratings. One of them was especially
good news for NBC, the preview of a new show, ``Baby Boom,'' based
on the movie by the same name and starring Kate Jackson as an
executive who inherits a baby. It ranked third. It had preceded
Miss America and followed ``Golden Girls,'' which was No. 2 in the
ratings. NBC said the ``Baby Boom'' rating was the highest this
season for the network in that time period.
   The rest of the top 10 were: ``The Cosby Show'' NBC, ``Monday
Night Football _ Washington vs. New York Giants'' ABC, the Bob Hope
Special on NBC, ``Full House'' on ABC in its Tuesday time period,
``Who's the Boss?'' ABC, ``Cheers'' NBC and ``227'' NBC.
   For the week ending Sept. 11, NBC won with a 12.6. ABC was
second with 11.2. CBS was third with 9.3. It's the 51st week since
the season began last September, and NBC has a season-to-date
rating of 14.5 to CBS' 12.2 and ABC's 12.1. NBC has placed first in
45 out of 51 weeks.
   The lowest-rated prime-time shows were: ``Blacke's Magic,''
``ABC Saturday Morning Preview,'' ``Funny People,'' ``Michigan Vs.
Notre Dame,'' ``Nebraska Vs. UCLA,'' ``Highwayman Special,'' ``48
Hours: Smoking War,'' ``First Impressions,'' ``Frank's Place'' and
``Tickets Please.''
   The evening news race was even tighter than usual, perhaps
partially due to the New York CBS affiliate moving the ``CBS
Evening News'' to 6:30, putting it against ABC's ``World News
Tonight.'' ``NBC Nightly News'' is on its own in New York at 7. New
York represents about 7 percent of the total television audience.
   But a lot of stations pre-empted network news last week for the
Jerry Lewis telethon, and that skewed the numbers. ABC News said it
had an ever lower station clearance because of ``Monday Night
Football,'' 96 percent to 97 percent for NBC and 98 percent for CBS.
   CBS and ABC's ``World News Tonight'' tied with a rating of 9.5.
``NBC Nightly News'' had a 9.4. Each of the three got a 20 share.
   Fox Broadcasting recorded the highest rating yet for its
prime-time series when ``America's Most Wanted,'' with got a 9.0
and ranked 43rd among all network shows. Two other Fox shows,
``Married ... with Children'' and ``21 Jump Street'' also landed
high enough in the ratings to out-rank several network programs.
</TEXT>
