<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeacherTest     09-13 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher Test,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Commission Says Teacher Test Biased</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission has ruled that a literacy test all Texas teachers were
required to pass to keep their jobs discriminated against teachers
who were black or over 40.
   State officials said they do not agree with the ruling and plan
to negotiate with the EEOC in an attempt to modify or reverse the
decision.
   A summary of the EEOC ruling was released by the Texas State
Teachers Association.
   ``We said all along that the test was discriminatory toward
blacks and older teachers,'' said Ollie Besteiro, vice president of
the Texas State Teachers Association.
   ``This means that school districts will have to go back and
review their records to see which former teachers might be eligible
for reinstatement, back pay or pension adjustments,'' Besteiro said.
   In the spring of 1986, teachers and school administrators had
two chances to pass the Texas Examination of Current Administrators
and Teachers, or TECAT.
   Out of the estimated 200,000 teachers and administrators in the
state, 1,875 failed the test and were not qualified to work in
Texas schools that fall.
   ``Failure rates for blacks and older persons indicated that the
TECAT adversely impacts on blacks and persons within the protected
age group under (federal law) who were either applicants or
employees for teaching positions in the Texas public school system
in 1986,'' the EEOC said.
   State figures showed a passing rate for whites of 99.9 percent,
compared to 98.9 percent for Hispanics and 95.4 percent for blacks.
   State education Commissioner William Kirby challenged the EEOC
decision, said the same statewide results showed that 99.29 percent
of educators under age 40 passed the test, while 99.64 percent of
teachers over 40 passed.
   ``Older educators did better on the test than younger ones. The
results clearly refute the contention that the test discriminated
against individuals on the basis of age,'' he said Tuesday.
   ``The test was a fair and accurate measure of the examinees'
basic reading and writing skills that was in no way influenced by
race or age,'' Kirby said.
   He said another federal agency, the Office of Civil Rights, had
looked at the test and ``found no evidence whatsoever of racial
discrimination.''
   The EEOC ruling was made in response to complaints filed by
several of the failed teachers against their school districts, the
state and the State Board of Education, which approved the content
and passing score of the exam.
   The teachers association represented the teachers before the
EEOC.
   David Thompson, legal counsel for the Texas Education Agency and
the State Board of Education, argued the EEOC erred in its findings
about the literacy test.
   ``We don't think their findings are factually or legally
valid,'' he said. ``I think they got their facts wrong and failed
to consider some legal precedents that affect the case.''
   State attorneys are negotiating with EEOC officials before
taking any action, said Thompson.
   Kirby said EEOC officials had asked for additional information,
including the civil rights report. ``We are confident they will
revise their decision when they review the complete information,''
he said.
</TEXT>
