<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EasterSentencing     09-13 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Easter Sentencing,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Easter, Sons Ordered To Serve Life In Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Tuesday sentenced a woman and her
three sons to life in solitary confinement at separate prisons so
they ``will understand the pain of separation'' felt by the
families of the three police officers they killed.
   Wayne County Circuit Judge Richard P. Hathaway also said he
wished he could have imposed the death penalty on Alberta Easter
and her sons George, Roy and William Lemons.
   Michigan does not have the death penalty.
   Easter and her sons killed three Inkster police officers during
an 11-hour hostage siege on July 9, 1987.
   Sgt. Ira Parker and officers Clay Hoover and Daniel Dubiel were
killed when they tried to serve a bad check warrant on Easter. All
three were taken hostage in adjoining rooms of the motel in the
Detroit suburb, where Easter and her sons were staying, and were
found dead of multiple gunshot wounds when the four surrendered.
   ``The actions on July 9 are a disgrace to the word family. I
only wish the victims' families could step forward and sentence the
defendants instead of the court,'' Hathaway said.
   In a 10-minute statement to the court, Easter passionately
maintained her innocence.
   ``Our blood is on your hands. You pray for us and our lives,''
she said.
   All three sons expressed remorse for the slayings but maintained
their innocence.

</TEXT>
