<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan-ChildCare 1stLd-Writethru a0713 09-13 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Child Care, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Democrats Would `License' Grandmothers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs of Dodd reax after 8th graf, ``And that;''
notes in 11th graf that subcommittee headed by Dodd; corrects
``qualification'' to ``qualifications'' in last graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Tuesday that Vice
President George Bush's child care plan would help provide children
with ``tender, loving family care'' while the Democratic plan
favored by Michael Dukakis would lead to ``licensing grandmothers.''
   Bush, the Republican candidate for president, has proposed a
plan to give tax credits of up to $1,000 to assist families with
child care. The money could be used either to pay for outside child
care or to enable a mother to stay home and take care of her
children instead of working.
   Dukakis, the Democratic presidential candidate, has endorsed a
bill by Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., providing for the federal
government to reimburse providers of child care. The providers
would have to meet federal standards in order to receive the funds.
   Dodd said recently that Bush's proposed tax credit was ``as
likely to be used for household expenses'' as for care of children
and would fall far short of the $3,000 average annual cost per
family for child care. He also said it would fail to repay the
wages lost by a mother who stays home.
   But Reagan, speaking at a Rose Garden ceremony at which he
signed a proclamation setting the current week aside as National
Hispanic Heritage Week, said Bush's plan ``will allow parents to
choose among a variety of options if they need child care
assistance.''
   ``Experts tell us what common sense always has _ the best people
to take care of children are family members,'' the president said.
``And that's the kind of care that George Bush's plan will help
provide _ tender, loving, family care.
   ``Now, compare this plan with the one offered by the liberals.
They've written a bill that gives assistance not to the parent, but
to the person who provides the care. And why? Because they want to
make sure that they have control over the kind of care your child
receives.
   ``And that means if you want to leave your child with his
grandmother during the day, she will have to be licensed under
federal standards if she's to be given assistance for helping to
raise her grandhild. Licensing grandmothers. Can you believe it?
Well, I think it's terrible, and I don't think the American people
are going to stand for it.''
   Dodd commented, ``No one is worried about the kinds who are left
in their grandmother's care; in a perfect world, every infant and
every young child would have a parent or grandparent who could stay
at home and look after him.
   ``What we are worried about and what the Act for Better Child
Care Services will address is the millions of children whose
parents don't have that option, who work for a living and have to
leave their kids in the hands of strangers _ in day care centers
and family day care homes. That's where we need at least some
minimum health, safety and competency standards.''
   Jason Isaacson, press secretary for the Senate subcommittee on
children and the family, headed by Dodd, said it was true that a
grandmother would have to meet federal standards in order to
receive funds under the bill.
   ``How else can you design a program that receives federal
funds?'' he asked. ``You just can't give federal funds out without
some assurance that they are not going to be used for child neglect
and abuse. We are not worried about grandmothers; we are worried
about 16- and 17-year-olds and people who have no training and no
qualifications.''
</TEXT>
