<DOCNO> AP880913-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1954EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ShuttleDanger     09-13 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Danger,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Says Most Spectators To Be Moved Away From Shuttle
Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spectators and journalists in the traditional
shuttle launch viewing area have one chance in a thousand of being
killed from an out-of-control rocket booster, the Air Force said
Tuesday.
   For that reason, said Col. Larry Gooch, visitors and more than
half the journalists expected for the Discovery liftoff later this
month will be placed at a site 6{ miles away from the launch pad,
instead of the usual 3{ miles.
   The chance of being killed by an exploding booster at the more
remote site is hundred times less _ or, one in 100,000 _ said
Gooch, the commander of the Eastern Space and Missile Center at
Cape Canaveral, Fla.
   The Air force is responsible for safety in the entire area which
is dotted with launch pads.
   More than 3,600 members of the news media already have applied
for credentials and the total is expected to rise to more than
4,000, said NASA public affairs chief William Sheehan.
   He said all news media who need to be at the close-in press site
at the moment of launch will be accommodated, the maximum number
being about 1,800. The journalists who will be moved will be those
who don't have immediate deadlines, such as weekly newsmagazines,
Sheehan said.
   He issued guidelines for credentials: as many as 40 for each of
the major television networks, 10 for each wire service, two each
for daily newspapers, six each for small television networks, four
each for radio networks, three each for individual television
stations and two each for individual radio stations.
   The rest of the credentialed journalists will be put at the
remote site, where there are no telephones and only minimal
services. The general public, which has turned out a million strong
for some past launches on the roads near the Kennedy Space Center,
will not be affected because admittance to the center is restricted.
   The changes were ordered, Gooch said, because the booster
rockets did not tumble end over end when the Challenger exploded,
but instead continued to fly ``in a missile mode.''
   In the case of the Challenger, they went out over the sea. But
if they had returned to land, they would have had to be destroyed
by command of the range safety officer, scattering shrapnel over
the area, Gooch said.
   ``We can never guarantee absolute safety but we can minimize the
risk by minimizing the number of folks,'' said Gooch.
   Jay Greene, a veteran shuttle flight director and chairman of a
NASA risk analysis team said, ``The risk hazard hasn't increased
since (the Challenger accident) ... we understand the risk better.''
   Asked if the Air Force was imposing censorship under the guise
of public safety, Gooch replied: ``I believe we are addressing the
safety issue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1955EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LabLicensing     09-13 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lab Licensing,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes Legislation to Require Federal Licenses for Medical
Labs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday approved legislation that
would for the first time require all medical laboratories _
including nearly 100,000 such labs in doctors' offices nationwide _
to be federally licensed.
   Such laboratories perform four billion to six billion tests a
year for diagnosis and monitoring of disease, and some have been
criticized because of rushed procedures that can lead to mistakes.
   Under the bill, passed on a voice vote, all medical labs would
have to meet quality control, personnel and equipment standards and
would be subject to penalties for violations.
   All laboratories would be licensed for two years at a time,
would have to pass proficiency tests and would have to meet
specific, stringent standards for evaluations of Pap smears which
are used to detect cervical cancer.
   There have been charges that private labs that process thousands
of Pap smears daily have been careless in efforts to maximize
profits and on occasion failed to spot cases of cancer.
   Backers of the legislation said there are some 4,500 independent
labs in the United States, 6,600 hospital laboratories and 98,000
labs in doctors' offices. The labs would be required to pay
issuance and renewal fees for their federal certificates.
   The measure now goes to the Senate for further action. The
Reagan administration has not expressed a position on the bill.
   Current law subjects hospital and independent laboratories to
regulation, but does not affect labs in physicians' offices. The
bill would require doctors'-office labs to be certified in order to
receive reimbursement for Medicaid and Medicare cases beginning in
1990.
   Certain relatively simple tests done in doctors' offices, such
as pregnancy tests, diabetes tests and certain urine tests, would
be exempted from the legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
