<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Hostages     09-13 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Hostages,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany Vows to Help Win Freedom Of Other Hostages</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German government, citing its
good ties to Iran and Syria, promised Tuesday to seek freedom for
other foreign hostages in Lebanon following the release of a
Frankfurt businessman.
   Rudolf Cordes, who was kidnapped in Beirut 20 months ago, was
released by his pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem captors late Monday night.
   The kidnappers seized Cordes and another German, Alfred Schmidt,
in January 1987 to try to win freedom for a Lebanese Shiite,
Mohammed Ali Hamdi, now on trial in Frankfurt for the 1985 TWA
hijacking and the shooting death of a U.S. Navy diver. Schmidt, an
engineer, was freed Sept. 7, 1987.
   Just before freeing Cordes, the kidnappers said they would now
try unspecified legal means to win Hamadi's release, but if that
didn't work ``then we shall be obliged to again resort to
violence.''
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher said Tuesday
that no ransom was paid for Cordes, and no deal was struck. West
German officials have also denied that any ransom was paid for
Schmidt's release.
   Genscher said that he had known since Aug. 24 that after months
of diplomatic efforts, Cordes would be freed on Monday.
   ``It was one of the best-kept secrets in Bonn,'' he said in an
interview with the Deutschlandfunk radio station.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl joined other West Germans in rejoicing
over the release of Cordes. Kohl also praised Syria and Iran for
helping to get him free. ``The Federal Government is extremely
happy over the release of Rudolf Cordes,'' Kohl told a Cabinet
meeting.
   Kohl said good relations between Iran and Syria were key
elements in West Germany's success in winning Cordes' freedom.
``Intense contacts with Iran and Syria were a central point in our
efforts (to gain Cordes' release),'' he said.
   Genscher met several times with Iranian officials over recent
months urging Iran to exert its influence over Cordes' kidnappers
to gain his freedom.
   West German officials had also been in contact with Syria, which
has thousands of troops in Lebanon and has been pressuring Shiite
Moslem militants there to release Western hostages.
   Both Genscher and Kohl pledged West Germany's help in trying to
get other foreign hostages in Lebanon released.
   Seventeen other foreigners, including nine Americans, are still
missing in Lebanon and it is believed most are held by pro-Iranian
Shiite kidnappers. Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent
for The Associated Press, is the longest held. Anderson, 40, was
kidnapped in Beirut on March 16, 1985.
   Residents of Cordes' hometown, the Frankfurt suburb of
Fischbach, were jubilant that he was finally coming home.
   ``And now I have only one wish,'' said Mayor Winfried Stephan.
``I hope that Mr. Cordes has been able to withstand the trials of
his captivity. That is the hope of everyone here who knows him and
his family.''
</TEXT>
