<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Abortion,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abortion Rights Group Endorses Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Abortion Rights Action League
endorsed Michael Dukakis for president Tuesday, saying his
appointees to the Supreme Court will ``respect women's right to
decide whether and when to have children.''
   ``Nineteen eighty-eight is truly the year of decision for
reproductive choice in America,'' said Kate Michelman, executive
director of the organization.
   ``Reproductive choice in America has survived eight years of
Ronald Reagan,'' Michelman told a news conference. ``It might not
survive four more years with George Bush.''
   She said Dukakis and his running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas, ``have demonstrated true concern for women, for families and
for the rights of individuals.''
   ``Their appointees are likely to respect women's right to decide
whether and when to have children,'' she said.
   She said Republican nominee Bush ``has abandoned reproductive
choice for the rigid views of the far right.''
   Dukakis says he personally opposes abortion, but believes that
decision that should be left to the woman and her doctor. He has
supported government funding of abortion for poor women.
   Bush supports a human life amendment to outlaw abortion except
in cases of rape, incest or to save the life of the mother. He
supports government funding only to save the mother's life.
 
