<2ND_LINE>AM-Abandoned Babies,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes Bill To Help Deal With Drug-Addicted, AIDS-Infected
Babies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed by voice vote Tuesday a bill
setting up a new federal program to try to figure out what to do
with the growing number of drug-addicted and AIDS-infected infants
abandoned in hospitals.
   The bill is similar to legislation passed Aug. 5 by the Senate.
Minor differences between the two measures will now have to be
resolved before each chamber votes again and sends the bill to
President Reagan.
   The House bill authorizes $10 million in the next fiscal year
for the Department of Health and Human Services to develop a
program to deal with abandoned infants.
   Growing numbers of children are being abandoned in big-city
hospitals, particularly in New York, California, and Florida,
according to the report accompanying the legislation.
   But there is no accurate number of abandoned children available.
In fact, the legislation directs HHS to survey the program and
report to Congress.
   The abandoned babies are children born of mothers who are drug
addicts or infected with the AIDS virus. Both those conditions can
be passed along to infants.
