<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Shultz-Refugees     09-13 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Refugees,470</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Appealing to Vietnam to permit thousands of
people who were detained in re-education camps after the Vietnam
War to leave the country, Secretary of State George P. Shultz said
Tuesday the United States is prepared to accept up to 94,000
refugees during the next fiscal year.
   But Shultz said that number could be reduced to no more than
70,500, in the 1989 fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, if Congress cuts
President Reagan's budget requests.
   ``We want to offer the opportunities of a new home in a new land
to the masses of unfortunates who need and long for these
privileges, as were given to our own forefathers,'' Shultz told the
Senate Judiciary subcommittee which has jurisdiction over the
refugee program.
   Since October 1981, the United States has processed and admitted
to the United States more than 400,000 refugees from Indochina,
200,000 of them from Vietnam, Shultz told the panel.
   But he noted that, ``for reasons not satisfactorily explained,''
the Vietnamese recently suspended cooperation with the United
States on resolving the issues of Americans missing or taken
prisoner of war in Vietnam and the resettlement of Vietnamese who
were sent to re-education camps after the war.
   ``We call upon Vietnam to heal one of the most painful of wounds
remaining from the war _ by responding favorably to the wish of
thousands of re-education camp detainees to be reunited with their
families in the United States or to come with their families to our
country,'' Shultz said.
   ``We hope Vietnam will lift its `temporary' suspension of
cooperation with us on this compelling humanitarian issue,'' he
said.
   Shultz said last year the administration set refugee admissions
numbers that were higher than the funds made avaiilable for the
program by Congress.
   ``This led to confusion and disappointment as the year went on
and the money ran out,'' he said.
   The House and Senate versions of the bill funding the refugee
program contain varying amounts.
   Shultz said that if the final bill provides $338.4 million, the
same amount as last year, that will be enough money to bring in
68,500 refugees, with funds available from other sources to bring
in an additional 2,000.
   A $361.9 million appropriations would pay for resettling 82,000
refugees, with funds avvailable from other federal and private
sources to bring in a total 94,000, he said.
   At the higher level the government would plan to resettle in the
United States 28,000 Vietnamese, including 25,000 Amerasian
immigrants, Shultz said.
   He said that level of funding also would permit resettling
24,500 persons from the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe, 7,000
people from the Near East and South Asia, 3,500 from Latin America
and the Caribbean and 2,000 from Africa with 4,000 refugees from
all areas to be paid for by private sector contributions.
</TEXT>
