<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland     09-13 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Accuses Solidarity of Violating Agreement on Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday the opposition
has broken terms set by Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and the
interior minister that talks on Poland's future be held without
preconditions.
   However, government spokesman Jerzy Urban said he still hoped
the talks would take place and be fruitful. And a member of the
ruling Politburo said on state-run television that the talks still
could begin within the next few days.
   No date has been announced for the discussions, which are to
consider Solidarity's status in addition to the enormous problems
facing Poland.
   Mieczyslaw Rakowski, the Polish United Workers (Communist) party
official in charge of propaganda, said the Politburo was informed
at its normal Tuesday meeting on preparations for the meeting.
   ``We believe that if everything goes well, the round table will
still take place this week,'' Rakowski said.
   Urban complained that resolutions adopted by the opposition
demanded legalization of the trade union Solidarity before the
talks begin.
   ``It was accepted in the talk between (Interior Minister)
Czeslaw Kiszczak and Lech Walesa that talks would be held without
preconditions and limits on subjects,'' Urban said at his weekly
news conference.
   ``This arouses justified doubts about whether some of our
potential partners at the round table really have a will for
dialogue,'' Urban said.
   Urban was referring to a meeting convened by Walesa at St.
Brygida's church in Gdansk over the weekend, where opposition
leaders called on the government to signal its readiness to
``create conditions'' for legalizing the union.
   However, they did not say they considered it an ultimatum.
   Solidarity's information commission responded to Urban's
comments on Tuesday by saying the spokesman ``distorted the
resolutions... None of the aforesaid statements laid down any
preliminary conditions.''
   Urban also said there would be no meeting Wednesday between
Walesa and Kiszczak, as proposed by Solidarity officials, to work
out remaining obstacles to the talks. But the government spokesman
did not exclude a meeting later.
   ``I can rule out, in fact, that this meeting will be held
tomorrow (Wednesday) in view of what I have said about the need for
certain preparations'' for the full-scale talks, he said.
   After nationwide strikes, the government agreed to the
negotiations on Aug. 31 and promised they would cover Solidarity's
future, the broader issue of union pluralism and workers'
grievances.
   Walesa then successfully persuaded strikers to end Poland's
worst wave of labor turmoil in seven years to allow the talks to
begin. The government earlier said that talks would start
automatically once the strikes stopped.
</TEXT>
