<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Kurds Bjt 1stLd-Writethru 09-13 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Kurds, Bjt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0673,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10 Countries Demand Probe Of Chemical Weapons Use</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 10 countries demanding probe, Iraq
saying it unlikely, comments from Secretary of State Shultz,
details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Ten nations have called on the United Nations
to investigate claims that Iraq used poison gas in an attempt to
crush the Kurdish rebellion in its country, an official said
Tuesday.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar conveyed the request
to Iraq's charge d'affaires, Ali Mahmoud Sumaida, said U.N.
spokeswoman Nadia Younes.
   Herbert S. Okun, the second-ranking diplomat at the U.S. Mission
to the United Nations, made the U.S. request Monday to Perez de
Cuellar. Okun acted on behalf of the United States, Britain, Japan
and West Germany, said a spokeswoman for the U.S. mission, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The other nations who requested the investigation were Italy,
Norway, Sweden, Denmark, Finland and Iceland, she said.
   In Baghdad, an Iraqi official said Tuesday his country probably
would not admit the proposed United Nations team to conduct the
investigation.
   ``This is considered a question of sovereignty and therefore I
do not think we are going to accept that,'' said the official, who
demanded anonymity.
   Iraq has denied charges that it used poison gas in a bloody
offensive against Kurdish guerrillas, a minority people living in
northern Iran, Iraq and eastern Turkey who are fighting for a
separate homeland in northern Iraq.
   Iraq acknowledged on July 1 that it used chemical weapons during
its nearly 8-year-old war with Iran but claimed the Iranians had
used them first.
   In Washington, Secretary of State George P. Shultz said Tuesday
the United States has ``compelling'' evidence that Iraq has used
chemical weapons against its Kurdish citizens. But he said the
United Nations should conduct its own probe before being asked to
condemn Iraq for alleged genocide.
   Shultz said the United States reached the conclusion Iraq was
using chemical weapons against the Kurds based on an examination of
Kurdish refugees in Turkey and on ``other evidence which to me
seems to be compelling.''
   About 60,000 Kurds recently fled Iraq to Turkey, citing poison
gas attacks.
   ``I feel our evidence is quite convincing...'' Shultz said.
``But we're not in a position to make that public.''
   The evidence led the Senate on Friday to vote for tough economic
sanctions against Iraq. The measure still must be approved by the
House and signed by President Reagan.
   In Geneva, about 150 Kurds demonstrated outside the U.N. office
Tuesday, calling for the world body to investigate the alleged gas
attacks and shouting ``Saddam, assassin,'' a reference to Iraq's
President Saddam Hussein.
   In Beijing on Tuesday, U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations
Vernon A. Walters said the United States ``is determined the use of
chemical warfare will not become an accepted part of regional
conflicts.''
   Walters spoke to reporters during a tour of Asia to discuss
issues to be considered at the 43rd session of the U.N. General
Assembly, which convenes Sept. 20 in New York.
   In London, the British Foreign Office said it wants an
investigation partly because of State Department evidence of
chemical attacks.
   The Foreign Office said it also based its decision on other
evidence, including reports from Western journalists in Turkey who
have seen Kurdish refugees they say are suffering from poison gas
injuries.
   However, Turkey said Friday it found no evidence of the use of
chemical weapons while examining sick and injured refugees.
   In Tunis, Tunisia, the Arab League said Tuesday that charges of
Iraq's use of chemical weapons were ``fallacious.''
   In Cairo, Egypt criticized the Senate sanctions, and a Foreign
Ministry official said the accusations against Iraq were groundless.
   The U.N. concluded in August following an investigation that
``chemical weapons continue to be used on an intensive scale
against Iranian forces.''
   In March, Iran claimed the Iraqi air force dropped cyanide and
mustard gas bombs on three Kurdish towns in Iraq, killing 5,000
Kurds and injuring 5,000. The towns targeted by the attack had been
captured by Iran.
   The 1925 Geneva Protocol bans the use of chemical or biological
weapons, although their manufacture and stockpiling is allowed to
deter attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 2001EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-OilReserves     09-13 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Reserves,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Proven Reserves Up Substantially, DOE Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proven reserves of U.S. crude oil rose
surprisingly last year, mainly because oil companies upgraded their
estimates of what Alaskan fields can produce, the Energy Department
said Tuesday.
   The department's Energy Information Administration said the
revisions in estimates of existing reserves were the largest ithas
ever recorded.
   Proven reserves amount to oil in the ground that has been
measured, and is considered producable with ``reasonable
certainty'' with current prices and techniques. Many analysts liken
the category to the on-the-shelf inventory in a store.
   Since the amount recoverable depends on price, with
costly-to-produce formations being passed over when prices are low,
proven reserves will fluctuate even if additions to reserves just
balance production.
   As of Dec. 31, the department said, U.S. proven reserves were
27.256 billion barrels, up 1.4 percent or 367 million barrels from
26.889 billion barrels recorded a year earlier.
   Proven natural gas reserves fell 2.3 percent from 191.6 trillion
cubic feet to 187.2 trillion cubic feet, continuing the trend of
the past six years.
   Alaska crude oil reserves increased 503 million barrels with net
upward revisions in estimates totaling 535 million barrels before
discoveries, other adjustments and production of 718 million
barrels. Projects to recover oil normally left in the ground,
``infill'' drilling to increase production from existing fields and
better estimates of field performance all contributed to the
increases, the department said.
   In the lower 48 states, reserves decreased 0.7 percent or 136
million barrels with net upward revisions in estimates of 1.353
billion barrels before discoveries, other adjustments and
production of 2.155 billion barrels.
   Large gross upward revisions in reserves also were recorded in
California, 505 million barrels, and in West Texas, 477 million
barrels, because of ``enhanced recovery'' efforts to produce oil
from existing fields, the department said.
   Overall Alaska reserves increased 7.3 percent from 6.875 billion
barrels to 7.378 billion barrels. Lower-48 reserves decreased 0.7
percent from 20.014 billion barrels to 19.878 billion barrels.
California reserves fell 0.5 percent from 4.734 billion barrels to
4.709 billion barrels and Texas reserves fell 0.6 percent from
7.152 billion barrels to 7.112 billion barrels.
   For the country as a whole, discoveries added 691 million
barrels to reserves in 1987, 29 percent above the 534 million
barrels added in 1986 but 22 percent below the 1977-1986 average.
   A higher average price for the year, $15.41 per barrel vs.
$12.51 for 1986, enabled oil companies to count more oil in the
``proven'' category, the department said.
   Prices are now falling, said Ed Murphy of the American Petroleum
Institute, the principal trade group.
   Though the Alaska gain was larger than he expected and the
lower-48 decline smaller, he expected, ``the downward trend in
reserves over the last four to six years is apparent,'' he said. In
only two years since 1980, when reserves were 29.805 billion
barrels, have reserves increased, 1984 and 1987.
   The upward revisions from enhanced recovery projects ``are the
result of substantial investments made in the late 1970s and the
early 1980s which are just showing up.''
   Such investments are now declining, and the consequent lack of
production and upward revision in reserve estimates will take a few
years to become apparent, Murphy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
