<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Iraq     09-13 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stalled Iran-Iraq Talks To Shift To New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N.-sponsored peace talks between Iran and
Iraq, stalled since they started almost three weeks ago, went into
recess Tuesday and will move temporarily to New York.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar hopes to unblock the
negotiations at U.N. headquarters there.
   U.N. mediator Jan Eliasson of Sweden said both sides accepted an
invitation by Perez de Cuellar to continue direct talks ``soon'' at
U.N. headquarters. He said they agreed to return to Geneva for
subsequent meetings.
   Eliasson has been presiding over the talks since last week as
the U.N. chief's personal representative. He said Perez de Cuellar
invited foreign ministers Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran and Tariq Aziz
of Iraq to meet in New York on Sept. 22. But the Iraqi delegation
said in a statement issued Tuesday night that Aziz could not be in
New York before the first week of October.
   The statement indicated that acceptance of ``one meeting'' in
New York was conditional on agreeing on a binding date for
reconvening the talks in Geneva.
   Eliasson told a news conference earlier Tuesday that both Iran
and Iraq ``seem committed to keep the peace process going'' and
both confirmed that they will continue to observe the cease-fire.
The truce went into effect Aug. 20 after nearly eight years of
fighting and about 1 million dead or wounded.
   The talks in Geneva began on Aug. 25.
   Eliasson conceded that ``on issues of substance there has been
little if any progress'' but said the most important thing at this
stage was that ``the peace process is kept alive.''
   The talks bogged down over differing priorities. Iran wants them
to stick to implementation of U.N. cease-fire resolution 598,
starting with withdrawal of ``all forces to the internationally
recognized boundaries without delay.'' Iraq wants the negotiations
to focus first on clearing the Shatt-el-Arab waterway, its main
link to the sea, and on freedom of negotiation in the Persian Gulf.
</TEXT>
