<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-ForestFires 1st-LdWritethru a0782saidhenoticedtheflags
09-13 0896</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Forest Fires, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0782,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials to Reagan: No Word on When Western Forest Fires Will
Burn Out</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after pvs 19th graf bgng ``Answering
questions...'' to add Fitzwater comment on let-burn policy</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan got a grim report on the
status of the nation's forest fires on Tuesday and was told there
is no way to predict when the blazes will be tamed.
   ``We are fighting with everything at hand,'' White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   The spokesman met with reporters after Reagan was briefed on the
forest fire situation by Interior Secretary Donald Hodel,
Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng and Deputy Defense Secretary
William H. Taft at the White House.
   Fitzwater described their session with Reagan as an ``update''
and said there were no new efforts to be announced following the
session.
   ``No one could give a prognosis of when the fires would be put
out, but it is clear that we have dedicated all of the resources
available and all of our energies, and the goal is the same for
everyone _ and that is, put those fires out,'' Fitzwater said.
   The meeting came as thousands of firefighters continued to
battle blazes in eight states, particularly California, Montana,
Colorado, Idaho, Utah, Oregon and Washington state.
   It also followed harsh words on the government's ``let-burn''
approach to the fires from a usually strong Reagan administration
supporter, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who called the situation ``a
catastrophe.''
   Fitzwater, asked if the president had been given a ``worst-case
scenario'' of the devastation in the briefing, shot back, ``We are
in the worst case.''
   He did note later, however, that some of the officials had
expressed ``some cautious optimism'' about prospects for calming
the fires.
   Hodel, Lyng and Taft had traveled West to review the situation
over the weekend.
   ``The president has been assured that we have been doing
everything possible,'' Fitzwater said.
   He noted that some 30,000 firefighters were involved in battling
32 fires in eight Western states, with approximately 4 million
acres burned.
   With the most recently dispatched military personnel on station
by mid-week, Fitzwater said, some 2,300 soldiers and 22 aircraft
had been sent to Yellowstone National Park alone to battle the
fires.
   ``The president has repeatedly expressed his concern for the
people living in the fire areas, for the welfare of their families,
for their businesses and occupations, and for the hardship that has
undoubtedly consumed their lives,'' Fitzwater said.
   He called the situation ``a natural disaster of unprecendented
proportions'' and said the people in the area and government
officials ``have responded with great selflessness and
determination to get the situation under control.''
   ``We will continue to work tirelessly to put out these fires,''
Fitzwater pledged.
   Earlier in the day, Reagan had said he'd not been aware of a
U.S. Park Service policy permitting some forest lands to burn, and
said that the policy has been scrapped.
   Asked what he thought of the so-called ``let-burn'' policy that
has been carried out by the Interior Department in recent years,
Reagan told reporters, ``I have questioned it. I did not even know
it existed, frankly.''
   Answering questions as he headed back into the Oval Office after
signing the fair housing bill, Reagan said that when Hodel arrived
in Wyoming last weekend, ``he made it plain that ... we were
withdrawing from this policy.''
   Asked how the administration planned to deal with any new
outbreaks of fires, Fitzwater said the ``let burn'' policy had been
dropped in July and that all new fires would be put out.
   The spokesman refused to entertain any discussion of the
criticism of the administration's controversial policy. But he
noted that since the nation has never faced such an outbreak of
fires before, the time ``certainly calls for some review of the
policy.''
   ``It's not a clear case of what's right and what's wrong,'' he
said. ``At this point, what's clear is that the fires are out of
control. ... We have extraordinary drought conditions and there is
no need to argue over policy differences until we come up with the
next firefighting season next year. Right now, its all-out,
fight-the-fires.''
   The government's let-burn policy has been harshly criticized by
House and Senate members from the Western states.
   Hatch, speaking to reporters after visiting the White House,
said, ``We all knew how dry it was and a lot of us were saying,
`Hey, Don't let this burn and they could have contained it at that
time.'''
   Some 8,000 firefighters have worked in past days to dampen fires
in Yellowstone National Park, where the historic fires have charred
939,270 acres of the 2.2 million-acre park since June.
   Referring to the damage done to Yellowstone, Hatch went on:
``Now you have a million acres lost in one of the most important
national park areas in the world. ... It's a catastrophe....''
   Without explanation the senator added, ``I suspect it comes from
just too much extremism in the environmental area and a lot of our
people in the West are very disappointed, very disenchanted about
it.''
   House Republican leader Robert Michel, emerging from a meeting
of GOP congressional leaders with the president earlier, also said
that he had not been aware of the policy. ``This let-burn policy
obviously is going to come under review,'' Michel said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
