<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Jews 1stLd-Writethru   09-13 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Jews, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0728,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker's Hand Seen in Anti-Semitism Purge in Bush Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Bush comments, INSERT two grafs after 17th
pvs, Those who...anti-Semite, picking up 18th pvs, President
Reagan...ethnic votes.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hasty departure of seven advisers to
George Bush with alleged ties to anti-Semitic activities
underscores how firmly James A. Baker III has taken charge of the
Republican nominee's campaign, according to top aides.
   ``Jim Baker is a guy who likes to get things resolved,'' said a
senior campaign official who spoke only on condition that he not be
identified.
   A top Bush adviser said the campaign was ``totally blindsided''
by the allegations of anti-Semitic activities, which surfaced last
Wednesday as the vice president prepared to address a national
B'nai B'rith convention in Baltimore.
   Circulated at that convention were copies of an article in
Washington Jewish Week which raised questions about members of the
the campaign's ethnic coalition. Baker met with Bush that evening
and discussed the smoldering controversy, aides said.
   Tension built over the weekend with a report in The Washington
Post that Frederic V. Malek, a senior Bush operative on the
Republican National Committee, had collected information on Jewish
officials in the Bureau of Labor Statistics for President Nixon in
1971.
   Malek resigned the same day, saying he was quitting for the sake
of the Bush campaign. He acknowledged collecting the data but
denied he had anything to do with the Jewish officials' later
demotions.
   Campaign sources said six members of Bush's Coalition for
American Nationalities who resigned had been approached by campaign
officials and told of Baker's resolve to take ``firm and decisive
action.''
   The situation was spelled out to those involved, said one top
official, and they were asked ``what do you folks want to do?''
   ``These individuals came to this conclusion (to resign) on their
own anyway,'' the official said.
   Five of the ethnic officials resigned Monday. The Bush campaign
announced the sixth resignation on Tuesday, when Radi Slavoff quit
as national co-chairman of Bulgarians for Bush.
   ``It was accepted. I think we're over it now,'' said Bush
spokesman Mark Goodin.
   Slavoff's resignation followed a story in the Philadelphia
Inquirer that identified him as former chief of a Bulgarian group
formed after World War II which consisted of members of the
Nazi-aligned Bulgarian Legion.
   The other five resigned after published reports linked them to
anti-Jewish or fascist activities.
   Bush campaign sources said they had no plans to replace Malek as
deputy Republican national chairman.
   The resignation of Malek and the six ethnic advisers occurred
with a lightning speed that would have been impossible before
Baker, the former treasury secretary and White House chief of
staff, took command of the Bush campaign, aides said.
   Even though Bush vigorously denied that any of the departing
officials were anti-Semitic, the resignations were viewed as a way
to distance the vice president quickly from a potentially explosive
campaign issue.
   Those who resigned said they were leaving to avoid any political
embarrassment to Bush, not because there was any substance to the
allegations of anti-Semitism.
   Bush, speaking Tuesday aboard Air Force Two, expressed
irritation at the allegations, saying: ``We are going through an
interesting period here, without hard evidence on various things. I
don't like the allegations about people, and I don't like it being
injected into the campaign.''
   Bush refused to say whether Malek would be given a position in a
Bush administration, but said he had ``a lot of confidence'' in
Malek.
   President Reagan declared Tuesday that ``there isn't one iota of
discrimination'' among members of the coalition created to court
ethnic votes.
   Reagan told reporters at the White House he believed the ethnic
advisers resigned ``because they didn't want to harm the campaign.''
   Before Baker's arrival, the Bush campaign was managed by a
committee of six advisers and marked by frequent squabbles between
Bush's campaign officials and his vice presidential office.
   Aides said Baker quickly established new lines of authority.
   Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of staff, and Lee Atwater, the
campaign manager, had shared overlapping responsibility for Bush's
overall campaign activities in the past.
   Under Baker's reorganization, Fuller is responsible only for
scheduling and Atwater for political activities, the sources said.
</TEXT>
