<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1858EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti-Priest     09-13 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Priest,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Priest A Hero To Poor, Villain To Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERRE-YVES GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jean-Bertrand Aristide is
a hero to the poor and hated by the government, a target of both
adulation and assassination for his outspoken criticism of Haiti's
military regime.
   The Roman Catholic priest was saying morning Mass last Sunday
when 20 to 30 thugs armed with knives, machetes and guns burst into
the St. Jean Bosco church in Port-Au-Prince and randomly
slaughtered worshipers.
   Six people were confirmed dead and 77 wounded, witnesses and
hospital officials said.
   Despite the carnage, witnesses said parishioners surrounded the
priest and protected him with their bodies, sweeping him to safety
and into hiding. Aristide is perhaps the most popular figure among
Haiti's slum-dwelling masses.
   During his sermons, in which he vigorously denounced army terror
and atrocities, his small, cement-block church in the La Saline
slum was regularly packed with exuberant, sometimes hysterical
supporters. He has often led them into the streets for
demonstrations during periods of unrest.
   ``Satan is eating us everywhere,'' Aristide said of the army
during a wave of anti-government demonstrations and harsh
repression in June and July of 1987. ``They (the army) are the
savages. Those who load their guns and shoot our children.''
   Since the riots that summer, gunmen in speeding cars have
frequently sprayed gunfire at the wall of his church's compound and
the homes of other Salesian priests close to Aristide.
   On Aug. 23, 1987, Aristide and four other priests were ambushed
near St. Marc on the main north-south highway 60 miles north of the
capital, Port-au-Prince.
   As they returned from a Mass in memory of a recent peasant
massacre, about 40 men armed with machine guns, stones and clubs
attacked their car, injuring two of the priests. Soldiers at a
checkpoint 70 yards away did not intervene.
   Aristide escaped and went into hiding for several weeks
following the incident.
   During a Sunday Mass on Sept. 4, a man entered Aristide's church
with a gun stuck in his belt. The man fled after parishioners
wrestled him to the ground and seized the pistol.
   Aristide's name and those of other opposition leaders are on a
``death list'' of people marked for assassination which has
circulated in Port-au-Prince.
   Aristide, who preaches that Marxism and Christianity are
compatible, has not actually called for an armed uprising, but
repeatedly advocated the overthrow of the Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy's
military government by ``active non-violent struggle.''
   The conservative hierarchy of the church has rejected Aristide's
``notion of class struggle.'' In April the church leadership
apparently attempted to rob Aristide of his power base _ the
capital's slums _ by transferring him to a remote rural parish
north of Port-au-Prince.
   For several days a dozen of his youthful followers occupied the
Notre Dame Cathedral in the capital and went on a hunger strike
which forced the bishops to rescind their order.
   Aristide, in his mid-30s, was ordained by his uncle, Bishop
Willie Romelus of the western town of Jeremie, who is the only
openly anti-military member of Haiti's 10-member Bishops Conference.
   Although the bishops have never called for the overthrow of
Namphy's government, they issued a statement last month that echoed
one made by Pope John Paul II during a tour of Haiti in 1983 which
said ``things must change'' in the impoverished nation.
   The statement protested the expulsion of a priest, the
assassination of human rights leader Lafontant Joseph in July and
accused the military government of authoritarian rule and disregard
for human life.
   Pope John's visit helped crystalize public repudiation of the
dictatorship of Jean-Claude Duvalier, who fled to exile in France
on Feb. 7, 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1859EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PresidentialPolls     09-13 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Polls,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Pulling Ahead in Two New Polls</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two national polls Tuesday found George Bush
pulling past Michael Dukakis in the presidential race, and they
indicated that Bush has scored points by pressing the Pledge of
Allegiance as an issue.
   Bush led by eight points in both national surveys, 47-39 percent
in a CBS News-New York Times poll and 49-41 percent in a Gallup
poll. The Gallup poll found Dukakis suffering his highest negative
rating of the race.
   Two polls released Monday showed a closer race, but two surveys
last week found Bush leading by six and eight points respectively.
Moreover, the new polls found support for Bush on underlying issues
he has been pressing.
   On defense, 28 percent of the probable voters in the CBS-Times
poll said Bush would make the nation stronger and only 4 percent
said he would make it weaker. By contrast, 39 percent said Dukakis
would make U.S. defenses weaker, and just 13 percent said he would
make the nation stronger. The rest in both cases said defenses
would remain unchanged.
   In another measure, Gallup found that 68 percent of the
registered voters it interviewed had heard of the Pledge of
Allegiance issue, and by a 2-1 margin they had a less favorable
view of Dukakis because of it.
   Bush, in what has become a repeated refrain, has criticized
Dukakis for vetoing legislation in Massachusetts requiring teachers
to lead classes in the Pledge. Dukakis said he acted on the basis
of a court opinion that the law was unconstitutional, and he
accused Bush of impugning his patriotism.
   But 70 percent in the CBS-Times poll said teachers should be
required to lead pupils in the pledge. And half of that group said
it should be mandated even if the courts ruled the requirement
unconstitutional.
   Bush also has been stressing environmental issues, traditionally
a strong suit for Democrats, and the CBS-Times poll found him
ranked nearly evenly with Dukakis on protecting the environment.
   The CBS-Times poll even found backing for Bush on an issue
Dukakis had sought to make his own: competence. Fifty-one percent
said Bush would be more competent at managing the federal
government, to 32 percent for Dukakis.
   Overall, the Gallup survey found 40 percent expressing an
unfavorable view of Dukakis, up from 32 percent three weeks ago and
the highest all year for Dukakis in Gallup's poll. Dukakis was
rated favorably by more voters, 53 percent, but Bush bettered him
in both ratings, with 59 percent favorable and 35 percent
unfavorable.
   Dukakis' confidence rating suffered in the CBS-Times poll, but
in that measure Bush's score worsened as well. Fifty-nine percent
said they would be uneasy with Dukakis in an international crisis,
up from 53 percent just after the Republican convention last month.
   Fewer _ 47 percent _ said they would be uneasy with Bush in a
crisis, but that was up 10 points from the post-convention poll.
Also, 45 percent said they would be confident with Bush, down from
51 percent; for Dukakis, 28 percent expressed confidence, little
changed from 29 percent.
   Dukakis continued to lead Bush on one other key issue:
Forty-seven percent said the Democrat would do more to help the
middle class, while 33 percent picked Bush.
   Finally, Bush encountered a low rating on his choice of Sen. Dan
Quayle of Indiana as his running mate. Fifty-eight percent said
they would be worried about Quayle stepping in as president if
something happened to Bush, and just 32 percent said Quayle was
qualified to serve as president.
   The CBS-Times poll was conducted among 1,043 probably voters
from Thursday through Sunday and had a margin of error of plus or
minus 3 percentage points. The Gallup poll was done Friday through
Sunday among 1,003 registered voters and was given a four-point
margin of error.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
