<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis Threat,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged In Threat On Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was charged Tuesday in a federal
indictment with attempting to kill Democratic presidential
candidate Michael Dukakis.
   The three-count indictment said Stephen W. Kimberling, 36, of
Springfield, told an unidentified party that he would shoot Dukakis.
   Kimberling was arrested Sept. 2 as he tried to board a plane at
Springfield Regional Airport. He was carrying a pistol and a 7-inch
hunting knife in his flight bag, authorities said.
   Kimberling has been undergoing evaluation at the psychiatric
unit of the federal prison medical center in Springfield since his
arrest.
   Kimberling was charged Tuesday with carrying concealed weapons,
attempting to kill a major presidential candidate _ a count
carrying a possible penalty of life in prison _ and threatening to
kill a major presidential candidate.
   He appeared before U.S. Magistrate James England shortly after
the indictment was issued Tuesday. England set a Friday hearing at
which Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Jones indicated he would ask
that Kimberling be held without bail.
   England ordered that Kimberling be held until Friday.
   Jones would not elaborate on the information contained in the
indictment.
   ``I can't tell you what the evidence is,'' he said.
   Initial reports indicated Kimberling had threatened Vice
President George Bush, but authorities later discounted those
reports.
   The flight Kimberling attempted to board was headed to Los
Angeles, where the Republican nominee appeared three days later,
and police said Kimberling was carrying documents pertaining to
Bush's campaign.
</TEXT>
