<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Weatherpage-Weather     09-13 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage-Weather,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outer Fringes Of Gilbert Being Felt On The Keys</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Macclenny in 11th graf is correct.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was scattered along the Rockies and across the South and
parts of the East on Tuesday, while the outer fringes of Hurricane
Gilbert brushed the Florida Keys with rain squalls and strong wind
gusts.
   Wind gusted to 39 mph at Key West Airport and tides ran 1 to 2
feet above normal.
   The hurricane's center was located far south of the Keys moving
towards the west-northwest.
   Its maximum sustained wind speed increased to 160 mph.
   This storm had become a category 5 hurricane on the
Saffir-Simpson scale, on which category 1 is the weakest and
category 5 the strongest, the National Weather Service said.
   Showers were scattered over western New Mexico, and northwestern
Wyoming.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended over the northern half of
Texas, the Gulf Coast states, Alabama and Florida.
   Wichita Falls, Texas, had a wind gust to 60 mph during a
thunderstorm that dumped more than 1.5 inches of rain.
   Showers were scattered across southeastern Ohio, northern West
Virginia, southwestern Pennsylvania and northeastern Pennsylvania.
   Storms that dumped 2 to over 6 inches of rain on northern
Alabama on Monday caused the Paint Rock River to crest Tuesday more
than 5 feet above its banks at Woodville, Ala., the weather service
said.
   In northeastern Florida, the Saint Marys River was 2 feet above
flood stage near Macclenny, the agency said. Lower river access
roads were flooded.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 45
degrees at Cody, Lander, Riverton and Yellowstone National Park,
Wyo., to 96 at Thermal, Calif. Tuesday morning's low was 21 degrees
at Truckee, Calif.
   For Wednesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
across eastern New Mexico and the Texas Panhandle, and over eastern
Louisiana, southern Mississippi and the Florida Peninsula.
Scattered showers were forecast over western Colorado, northeastern
Utah, most of Wyoming, and western Nebraska and western South
Dakota. Snow showers were forecast at higher elevations of the
central Rockies. Scattered showers were forecast over northern New
England and northern New York state.
   Highs in the 50s and 60s were predicted over the central
Rockies; in the 60s from northern Minnesota across the northern
section of the upper Great Lakes to northern New England; in the
90s over the inland valleys of California and Oregon, eastern
Texas, the lower Mississippi Valley, the Gulf Coast, Florida, and
extreme eastern sections of the southern Atlantic Coast states;
around 100 over the desert Southwest; and in the 70s and 80s over
the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
