<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kurds-Resettlement     09-13 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kurds-Resettlement,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Official Says Some Kurds Must Be Resettled</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Kurds, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-ranking official said Tuesday that
Iraq is moving many Kurds from small villages for security or
better services, but insisted it is not trying to wipe them out or
change their style of life.
   Kurdish rebel groups and others have denounced Iraq's policy of
demolishing small villages and relocating their population. The
U.S. Senate suggested on Friday such acts were connected with
``genocide'' against the Kurdish people.
   But the official, Nizar Hamdoon, deputy foreign secretary and
former Iraqi ambassador to the United States, said in an interview
that the government has no intention ``to change the life of the
Kurds.''
   Asked about reports of widespread relocations, he said: ``If
you're talking about the border area, the reasons are mainly
security reasons, so that (rebel) infiltration stops.
   ``With development ... it's more feasible to bring people
together to provide better services.''
   Hamdoon said some of the Kurdish rebels who were offered amnesty
after fleeing to Turkey would be relocated if they return.
   ``Obviously, for security reasons we have to relocate some of
them ... but they will be provided with a place within Kurdistan,''
he said, refering to the remote northern region of Iraq where Kurds
live.
   Following a round of fighting that ended in 1975, Iraq
demolished a string of villages along its border with Iran and
moved their people.
   Over the last year, Baghdad-based diplomats said the Iraqi army
demolished scores of other small villages in the mountainous
Kurdish territories and moved the people into towns or new concrete
apartment blocks along main roads.
   The diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
intention seemed to be to keep closer watch on the Kurds and rob
the rebels of village sanctuaries in the rugged mountains.
   Iraq grants its 2.5 million to 3 million Kurdish inhabitants a
form of regional autonomy, including their own assembly and use of
the Kurdish language.
   Rebel groups demand wider autonomy or creation of an independent
state. An additional 6 million Kurds live in Turkey, Iran, the
Soviet Union and Syria.
   Hamdoon noted that none of those countries granted the Kurds any
form of autonomy.
   He said the policy of moving Iraqis from remote villages to
larger towns is not limited to Kurdistan.
   He said similar moves had also taken place in the marshy Misan
province in the south; the Kut region, south of Baghdad, and the
western deserts.
   Observers who visited eastern Kurdistan said they saw only a few
small villages still standing along the main roads, and many old
ones bulldozed.
   But an Associated Press reporter who recently visited the
northern town of Amadiya, 12 miles from the Turkish border, said
relatively few destroyed villages were visible and several small
ones still were standing and populated.
   In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
conveyed to Iraq's charge d'affaires, Ali Mahmoud Sumaida, on
Tuesday a request from 10 nations, including America, that Iraq let
chemical weapons experts go there to investigate claims that Iraq
used poison gas to crush the Kurdish uprising.
   Iraq denies using gas against the Kurds, but previously
acknowledged using chemical weapons against Iran in their
8-year-old war.
   An Iraqi official said in Baghdad that Iraq probably would not
admit such a proposed U.N. team as a matter of sovereignty.
</TEXT>
