<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TheRapture     09-13 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-The Rapture,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Date, Time Of Biblical Rapture Prediction Revised</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who predicted all the faithful
would be called to heaven by Tuesday morning, leaving a warring
world of non-believers, has revised his prediction.
   Edgar C. Whisenant now believes a process called the Rapture
will begin at 9:55 a.m. CDT Wednesday, said Dianne McArthur,
general manager of Christian radio station KAAY at Little Rock.
   Whisenant will not consent to interviews with the secular press,
Mrs. McArthur said. Calls to Whisenant's Rapture 88 Ministries in
Little Rock were greeted by an answering machine, and Whisenant did
not return a call to The Associated Press.
   Whisenant, 56, a retired civil engineer and self-taught Bible
student, has predicted on broadcasts carried by more than 90 radio
stations nationwide that Jesus would ``rapture the church'' _ take
the faithful to heaven _ on Sept. 11, 12 or 13.
   Mrs. McArthur said she spoke with Whisenant on Monday.
   ``I wanted to nail down when he felt like was the last possible
moment before the rapture,'' she said.
   That's when she discovered Whisenant's revision.
   ``All through this, Edgar has been basing things on Jerusalem
time because he feels like God's heart is in Jerusalem,'' Mrs.
McArthur said.
   But Whisenant was reminded Monday of Bible teachings that the
rapture will not occur until the last trumpet blast on earth
signaling the end of Rosh Hashana, the Jewish new year, Mrs.
McArthur said.
   Whisenant figures the last trumpet blast will occur along the
international date line, and that will signal Christians that they
are about ``to meet the Lord in the clouds,'' she said. ``As best
he can calculate it, that looks like 9:55 a.m. Wednesday.''
</TEXT>
