<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SailorFound     09-13 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sailor Found,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sailor Leaner After Ordeal, But Will Sail Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUREKA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventy-five days after he set sail, and
44 days after he was reported missing at sea, Donovan Jones
returned to dry land Tuesday with new respect for canned food and
the Coast Guard.
   The 58-year-old Eugene, Ore., man had planned to sail his
32-foot wooden sloop from Marina Del Rey in southern California to
Oahu, Hawaii. He left in late June expecting to arrive by late July.
   ``I'm not an old salt or anything like that, but I'm not a
novice,'' he said.
   On July 31, his family reported him missing.
   ``I'm married, but I did tell my wife before I left not to call
the Coast Guard. I told her it takes a long time to get anywhere,''
he said during a telephone interview with The Associated Press
minutes after he reached land here in northern California.
   ``I haven't called her yet.''
   Jones' plans went astray shortly after he left. He headed south,
then turned west at 16 degrees north latitude to swing over toward
Hawaii.
   ``And then a storm came along and blew me south and to the west
of Hawaii,'' he said.
   Because of prevailing wind patterns, ``I couldn't come back
(northeast) to Hawaii against the wind, so I decided to come back
to the mainland.''
   With his radio batteries dead, he slowly worked his way through
a small stock of canned food and vitamins. He dragged a line in
hopes of catching fish, but ``I guess I'm not much of a fisherman.''
   He hadn't had a chance to weigh himself yet, but guessed he lost
20 to 25 pounds.
   Early Sunday, when he was just 100 miles off Eureka, a large
storm came up and ripped away his hatch cover.
   ``Everything was in a shambles inside and I was having a hard
time keeping the water out,'' Jones said. Then another sailboat
came along and called the Coast Guard on its radio.
   A Coast Guard helicopter flew out a portable generator to power
Jones' radio and some rations. Then a Coast Guard boat towed him
into Humboldt Bay.
   ``The Coast Guard was really wonderful, and I can't say enough
about them,'' said Jones.
   He isn't ready to give up sailing just because of one
misadventure.
   ``I love the sea, and this hasn't changed me so far as I want to
give it up,'' he said. ``I feel healthier since I've sailed. Life
in the city isn't good for you.''
</TEXT>
