<DOCNO> AP880913-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 2046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WrightInvestigation     09-13 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright Investigation,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethics Panel Seeking Another $550,000 For Wright Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee is seeking another
$550,000 to pay the outside counsel hired by the panel in July to
investigate allegations against House Speaker Jim Wright.
   The committee's contract with the special counsel, Chicago
attorney Richard J. Phelan, provides that he will be paid not more
than $300,000 plus expenses.
   But Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., chairman of the committee, said
Monday that based on costs for professional services provided by
Phelan's law firm through Aug. 31, the committee will exceed the
$300,000 limit before Congress adjourns next month.
   In a letter to Rep. Frank Annunzio, chairman of the House
Administration Committee, Dixon said the extra $550,000 will ensure
that ``there will not be any financial impediment to the efficient
completion of the preliminary inquiry'' into the allegations
against Wright.
   Dixon said he was prohibited by House rules from disclosing
``the status, progress or projected completion date'' of the Wright
investigation, but he said Phelan's law firm has six attorneys
working on the case full time and other attorneys working part
time, ``all of whom are compensated at an hourly rate of $125.''
   The ethics committee, formally known as the Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct, initially received a $400,000
appropriation for fiscal 1988. After the panel hired Phelan to
conduct the Wright investigation, the House approved an additional
$350,000 for the panel.
   The committee, acting on a complaint filed by Rep. Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., voted in June to launch an investigation into six
allegations against Wright, including charges that he used his
office improperly to lobby federal officials and others on matters
in which he had a financial interest.
   The investigation also is focusing on alleged improprieties in
the publication of a book by a campaign contractor for which Wright
received unusually high royalties.
   Wright has denied any wrongdoing and has insisted that he will
be cleared by the investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
