<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-USDues     09-13 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-US Dues,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Hails U.S. Decision To Pay Dues Arrears</HEAD>
<HEAD>With WASHINGTON-dated AM-Reagan-United Nations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
on Tuesday welcomed the U.S. decision to pay in full its U.N.
financial arrears, but added that the world body needs more money
and still faces a financial crisis.
   U.N. officials had said that without the U.S. payment, the
organization would have run out of funds in October and would be
forced to use money meant for salaries to finance a peacekeeping
force in the Persian Gulf.
   Perez de Cuellar told reporters as he left U.N. Headquarters,
``It (the U.S. decision) is a very positive development which I
very much welcome and which alleviates our difficulties.
   ``Of course, it is not the end of our financial problems, but it
will alleviate them very much.''
   The United States is the biggest U.N. contributor and is
assessed one-quarter of the annual regular budget of about $800
million. It has withheld funds for years to protest what it called
the organization's political bias and to compel it to institute
budgetary, political and administrative reforms.
   Perez de Cuellar said that because of the payment, President
Reagan would ``feel much more comfortable'' when he addresses the
General Assembly Sept. 26, but added that the president ``is always
welcome.''
   He said he hoped other nations also would pay their arrears to
the 159-member organization. A U.N. statement on July 31 said 73
nations owe money.
   On Tuesday the U.S. government said Reagan authorized immediate
release of $188 million in U.S. dues to the United Nations. He also
directed the State Department to work on a plan for settling all
past debts of $520 million.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters the
United Nations ``has reformed its operations to the point'' where
Reagan felt he could act.
</TEXT>
