<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HurricaneGilbert-US     09-13 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Gilbert-US,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Coast States Brace for Gilbert's Wrath</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents along the Texas Gulf Coast on Tuesday braced for the
possible onslaught of Hurricane Gilbert, which ripped through
Jamaica and the Cayman Islands with winds of 140 mph before taking
aim at the Gulf of Mexico.
   In Louisiana, oil companies evacuated thousands of workers from
rigs in the gulf, and residents along the coast awaited word on
whether Gilbert would become the second storm to hit them in a week.
   And on the New York Mercantile Exchange, oil futures prices
moved up a bit Tuesday, driven by a rise in gasoline prices spurred
by concerns about the effects of the hurricane.
   ``Oh man, business is really booming,'' said George Shannon, an
assistant manager at a Wal-Mart store in Galveston, Texas. ``We've
got people all over the place right now buying flashlights,
batteries, lamp oil _ everything.
   ``It's very steady and they're not just coming in getting a
handful of stuff _ it's cartloads of stuff.''
   Gilbert, which could hit the Gulf of Mexico by Thursday, reached
Category 5 on the Saffir-Simpson scale of hurricane strength. The
scale lists such a storm as causing catastrophic damage and having
a storm surge of greater than 18 feet.
   ``Everyone's buying plywood,'' Ricky Burge, an assistant manager
at McCoy's Building Center in Galveston, said. ``It's escalating at
this time and it doesn't look like it's going to slow down. Our
business easily has doubled since yesterday.''
   ``Everybody is on standby,'' added Mary Vandewalli, Galveston
County disaster chairman for the Red Cross. ``No matter where it
hits, we're going to get something.''
   Ms. Vandewalli said no shelters would be set up on Galveston
Island and if an evacuation was ordered, people would be sent to
Houston, about 45 miles to the north, and to shelters planned north
of Houston as far away as Conroe, nearly 90 miles inland.
   ``It is not safe to be on the island,'' she said, explaining why
no shelters would be established on Galveston before the storm.
   Elsewhere along the Texas Gulf Coast, emergency preparedness
officials were meeting to plan for the possibility of a storm and
to decide if and when evacuations would be ordered.
   In Louisiana, where last week, Hurricane Florence blew ashore,
oil company officials said they weren't taking any chances with
crews at sea.
   The storm was moving to the northwest about 15 mph.
   ``We began evacuating our offshore drilling personnel yesterday
and we're finishing that up today,'' Shell spokesman Billy
Vehnekamp said. Other companies were following suit.
   Gene Graves, marketing director for Petroleum Helicopters Inc.
in Lafayette, said his company's 18 bases in the Gulf Coast region
were operating at full capacity evacuating the rigs. He estimated
that all the 10,000 or so workers who normally work the gulf would
be evacuated by Wednesday.
   ``I don't think anybody's going to ride this one out, that I'm
sure of,'' he said.
   Vehnekamp said many workers had not yet returned to Gulf rigs
following evacuations before Hurricane Florence hit the southeast
Louisiana Gulf coast last weekend.
   While the oil industry was gearing up for the storm, residents
in areas along the south Louisiana coast were monitoring the
storm's progress.
   ``People have been watching this storm since it was a depression
and they'll be watching it until it comes through,'' said Hayes
Picou, Jr., civil defense director in Cameron, La.
   ``It's too early for us to be doing anything about it,'' he
said. ``Our action will begin tomorrow.
   ``Believe me though, you won't have to tell anyone in Cameron
what to do about it if it comes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
