<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   09-13 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0654,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Kidnapped By Christians For Three Hours</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 12 grafs SUB for grafs 7-24 pvs, UPDATING with Osseiran
comments, descriptive, Sidon fighting.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian militiamen kidnapped the
defense minister Tuesday but freed him three hours later under
pressure from the army. The incident worsened a political crisis
that could reignite Lebanon's civil war.
   Police said the kidnappers, members of the Lebanese Forces
militia, released Adel Osseiran, 83, at 2:40 p.m. after the army
command threatened to storm an apartment building in which he was
being held in east Beirut.
   A police spokesman said Moslem and Christian militiamen traded
automatic rifle fire and rocket-propelled grenades across Beirut's
dividing Green Line after the Shiite Moslem minister's abduction.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified in line with standing
regulations, said at least two gunmen were killed and two wounded
in the fighting, which he described as a ``localized'' incident.
   He said the commander of the Lebanese Forces, Samir Geagea,
received Osseiran after his release and ``apologized to him for the
behavior of the unruly militiamen.''
   ``We denounce such acts in our areas, especially when they
target a personality like Osseiran who is one of heroes of
Lebanon's independence,'' Geagea said in a statement broadcast by
radio stations in east Beirut.
   The silver-haired Osseiran drove from east Beirut to the Alumni
Club of the American University of Beirut in the city's Moslem
sector for lunch after his release.
   The minister, wearing a dark gray suit, told reporters his
captors took him to a ninth-floor apartment in east Beirut's
Ashrafiyeh district.
   ``They prepared coffee for me,'' he said. ``As a matter of fact,
I can say that I enjoyed meeting these people.''
   Osseiran said in English that the kidnappers were members of the
Lebanese Forces from the Christian town of Jezzine in south Lebanon.
   The kidnappers had offered to trade Osseiran for a Christian
parliament deputy, Farid Serhal, who they claimed was kidnapped
Thursday in west Beirut.
   Police said gunmen seized Osseiran in east Beirut at a
checkpoint near the Green Line manned by the Lebanese Forces and
took him to their headquarters.
   An hour later, army commander Gen. Michel Aoun, a Christian,
ordered his 42,000 troops on alert and warned the kidnappers to
release Osseiran ``at once.''
   Aoun has long been at odds with the Lebanese Forces over their
growing dominance of east Beirut and the Christian heartland north
of the capital that has eroded the authority of Lebanon's divided
government.
   The Lebanese Forces claim Serhal, a Maronite Catholic, was
kidnapped by pro-Syrian militiamen of Druse warlord Walid
Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party at a checkpoint south of
Beirut as he drove to Jezzine. They said Serhal was being kept at
west Beirut's Bristol hotel ``against his will.''
   Osseiran's abduction heightened tension between Moslems and
Christians during a political deadlock in efforts to elect a new
president.
   Moslem factions and Christians have been fighting a civil war in
Lebanon for 13 years, ravaging the economy and leaving more than
130,000 dead. Syria is the main power broker, maintaining 40,000
troops in eastern and northern provinces as well as west and south
Beirut.
   In the southern port city of Sidon, fighting broke out Tuesday
between two local Sunni Moslem factions. Police said one person was
killed and seven were wounded.
</TEXT>
