<DOCNO> AP880913-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 2054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DelawarePrimary 1stLd-Writethru a0743 09-13 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delaware Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0743,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recount Begins in Delaware Senate Primary Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with no change in Kent County
recount. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `The recounts...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recount began Tuesday of ballots cast in
Delaware's Democratic primary for the U.S. Senate, after the
discovery of a clerical error that incorrectly tallied 2,800 votes.
   The Kent County Board of Elections conducted its recount Tuesday
and recounts were scheduled Wednesday in the state's other two
counties.
   The Kent County board recertified its ballots when the recount
determined nothing had changed.
   ``We have no change in the results. It's over in Kent County,''
said Donna Harrington, administration director of the board of
elections.
   The recounts were requested by both candidates, civic activist
and millionaire Samuel S. Beard and Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo.
   They are seeking their party's nomination to challenge incumbent
Republican William V. Roth Jr., who is seeking a fourth term. Roth
did not have a primary opponent.
   Beard was declared the winner in Saturday's voting, but election
officials discovered early Monday that he had been given 2,800
votes too many.
   Saturday's results showed Beard with 22,418 votes to Woo's
19,624.
   By Monday night, the unofficial statewide tally showed Beard
trailing by 88 votes, with 20,133 votes to Woo's 20,221.
   Those figures included certified results from Kent and Sussex
counties, which had changed slightly from the counties' reports
Saturday night.
   The 2,800-vote mistake occurred in the 23rd representative
district in New Castle County, where about 280 Democrats are
registered. Beard received 28 votes in the district, but the votes
were recorded as 2,828 in the computer at the county's department
of elections, according to Paul T. Hart, administrative director of
the county Department of Elections.
   Woo, 51, a physics professor at the University of Delaware, was
a political newcomer when he was elected lieutenant governor four
years ago. The native of Shanghai, China, had heavy financial
backing from Asian-Americans nationwide.
   Woo heavily outspent Beard, a millionaire who inherited his
wealth.
   Beard, 49, had the backing of party loyalists and labor. He has
served as chairman for job creation commissions under the past four
presidents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
