<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0720 09-13 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0720,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Asks How Bush Would Measure Up to Gorbachev</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS two grafs of Dukakis comments in Washington</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis questioned on Tuesday
whether Republican rival George Bush is up to dealing with Soviet
leaders at a time when Soviet economic difficulties offer great
opportunities for the United States.
   ``George Bush has been around Washington for a long time, but if
he couldn't stand up to the ayatollah or say `no' to (Panamanian
Gen. Manuel) Noriega, how will he measure up to Gorbachev?''
Dukakis said.
   ``And if he truly believes that J. Danforth Quayle is qualified
to be one heartbeat away from the presidency, how can we trust his
judgment when America's future is on the line,'' he said.
   Dukakis spoke to the Chicago Council on Foreign Relations in
what campaign aides described as a major address outlining his view
of U.S.-Soviet relations. It was part of a week devoted largely to
national security issues by the Democratic presidential nominee,
who is trying to counter the Republicans' depiction of him as soft
on defense.
   Dukakis intensified that effort later at a General Dynamics tank
facility in Sterling Heights, Mich., where he donned a helmet and
rode in a M-1 Abrams tank, the military's top battlefield tank, and
pledged to make strengthening conventional weapons among his top
defense priorities.
   Dukakis stood through the hatch of the tank, his hand resting on
a 7.62 mm machine gun, the tank's turret and cannon spinning, as
the tank was driven at high speed around a grassy field.
   He said the Reagan administration had tried to cut tank
production by one-quarter and asserted that Bush would cut
conventional military spending to finance the Star Wars nuclear
defense program.
   Dukakis planned to address defense and weapons in a speech
Wednesday in Washington. Aides scheduled a stop in Yellowstone
park, to view fire damage, on his way to California Thursday.
   In his Chicago speech, Dukakis said the next president must
``seize the intiative'' in dealing with the Soviets. However, he
said Bush ``has no strategy for testing the limits of what is
called `new thinking' in the Soviet Union.''
   He said the Soviet Union under Mikhail S. Gorbachev has an
economy facing difficulty in providing for its people and that
Gorbachev wants access to Western technology, resources and trade.
   ``Mr. Gorbachev wants to make his country part of the
international economic community,'' Dukakis said. ``What is he
prepared to do in return? Will we allow him to pursue that strategy
unchallenged, or will we have a strategy of our own to rotect
American interests and translate Soviet economic weakness into
improved Soviet behavior in world affairs?''
   Dukakis said he would deal firmly with the Soviets and said
Gorbachev is a Leninist who ``has not abandoned Soviet goals.''
   He said, ``It would be naive to take Gorbachev at his word, but
it would be dangerous to allow his words to go unanswered.''
   Dukakis said he would challenge the Soviets to reduce European
troops, cool regional conflicts, end the spread of nuclear and
chemical weapons and missiles, reject terrorism and allow the
emigration of Jews and other minorities.
   ``Mr. Gorbachev must understand that if there is to be a
fundamental change in the relationship of his country with the
Western world, there must first be a fundamental change in the
balance of forces in central Europe,'' Dukakis said.
   He said he wanted to build on the Intermediate-range Nuclear
Forces reduction agreement and would challenge Gorbachev to
eliminate a Soviet advantage in tanks and artillery in Europe,
``not just by demobilizing those weapons but by destroying them.''
He also said he would seek to have the Soviets withdraw troops
``back into the Ukraine.''
   Dukakis hammered at his theme that Sen. Quayle, Bush's running
mate, was not up to dealing forcefully with the Soviets. He noted
that three vice presidents since 1945 have been propelled suddenly
to the presidency and that all of them later met as president with
Soviet leaders.
   ``Dan Quayle is no Gerald Ford,'' Dukakis said. ``He's no Lyndon
Johnson. And he sure ain't Harry Truman. Can we stake our future on
the hope that he is a match for Mikhail Gorbachev?''
   Dukakis wrapped up the day in Washington, where in a speech to
the Congressional Hispanic Caucus he said Reagan's appointment of a
Hispanic, Lauro F. Cavazos, to Secretary of Education, was too
little too late.
   ``For some people it's enough to wake up after eight years and
create opportunity for one Hispanic,'' he said. ``I want to stand
with you and create opportunity for 20 million Hispanics.''
</TEXT>
