<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-NATO     09-13 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-NATO,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woerner Warns Against Dropping Guard, Sees Larger European Role In
NATO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner said on
Tuesday that Western Europeans will have to spend more for defense
to avert a trans-Atlantic ``slanging match'' between the United
States and its allies.
   Woerner, in his first public speech since taking over as top
political official of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, said
he welcomed Soviet reforms, but doubted they would ``go far
enough.''
   ``We must take account of realities more than intentions,''
Woerner told the Atlantic Council, a private organization. ``Soviet
defense programs have not slowed down.''
   But he added, ``I see more opportunities than risks ahead.''
   The NATO allies should challenge Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev to make more progress toward military stability in
Europe, a global ban on chemical weapons, greater observation of
human rights and deeper economic and scientific cooperation.
   ``The success of the West is the driving force behind the Soviet
leadership's reforms, political as well as economic, but it is
doubtful that they go far enough to overcome the structural
failings of the Soviet system,'' Woerner said.
   ``All this underscores just how wrong, indeed dangerous, it
would be for the alliance to take a leap of faith and to let down
its guard,'' said Woerner who had been the West German defense
minister before taking the alliance post last July 1.
   Woerner said the issue of Europe and Japan assuming a larger
share of the common defense burden had been a central theme in his
first discussions with European leaders, and ``they are committed
to an equitable sharing of responsibility for collective defense,''
he said.
   ``The burden-sharing debate must not be allowed to degenerate
into a numbers game or a trans-Atlantic slanging match,'' he said.
   Woerner said he would work for ``a stronger European pillar
within the alliance'' but added that it was essential for the
United States and Canada to remain committed to the defense of
Europe.
   He said the allies should expand their cooperation outside the
NATO area, an idea that has encountered resistance in Europe.
   ``The Europeans and Canadians do not have the same kind of
superpower responsibilities as the United States, but they do have
a global role,'' Woerner said, citing examples such as providing
aid to the Third World, thwarting Libyan aggression in Chad and
patrolling the Persian Gulf.
   Woerner met for nearly three hours on Tuesday with Defense
Secretary Frank Carlucci and discussed the ``full range of NATO
issues,'' a Defense Department spokesman said. He is to meet with
other U.S. officials this week, including President Reagan on
Friday.
</TEXT>
