<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 2206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BusCrash 1stLd-Writethru   09-13 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0722,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>5 Die, 14 Injured in Rock Slide Bus Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos XSFE1,2; AQ3, LaserGraphic NY7</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The names...' to UPDATE with victims'
identities; INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th to UPDATE with unidentified
toddler and conditions of the injured; picks up 9th graf pvs,
`Rocks ranging...'; ADDS 4 grafs at end to UPDATE with quotes from
passenger</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED MORENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EMBUDO, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A severe thunderstorm may have triggered a
rock slide that sheared off the front of a Greyhound bus, killing
five people and injuring 14, police said Tuesday.
   The accident occurred late Monday as the driver and 20
passengers drove through a mountainous strip of New Mexico Highway
68 above the rain-swollen Rio Grande, about 50 miles north of Santa
Fe. The bus was en route to El Paso, Texas, from Denver, via
Albuquerque.
   A boulder the size of a car's front end tumbled from the
mountain as the bus approached, striking it broadside and
apparently killing the driver instantly, police said.
   ``It sheared the front end of the bus off,'' said state police
Officer Harold Zuni.
   Witnesses said that after the boulder hit, the bus crashed into
several large rocks but remained upright. The rocks probably
prevented the bus from careening off a steep embankment and
plummeting into the Rio Grande, said the Rev. Andrew McComb, a
Dixon Fire Department volunteer.
   ``All we heard were screams,'' said David Fuller, a Mormon
missionary from Toronto traveling with another missionary, Sean K.
Jones. ``People were thrown out of the bus when we hit these rocks
here.''
   The driver was identified as Gaylon Greer Parks, 39, of Denver.
George Gravley, a spokesman for Greyhound in Dallas, said Parks had
worked for the bus company exactly seven years on Monday.
   The dead were identified as Peedjk Akkandi Sridnaran, 59,
Bombay, India; Esther Grimes, 41, who was believed to be en route
with her family to a new home in Arizona from Denver; a 64-year-old
man from Tokyo, whose name was not being immediately released; and
a woman about 18 years old who carried no identification and is
believed to be a Mexican national.
   Authorities still were trying to identify the toddler belonging
to the unidentified woman who was killed. The child, estimated to
be 18 months to 2 years old, was in the Espanola Hospital in stable
condition, and will be placed in the state's custody if relatives
can't be found, officials said.
   Four of the 14 injured were hospitalized in either stable or
satisfactory condition. Ten people were treated and released.
   Rocks ranging from baseball- to file cabinet-size littered the
road near the bus. The owner of an Espanola radio station said the
area had been hit by a powerful storm just hours before the
accident.
   State Police Officer T.R. Rodella said the rain might have set
off the slide. ``It's been raining off and on here all day,'' he
said.
   Fuller said the driver was going only 45 or 55 mph when the
crash occurred.
   ``I felt an impact,'' said Jones. ``All of a sudden I felt
debris coming at us. A bright light flashed, like sparks and
electricity in the front end of the bus, being destroyed.''
   Jones said he and Fuller, the only passengers not injured,
escaped through windows and helped others out.
   Passenger Cruz Sanchez of Houston said he was sitting about six
seats behind the driver when he heard three crashing sounds he
believed were caused by rocks.
   He said he hit the floor and that people were flying around the
bus. He looked next to him and saw a crying baby trapped beneath
some seats, he said.
   Sanchez said he went to the mother and saw blood on her face. He
was unable to feel a pulse and assumed she was dead, Sanchez said.
He said he and another man freed the child.
   ``Children were crying, people were crying, people were lying
down,'' Sanchez said.
</TEXT>
