<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti-Acquittal     09-13 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Acquittal,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Acquits Militiaman Accused Of Killing That Led to Duvalier
Downfall</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A militiaman was acquitted in a
November 1985 slaying which created such public outrage that it led
to the eventual ouster of dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier, Radio
Soleil said Tuesday.
   A criminal court in Gonaives, 100 miles north of Port-au-Prince,
acquitted Cereste Saint-Phard because of insufficient evidence
after three of six witnesses failed to appear at his trial, the
station said.
   Saint-Phard is an ex-member of the feared Tonton Macoutes, a
private militia of terror that kept the Duvalier family in power
for 29 years.
   He was charged with the Nov. 28, 1985, shooting death of
Jean-Robert Cius, one of three high school students killed by
Macoutes during an anti-government demonstration.
   The killing of Cius, Machenson Michel and Daniel Israel in the
playground of their Immaculate Conception High School in Gonaives
fueled anti-government protests that led to Duvalier's flight to
France on Feb. 7, 1986.
   Haiti was taken over by a military junta led by Lt. Gen. Henri
Namphy, who ruled two years. Namphy returned to power in a June 19
coup that ousted President Leslie Manigat, who held the title of
president for only four months.
   Radio Soleil said two of the three witnesses who appeared in
court Monday evening were also former Macoutes under the orders of
Saint-Phard, who was a commander of the Volunteers of National
Security, the formal name of the Tonton Macoutes.
</TEXT>
