<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 2306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile     09-13 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Denounces Banning of TV Spot on Torture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders on Tuesday denounced
the banning of an anti-government campaign commercial describing
alleged torture by President Augusto Pinochet's secret police.
   Pinochet, meanwhile, ordered the cancellation of a
pro-government television advertisement scheduled for Tuesday to
make up for the banning of the opposition's Monday night spot.
   Pinochet, the 72-year-old army commander who seized power in a
1973 military coup, faces a national referendum Oct. 5 on a
proposed eight more years of rule. According to government-approved
rules for the campaign, his backers and opponents each receive 15
minutes of free television time nightly.
   On Monday night, only the pro-Pinochet spot was aired. The
national television censorship board had objected to a one-minute,
55-second segment of the opposition's advertisement that quoted a
federal judge investigating alleged cases of torture by the secret
police.
   Opposition leaders said Wednesday the board offered to let them
substitute a different segment, but they refused. The board then
decided to bar airing of the entire 15-minute spot.
   ``We don't accept censorship,'' Socialist Ricardo Lagos,
co-leader of a 16-party opposition coalition, told a news
conference Tuesday. ``What happened last night helps to remind us
that we are facing a dictator, and not in a fair electoral battle.''
   Andres Zaldivar, a Christian Democrat also leading the
coalition, said: ``It's a dictator's action.''
   The absence of the opposition ad sparked pot-banging and other
demonstrations of anti-government sentiment around Santiago,
especially in working-class neighborhoods.
   ``Pinochet made a big mistake,'' Zaldivar said. ``In trying to
do us damage, he created a reaction in the people that is
overwhelmingly in our favor.''
   Denis Lustig, executive secretary of the censorship board,
called the National Television Council, said it objected to the
segment because ``it attempted to involve the judicial power in a
political campaign.''
   He said at a news conference that the council had consulted the
Supreme Court, which said it had not authorized the judge's remarks.
   The judge, Rene Garcia, was quoted in the advertisement as
saying he is investigating cases of torture involving more than 50
people arrested by the secret police agency, called the National
Information Center, known by its Spanish acronym, the CNI.
   ``It is duly established that they were arrested by CNI agents,
that they were tortured by CNI agents, in CNI jails,'' Garcia
declares in the segment. The segment was extracted from a
television interview Garcia gave months ago, apparently to a
foreign network. In March, he was told by the Supreme Court to stop
speaking publicly about the cases.
   Lagos said the segment had been broadcast in at least 15 other
countries. ``I ask why they refuse to let Chileans see what a
Chilean judge has said, and which can be seen in the rest of the
world?'' he said.
   Orlando Poblete, the Cabinet-rank government general secretary,
told reporters that on Tuesday night only the opposition's
15-minute time slot would be broadcast. The pro-government spot was
being canceled at Pinochet's order to keep the campaign fair, he
said.
   If a majority vote yes in the plebiscite, Pinochet will remain
president until 1997. If most voters reject him, open elections
will be held in a year and he will hand over power to the winner in
1990.
   The government ordered free television time, from 10:45 p.m. to
11:15 p.m. each weeknight and at mid-day on weekends, starting
Sept. 5 and ending Oct. 1.
   Besides the 15 minutes of free time, paid pro-government
advertisements appear several times daily on all TV channels. The
opposition says it cannot afford paid ads, and doubts that the
channels would allow them.
   Pinochet toppled the elected government of President Salvador
Allende and took power Sept. 11, 1973. Allende, a Marxist, died in
the takeover.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
