<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti 3rdLd-Writethru   09-13 0888</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0851,0913</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attackers Burn Second Church, Attack Radio Station</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 17th graf, `Volel and...' with three grafs to UPDATE
with church denials that rivalry between priests led to massacre;
PICKS up 18th graf pvs: The government...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Thugs burned down an empty Roman
Catholic chapel Tuesday several hours after six people claimed
responsibility for a massacre inside another church and threatened
more such attacks.
   The government said it would investigate the attacks, but the
opposition said the military regime instigated them.
   Later Tuesday, unidentified men attacked Radio Cacique _ which
often airs opposition opinions _ slightly injured three employees
and made off with broadcasting equipment, Radio Haiti Inter
reported.
   Radio Haiti Inter said police did not respond to a telephone
call for help from Radio Cacique.
   Opposition figures charged that the military regime of Lt. Gen.
Henri Namphy was behind the pre-dawn blaze Tuesday that leveled the
Chapel of Immaculate Conception in Port-au-Prince's Cite Soleil
slum area.
   Reporters who arrived on the scene said they were chased away by
hoodlums.
   The reporters said the hoodlums included one of the six people
who appeared on television Monday night to boast about his
participation in the Sunday massacre at the St. Jean Bosco Roman
Catholic Church.
   At least six people died and 77 were wounded when thugs armed
with machetes and guns burst into St. Jean Bosco during a Mass and
attacked parishioners while police and soldiers stood by outside,
witnesses said.
   The pastor of the St. Jean Bosco church, which was burned after
the slaughter, is Rev. Jean Bertrand Aristide, a critic of Namphy's
military government and a popular figure among Haiti's
povertry-stricken masses.
   ``The government has committed a genocide on an unarmed people.
It is for the international community to put a stop to it,'' Sylvio
Claude, head of the Christian Democrat Party and one of Haiti's
most popular opposition leaders, said on Radio Metropole on Tuesday.
   ``After all the evidence I have heard on the St. Jean Bosco
affair it is clear that the government organized it,'' Claude said.
   The five men and a woman who appeared on government television
Monday night claimed they were supporters of a rival priest, the
Rev. Arthur Volel of the Chapel of Immaculate Conception.
Opposition leaders said the story was concocted by the government
to cover the real reason for the attack.
   ``The story of bloody rivalry between priests is baseless. It is
a blatant attempt by the government to mislead the public,''
Jean-Jacques Honorat, head of the Haitian Center for the Defense of
Human Liberties, said Tuesday.
   The six who appeared on television made no attempt to hide their
identity and spoke on the government-controlled network without
apparent fear of arrest or reprisals. They also spoke on radio.
   They claimed the violence was related to an internal conflict
within the church and threatened ``a heap of corpses'' at any Mass
celebrated by Aristide.
   Volel and Aristide, members of the Salesian order, are
well-known in Haiti for their work with the urban poor. Volel
denied on private Tele-Haiti Tuesday that there was a rivalry.
   Rev. Jacques Mesidor, superior of the Salesian Order, said on
Radio Soleil: ``We denounce all worn-out trickery and maneuvers
which would lead people to believe that everything which happened
is a result of internal conflict between priests.''
   Rev. Joseph Lafontant, auxiliary bishop of Port-au-Prince,
denounced the attacks. ``In the name of Jesus Christ we say stop
this destruction,'' Lafontant said on Radio Soleil, a church-run
station.
   The government issued a communique late Tuesday promising to
investigate the church attacks and saying it ``sympathizes with the
families of the victims, the Salesian fathers and the Catholic
Church.
   ``The military government regrets the incidents which occurred
on the 11th and 12th of September ... in which the churches of St.
Jean Bosco and Immaculate Conception were burned,'' read the
communique broadcast by radio stations.
   ``The police (are) pursuing the culprits, among whom are the
self-proclaimed perpetrators who appeared on television,'' it said.
   The government issued similar statements following previous mass
killings and political assassinations, but did not follow through
with investigations.
   Namphy returned to power in a June 19 coup that ousted the
4-month-old civilian government of President Leslie Manigat. Namphy
ruled for two years before that as head of a junta after former
President Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to exile in France on Feb. 7,
1986.
   Aristide, during his sermons, has denounced army atrocities.
Port-au-Prince Mayor Franck Romain said on Radio Metropole on
Monday that Aristide was ``justly punished'' by the massacre. The
priest was shielded by parishoners during the attack Sunday and
escaped.
   ``Those who massacred the worshippers at St. Jean Bosco Church
have been identified as the henchmen of the mayor,'' Honorat said.
   Several witnesses said they recognized city hall employees among
the assailants. Romain denied it.
   When reporters from Radio Metropole and Radio Haiti Inter
visited the charred remains of the Immaculate Conception Chapel
Tuesday, unidentified men at the scene threatened the reporter from
Haiti-Inter, which refused to broadcast the statement by the six
self-confessed killers Monday.
   The Radio Metropole reporter recognized one of the men as a
member of the group of six who boasted about Sunday's massacre.
They made their statement on private Radio Metropole and Tele-Haiti
and government-run Television Nationale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
