<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Crash, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0842,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two F-16 Jets Crash in Separate Accidents</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE to eight injured on ground in
South Carolina, CORRECTS that plane hit trees not house, pilot
released from hospital and identity of critically injured man.
Picks up 8th graf pvs, `It was...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Air Force F-16 jets crashed in separate accidents Tuesday,
injuring eight people on the ground in South Carolina, while the
pilot of the second craft ejected to safety near a base in Utah,
officials said.
   Shaw Air Force Base spokesman Dave McMahon said a jet crashed
into a stand of trees in Sumter, S.C., and exploded, injuring eight
people on the ground. The pilot, Capt. Ronald J. Garan Jr., 27, of
Yonkers, N.Y., ejected from the plane and was treated at the base
hospital.
   The plane crashed about 3:50 p.m., about one mile south of the
military facility after taking off on a training mission.
   ``The explosion felt like my house was breaking in two,'' said
Marilyn Holley, who ran outside her trailer home when she heard the
crash about 75 yards away. ``It was a fireball and the house behind
it was on fire and people were yelling and screaming and it was
horrible.''
   Officials at first thought the plane hit a house, but later
decided the house caught fire after the plane crashed.
   ``The house didn't appear to be hit,'' Sumter County Fire Chief
Larry Causey said. ``It appeared the plane hit, skipped and went by
the house. Evidently it caught it on fire.''
   William Smith, 59, suffered second- and third-degree burns over
50 percent of his body and was taken to Tuomey Hospital in Sumter
where he was in critical condition, according to McMahon and Susan
Worley, director of business development at the hospital.
   McMahon said Smith was being transferred to Humana Hospital in
Augusta, Ga., Tuesday night.
   Five of the people injured were treated and released, McMahon
said. One person was admitted to the base hospital in stable
condition, another was in good condition at Tuomey Hospital.
   It was not immediately known whether those injured were inside
the house the plane struck.
   In Utah, pilot Capt. Hal K. Bird, 28, of Dallas, ejected safely
when the jet went down 25 miles west of the Hill Air Force Base
near the Great Salt Lake, said spokeswoman Sylvia Le Mons-Liddle.
   The fighter was returning to the base from a routine training
mission.
   Both accidents were being investigated.
   The South Carolina crash was the third involving an Air Force
jet from the base in the past several weeks. Sumter is 40 miles
east of Columbia.
   And in Utah, 27 F-16 crashes with seven fatalities have occured
at the base since the aircraft began to be flown there in January
1979, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
