<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Pillsbury     09-13 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pillsbury,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Pillsbury Chief Expects Flat First Quarter Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. expects its first quarter
operating income to be flat, due to continued sluggish sales by its
Burger King fast-food restaurant chain, the company's chairman said
Tuesday.
   Philip L. Smith, in his first major public appearance as the
food and restaurant company's new chairman, told Pillsbury's annual
meeting that comparable Burger King restaurant sales were off 2
percent in the first quarter of fiscal 1989 from the same period
last year.
   The decline extended a trend that contributed to a major
restructuring in the previous year, which sharply reduced
Pillsbury's net earnings. Pillsbury had net earnings in fiscal 1988
of $69.3 million, or 81 cents a share, compared with $181.9
million, or $2.10 a share in fiscal 1987.
   Smith said that for the first quarter of fiscal 1989 operating
results should be ``virtually flat'' although net income will be up
about 25 percent because of a one-time benefit in deferred taxes.
   ``Foods will have an excellent first quarter, but restaurants,
as I indicated, will be down because of the investment expenses we
are incurring and because of continued sluggish sales at Burger
King,'' Smith said.
   Besides spending $30 million this year to upgrade training and
add new managerial staff at Burger King, Pillsbury will begin a
$150 million capital improvement plan to add 60 new company stores
and upgrade existing stores, Smith said.
   ``The long-term profit performance for the whole company makes
it essential that we succeed, and there is no reason why we
cannot,'' Smith said. ``I will be present in Miami at our Burger
King headquarters frequently to provide encouragement and to assist
in making the right judgments with a clear sense of urgency.''
   Smith said he expects profit growth in the foods division during
the coming fiscal years and an overall ``solid financial gain''
despite the expenses incurred to improve restaurant sales.
   He said the company's S&A Restaurant Corp., which operates the
full-service chains of Steak and Ale and Bennigan's, experienced
its first upturn in average restaurant sales in four years during
the first quarter of this year.
   In last year's restructuring, the subsidiary dropped two small
chains, got out of the hotel food service business and closed 23
underperforming Steak and Ale restaurants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
