<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     09-13 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights,0519</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Macmillan Inc. has agreed to a $2.36 billion
takeover by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., a private investment
firm enlisted by the publishing-and-information giant to help it
elude other unwanted bidders.
   The $85-a-share acquisition in cash and securities announced
Monday would, if successful, conclude Macmillan's struggle to
thwart unwelcome takeovers by British publisher Robert Maxwell and
Texas investor Robert Bass.
   Some analysts speculated that either Macmillan's publishing or
information division would be sold by Kohlberg to help finance the
acquisition.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armtek Corp. has accepted a sweetened
$561.2 million buyout offer from its once-hostile suitor Mark IV
Industries Inc., ending a brief battle for the auto parts maker.
   The agreement Monday calls for Mark IV to pay $46 a share, $2 a
share higher than its previous offer, to acquire Armtek.
   Armtek, the former Armstrong Rubber Co., makes plastics and
specialty chemicals for cars and other products. It sold its
Armstrong Tire Co. division to Italy's Pirelli Group earlier this
year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co., which holds just less
than a fourth of the fast-growing minivan market with its Aerostar,
has announced plans to join Nissan Motor Corp. to make a minivan in
northeastern Ohio.
   The project is to deliver the new vehicles to showroom floors in
three years. Ford will invest $1 billion and Nissan less, the
companies said Monday.
   The expansion of Ford's Avon Lake plant will add 1,300 jobs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hugh Hefner, the jet-setting founder of Playboy
magazine, says he is giving his daughter, Christie Hefner, full
command of the business empire he built from a $600 investment into
a symbol of sexual liberation.
   Hefner, 62, announced Monday he won't run for re-election as
chairman and chief executive officer of Playboy Enterprises Inc. at
the board of directors' meeting in November.
   The company also revealed it would receive ``a substantial
seven-figure advance'' from Bantam Books Inc., which is publishing
Hefner's autobiography.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   US Sprint Communication Co.'s pre-tax
operating losses in the third quarter should be sharply reduced to
no more than $35 million, according to William Esrey, United
Telecommunications Inc. president and chief executive officer.
   US Sprint lost $165 million in the same period of last year and
$112 million in the second quarter of this year.
   Esrey, who released the statement Monday, is the chief executive
of US Sprint, which is owned jointly by his company and GTE Corp.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rivals of International Business Machines Corp.
are bringing out a new ``bus'' for the flow of communications
inside personal computers that differs from IBM's own.
   The new standard rivals the Micro Channel used inside IBM's
Personal System-2 line and could hamper sales of the PS-2, analysts
say.
   Details of the new standard were scheduled to be announced today
by the PC makers, led by Compaq Computer Corp. of Houston.
</TEXT>
