<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     09-13 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights,0516</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought and hot weather nibbled at the
nation's corn and soybean crops last month, but new Agriculture
Department estimates show most of the damage was done in June and
July.
   Officials held Monday to an earlier prediction that consumer
food prices would rise an average of only 3 percent to 5 percent
this year, with about 1 percent of the rise caused by drought. A
further increase is expected in 1989.
   The new projections for the size of crops, based on Sept. 1
surveys, were down by less than 1 percent from the forecast a month
ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 500 federal savings institution
regulators have been exempted illegally from government salary
limits, according to a congressional report.
   The General Accounting Office, in a report Monday, said
employees of three subsidiaries of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board
are, in fact, federal employees and should be subject to civil
service pay classifications. The top civil service salary is
$75,500 a year.
   Salaries have ranged as high as $150,000.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have decided the staff
overseeing the Pilgrim nuclear power plant is ready to handle a
restart under intense monitoring, an inspector says.
   The Boston Edison Co. plant has been shut down under government
order since 1986.
   Nuclear Regulatory Commission inspectors recently found no
``fundamental flaws'' that would inhibit reactor or public safety
during plant operation, it was reported Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc. announced price
increases ranging up to 29 percent for some of its personal
computers, external drives, monitors, printers and expansion kits.
   One reason for the increases is that computer memory chips have
gone up in price. Because of strong sales, Apple has been forced to
buy some chips at premium prices on the spot market, the company
said Monday.
   The Macintosh II rose 29 percent to $4,869 from $3,769. The
price of the Macintosh Plus remains unchanged at $1,799.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winnebagos, those behemoths of America's wide-open
spaces, have launched in the home of the compact car with the
blessings of the Japanese government.
   The venture announced Monday between Mitsubishi Corp. and
Winnebago Industries Inc. of Forest City, Iowa, had the glitz of
professional marketing.
   The Japanese government is seeking to cut Japan's $60 billion
annual trade surplus with the United States by encouraging more
imports of American goods into Japan.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market showed little movement in a listless session
Monday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 3.56
points to 2,072.37 while the broad market fell.
   Oil futures prices fell below $14 a barrel Monday, but surged
back to finish the day higher after Saudi Arabia's King Fahd called
for production discipline among OPEC nations.
   Bond prices fell in thin trading in reaction to the jump in oil
prices. The dollar weakened marginally. Grain and soybean futures
were mixed.
