<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Playboy-Hefner     09-13 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Playboy-Hefner,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hugh Hefner Isn't Running for Re-Election to Playboy Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hugh Hefner, whose name is synonymous with
Playboy magazine, has decided to step down as chairman and chief
executive officer of the business empire he launched with a $600
investment.
   Hefner, 62, issued a statement Monday that he would not run for
re-election to the board of directors of Playboy Enterprises Inc.,
the magazine's parent company. The directors election is scheduled
following Playboy's shareholders' meeting Nov. 10.
   Hefner's daughter Christie, who has run the day-to-day
operations of the company since 1982, is expected to be elected to
the posts now held by her father, the statement said.
   The company also revealed it would receive a seven-figure
advance from Bantam Books, Inc., which is publishing Hefner's
autobiography.
   Hefner, who mortgaged his furniture and invested $600 of his own
to publish the first issue of Playboy in December 1953, called the
change ``just another evolutionary step consistent with my own
personal plans.''
   Christie Hefner said in a statement that she hopes to expand
Playboy's licensing, television and video businesses.
   ``The geographic reach of the company also will continue to be
expanded,'' she said, ``with new markets such as India and Eastern
Bloc countries opening up for Playboy-licensed products, and
foreign distribution of home video and television programs
growing.''
   Ms. Hefner, 35, who over the past six years returned the company
to profitability by selling off its sour businesses, now is
president, chief operating officer and vice chairwoman of Playboy
Enterprises.
   After she becomes Playboy's top board executive, the company's
founder will remain the major stockholder, with the titles of
chairman emeritus and editor-in-chief of Playboy magazine, the
company's statement said.
   ``Christie has had my full support since she took responsibility
for the day-to-day operations of the company in April of 1982,''
Hefner said in a statement.
   Under Ms. Hefner's business direction, Playboy Enterprises
closed the last of its U.S. key clubs and shed its interests in
movie theaters, modeling and book and record clubs. Playboy
Enterprises made a $2.6 million profit in 1988.
   Dan Lee, an analyst with Drexel Burnahm Lambert Inc. in New
York, speculated Hefner may have stepped down to spend less time on
business and more on his fiancee, Kimberley Conrad, 26, Playboy's
Playmate of the Month for January.
   ``In a business sense, Christie Hefner has largely been running
the company for the past several years. But he owns about 80
percent of Playboy's stock, so there won't be any dramatic
changes,'' Lee said.
   ``I think in terms of the company overall _ it is a changing of
the guard, a sort of passing the reins along,'' said Playboy
spokeswoman Robyn Radomski.
   ``In terms of where the company is now, it's a logical step.
...But Hef is still going to be editor-in-chief of the magazine and
be involved in major strategic decisions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
