<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0737EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Banks-Securities Bjt   09-13 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banks-Securities, Bjt,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Members Scrutinize Plan To Give Banks New Securities Power</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subcommittee hearing begins 10 a.m. EDT; tops uncertain. A
version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress wary of granting banks new
securities powers are marshaling evidence to back their position by
looking at U.S. banks' overseas operations.
   Rep. John D. Dingell, D-Mich., called a meeting of his Energy
and Commerce oversight subcommittee today to review a General
Accounting Office report suggesting banks may have problems
handling new powers.
   Although banks are barred from most securities activities in the
United States, Federal Reserve rules permit bank subsidiaries to
trade and underwrite securities abroad.
   The GAO, at the request of Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass.,
looked at how large U.S. banks with European operations fared in
the London markets in 1986 and 1987.
   ``Bank examination reports ... indicate that most of the London
securities subsidiaries of U.S. banks recorded losses or were
marginally profitable,'' the report said, noting that the problems
were made worse by the world stock market crash in October 1987.
   The GAO attributed U.S. banks' poor showing in London in part to
``significant management and internal control problems.'' However,
it also took note of the turbulence of the London market, which
recently had been deregulated by the British government.
   Eighteen of the 50 U.S. banks operating in London engaged in at
least some securities underwriting and dealing, the watchdog agency
said.
   In several instances during the period of the crash, London
securities subsidiaries were forced to call on their parent U.S.
banks for infusions of capital to make up for losses, it said.
   ``This study foreshadows the threat to our banking system if
banks are allowed unfettered entry into our domestic securities
markets,'' said Markey, chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
finance subcommittee.
   Dingell and Markey are using the study in their efforts to
counter bills that would repeal or substantially alter the 1933
Glass-Steagall Act, which separated commercial and investment
banking in the wake of the 1929 stock market crash and subsequent
wave of bank failures.
   Bills granting banks new securities powers have passed the full
Senate and the House Banking Committee. The legislation must be
reviewed by Dingell's committee before the full House can act.
   Both Dingell and Markey have expressed skepticism about relaxing
the Glass-Steagall barriers. In a television interview over the
weekend, Dingell said ``if I have any say'' such legislation will
not be enacted this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 0809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Taiwan-Tariffs     09-13 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Taiwan-Tariffs,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Taiwan Planning To Cut More Tariffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan plans to cut import tariffs on
several additional products, including mineral oils and cooling
equipment, to help reduce trade friction with the United States, a
newspaper reported Tuesday.
   The widely circulated China Times quoted unidentified financial
officials as saying Taiwan would lower tariffs on the 56
``competitive U.S. products to effectively ease trade tension''
between Taiwan and its chief trading partner.
   For each of the 56 items, U.S.-made products currently make up
more than 20 percent of Taiwan's imports of that item, the
newspaper said.
   Wang Fu-jen, a Customs Administration official, declined to
comment on the newspaper report.
   Last month, Taiwan announced it would cut import tariffs on 335
other items later this month.
   The newspaper said tariffs would be cut for 52 of the 175 items
for which U.S. negotiators requested reductions during trade talks
in April.
   However, tariffs will be cut for only two of the 102
agricultural items requested by the U.S. side because Taiwanese
officials believe local farmers need protection, the newspaper said.
   The new items include broth, mineral oils, compressors and
cooling equipment, it said.
   In February, tariffs on 3,500 items were cut by an average of 50
percent in Taiwan's most sweeping tariff cuts.
   Taiwan has been under U.S. pressure to reduce its large
bilateral trade surplus. Trade between Taiwan and the United States
last year totaled $31.2 billion, with Taiwan's exports exceeding
imports by $16 billion.
   During the first eight months of this year, Taiwan's imports
from the United States totaled $9.3 billion, up 102 percent from a
year earlier. Its bilateral trade surplus totaled $6.4 billion
during the period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
