<1ST_LINE>r f BC-HongKong-Economy     09-13 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hong Kong-Economy,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation, Labor Shortage Troubling Financial Secretary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation and labor shortages are two major
economic problems facing Hong Kong, Financial Secretary Piers
Jacobs said Tuesday.
   Jacobs, in an evaluation of the economy's performance, also
slightly revised his projection of this year's growth rate to 6
percent from 5 percent, still well below the 13.5 percent rate for
1987.
   Interest rate increases in the United States and Europe and the
slower economic growth worldwide are contributing factors in the
decline in growth of the British colony's export-fueled economy, he
said.
   Jacobs noted, however, that the local economy ``is still
operating close to capacity, so that inflation and labor shortages
continue to be our two major concerns.''
   He said the inflation rate was expected to hit 7.5 percent this
year, slightly higher than previously projected. The unemployment
rate, 1.8 percent in June, has reached historic lows, resulting in
rapid increases of wages and salaries, Jacobs added.
   The government is considering easing a ban on the import of
foreign labor because of the widespread labor shortages, but Jacobs
did not say whether he favored such a move.
</TEXT>
