<2ND_LINE>PM-Monsanto-Copper-7,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Monsanto Suffers Another Setback In Copperr-7 Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ruled that Monsanto
Co. also could be held liable for damages from the Copper-7
intrauterine device that is produced by its subsidiary G.D. Searle
& Co.
   The ruling Monday by U.S. District Judge Robert Renner
represents a second legal setback for Monsanto involving the
Copper-7 device, which was taken off the market in 1986, a year
after Monsanto acquired Searle.
   Last week Searle was ordered by a jury to pay $8.75 million in
punitive and compensatory damages to Esther Kociemba, an Elk River,
Minn., woman who said the IUD caused her to become sterile.
   In the latest case, Renner ruled that Julie Daher, of Columbia
Heights, Minn., could sue both Searle and Monsanto for damages from
a Copper-7 she used between October 1984 and October 1987.
   Monsanto, based in St. Louis, Mo., had been named as
co-defendant in about two dozen Copper-7 cases, but all of those
cases had been dismissed in court or dropped by the plaintiffs
until Monday's decision.
   Monsanto stock plunged after the ruling Monday, falling $7.12{
to $78.62{ in active trading on the New York Stock Exchange. In
early trading today it was off another $1.50 to $77.12{.
   Daher's attorneys claim Monsanto acted in concert with Searle in
misrepresenting the safety of the Copper-7 and fraudulently
concealing dangers associated with the device after it acquired
Searle in October 1985 for $2.8 billion.
   Legal experts have said Friday's jury verdict could result in
thousands of lawsuits against Searle.
   Monsanto maintains ``there simply is no justification for the
jury's action.''
</TEXT>
