<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-BugVac Adv17-18   09-13 0744</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-BugVac, Adv 17-18,0769</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 17-18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Zapping Those Bad Bugs With Vacuum Cleaner</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A contraption that sucks bad bugs off
strawberry plants may become a handy tool for farmers in the drive
to kill pests without using so many chemicals.
   Three farming members of Driscoll Strawberry Associates Inc. of
Watsonville, in northern California, are using a company-designed
machine called a BugVac this year to vacuum lygus bugs off their
plants.
   The custom-made vacuum machine, mounted on a tractor, moves down
rows of young berries, providing just enough suction to zap lygus
bugs that like to live near the top of the plants.
   Beneficial insects that live lower on the plants are not
disturbed by the machine, explained Driscoll researcher Ed Show.
Green leaves and the ripening fruit also are left unharmed.
   Show adapted the idea from a hand vacuum the University of
California developed years ago to test the levels of insect
populations. The researcher's innovation consists of hydraulically
driven fans and suction hoses.
   ``The vacuum doesn't deep clean the whole strawberry plant,''
Show said in an interview. ``We're affecting only the bugs on the
top part of the plant. It will suck up and remove bugs of all
kinds, the good and the bad, but it's not as detrimental to the
beneficial insect community.''
   Perhaps the main benefit from the BugVac is saving the
beneficial insects needed to eat other damaging bugs such as
western spider mites, which have become resistant to pesticides.
   ``We have no effective miticides to control spider mites, so if
we spray for lygus bugs, we create a real spider mite problem
because we knock out the beneficial insects,'' Show says.
   Vacuum cleaning the plants does not eliminate as many lygus bugs
as spraying them with pesticides would. However, growers who tried
the new technique were able to keep the lygus bug population close
to or slightly below what is termed the economic threshold in
integrated pest management _ the level at which the pest population
causes financial losses.
   ``We're learning how many lygus bugs we can get away with in a
field,'' Show said.
   The board of Driscoll Associates, which provides its own
patented strawberry varieties to affiliated growers, asked Show to
find ways to reduce or eliminate as much use of pesticides as
possible because of increasing regulatory restrictions, increasing
resistance by bugs to some chemicals and doubts about whether
adequate new chemicals will become available.
   Show decided to adapt the DVac machine, a hand-held or backpack
device used to suck up small numbers of pests in estimating how
badly a field is infested.
   ``Given that basic idea, we built a prototype on bicycle wheels,
pushed it through test plots and found it could catch what seemed
like an impressive number of lygus bugs,'' Show said.
   This was the first season growers used Show's device
commercially, and the three who had machines built seem satisfied
with the results.
   Reiter Affiliated of Watsonville used a BugVac on 71 acres of
strawberries at Salinas, about 125 miles south of San Francisco,
and plans to have two more machines built for use on all of the
company's 225 acres next year.
   General manager Tom Jones estimates the vacuum machine saved
$100-$200 an acre over the cost of pesticides, and owner Miles
Reiter said the savings may even be higher.
   ``It's been a real good deal for us,'' Jones said.
   Mike McCluney of Watsonville, who manufactures the BugVacs, says
he's now built nine or 10 and has orders for at least that many
more with still other farmers considering the device. The cost of
the machines runs between $12,000 and $17,000.
   ``It definitely does work under most circumstances when properly
used with integrated pest management and other methods,'' McCluney
said. ``It's not just a replacement for a spray tractor but needs
to be in conjunction with predator releases.''
   Use of the BugVac may spread from strawberries to other
California vegetables, such as lettuce.
   ``There's interest on the part of some other vegetable
growers,'' said Show, adding that he has heard of at least one
Maine farmer who uses a similar apparatus to control potato beetles.
   McCluney said he plans a trip to Brawley in southeastern
California ``to see if we can use this new idea to help out with
their white fly problem.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Sept. 17-18</NOTE>
