<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Open Lower; Wheat Rallies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures opened lower today on
the Chicago Board of Trade while wheat traded higher, all in
reaction to Monday's crop production report from Agriculture
Department.
   The government's new harvest projections of 4.46 billion bushels
of corn and 1.47 billion bushels of soybeans were higher than the
market had expected, prompting many players to sell contracts for
future delivery of those commodities, analysts said.
   The USDA's wheat production number _ 1.81 billion bushels _ also
was higher than expected. But its bearish implications were more
than offset by new government predictions of lower grain production
in the Soviet Union and Canada, and a forecast for increased grain
imports by the Soviets. The United States is negotiating a new
long-term agreement to supply grain to the Soviets.
   Demand concerns have replaced supply fears as the main influence
on crop futures prices and will continue to dominate trading as the
corn and soybean harvest progresses, said Ted Mao, grain specialist
with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   ``The key is how is the demand going to respond, when are the
spurts of business going to come, how is the market going to handle
the fact that over the next 60 days we are going to be harvesting
and maximizing the supply side in the U.S.,'' he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 3\ cents to 6 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.08 a bushel; corn was 1
cent lower to 1} cents higher with September at $2.85 a bushel;
oats were { cent to 2{ cents higher with December at $2.75 a
bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents to 8 cents lower with September at
$8.66 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .22 cent to .48 cent higher with October at
70.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent lower to .05 cent
higher with September at 79.15 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to
.68 cent higher with October at 38.40 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .08 cent to 1.23 cents higher with February at 47.50
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Monday.
</TEXT>
