<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Up 11.7 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices moved higher Tuesday as the market
was buoyed by developments in the oil sector.
   Confidence was given a much needed boost by British Gas PLC,
which staged a ``dawn raid,'' scooping up shares in London and
Scottish Marine Oil Co., known as Lasmo.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed up
11.7 points, or 0.7 percent, at 1,756.3.
   Trading volume was 369.2 million shares, compared with 213.2
million shares traded during Monday's session.
   Although British Gas failed to achieve its target of aquiring a
14.9-percent stake in Lasmo, the hectic buying and the general
speculation surrounding the raid helped the whole oil sector and
share prices generally.
   ``You can see what happens to this market when there's a little
bit of good news,'' said Roger Charlesworth, senior dealer at Chase
Manhattan Securities Ltd. in London.
   The market has lately been plagued by confusion over the
near-term direction for equities and by particularly low levels of
participation.
   The raid on Lasmo started before the official market opening,
with the brokerage Hoare Govett Ltd. offering to purchase Lasmo
shares on behalf of British Gas at 480 pence, or $8.16, apiece,
well above Monday's closing Lasmo price of 390 pence.
   Hoare Govett said it obtained a small amount of Lasmo's stock.
   The raid sparked speculation of a forthcoming takeover bid for
Lasmo.
   Takeover speculation also surrounded Enterprise Oil PLC, another
independent British oil company, because of Lasmo's 25 percent
holding in Enterprise.
   A successful bidder for Lasmo could use the Enterprise holding
as a platform for a bid for Enterprise as well, analysts said.
   Lasmo shares surged to close at 543 pence, a jump of 153 pence.
Enterprise closed 126 pence higher at 562 pence.
</TEXT>
