<HEAD>Dollar And Gold Both Firmer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar firmed against all major
currencies except the Canadian dollar in European trading Tuesday.
Gold prices also rose.
   Foreign exchange dealers said trading was dull with markets
waiting for Wednesday's U.S. trade figures.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6965 late Tuesday, more
expensive for buyers than Monday's late $1.6958.
   Other late rates in Europe, compared with late rates Monday,
included: 1.8470 West German marks, up from 1.8453; 1.5600 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5535; 6.2935 French francs, up from 6.2775;
2.0845 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0817; 1,380.50 Italian lire, up
1,378.50; 1.2307 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2395.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 133.07 Japanese yen, down from
133.42 yen at Monday's close. In later London trading the dollar
traded at 133.30 yen.
   Gold bullion prices moved higher in a recovery from low levels
Monday, when the price fell below $420 for the first time this
year, undermined by weaker prices for oil and other commodities.
   Gold closed in London at a late bid of $420 a troy ounce, up
from $419.25, and in Zurich at $421 bid, up from $418.
   Gold closed in Hong Kong at $422.69 bid, up from $419.18.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a late bid of $6.46 a
troy ounce, up from $6.41.
