<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     09-13 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0445</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was lower in early trading
today, lacking momentum as traders waited for Wednesday's report on
the nation's merchandise trade deficit for July.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 3.56 points at
2,068.81 at 2 p.m. EDT, having bounced back from an early fall of
10.31 points and then stayed in a narrow range.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by around 7-to-5, with 749
issues down, 559 up and 536 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 119.05 million shares. Activity
was said to be dampened, though less so than on Monday, by the
observance of the Jewish New Year holiday.
   ``Rip Van Winkle would love this one,'' said Bill Raftery, an
analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. ``It's like watching
paint dry on the walls.''
   Analysts said the overall market was dragged down early in the
session by negative news affecting shares of semiconductor
companies, including National Semiconductor Corp.'s reported loss
Monday of $30.5 million in its first fiscal quarter.
   Shares of National Semiconductor, one of the most actively
traded companies, were down } at 8].
   ``That sent the whole group into a tailspin,'' said Hildegarde
Zagorski, an analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
