<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Oshman-Supercomputers     09-13 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Oshman-Supercomputers,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Rolm Head Announcing New Computer Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ken Oshman and other former executives
of Rolm Corp. now at Ultra Network Technologies are introducing a
product Oshman says will revolutionize the world of high-speed
computer networks.
   ``It is, in a real sense, uncharted waters,'' Oshman, Ultra's
chairman, said Monday of the new network being unveiled next
Tuesday.
   Ultra's system, which already has won endorsements from several
makers of a new generation of so-called mini-supercomputers, is
essentially a local area network that passes information among
computers at a theoretical maximum rate of 1 billion bits per
second.
   Ultra can transfer the contents of an encyclopedia in a few
seconds, 100 times faster than one widely used network for office
computers.
   Supercomputers need faster local area networks because computer
speed has outpaced the ability of the machines to transfer
information.
   ``Ultra has basically found a very fast way of allowing
high-performance computers to talk to each other,'' said Richard
Shaffer, editor of Technologic Computer Letter in New York. ``It is
hot stuff.''
   Several makers of high-speed computers have agreed to market the
network and connect their machines to the system.
   Rolm, his former company, was sold to IBM in 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880913-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-88 1525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Drought-Barges     09-13 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Drought-Barges,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Execs: Drought Hurt River Barge Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Executives of river barge companies say this
summer's drought stalled their efforts to recover from some lean
years.
   After a severe recession in the early 1980s, when some barge
lines merged and others went broke, the companies saw 1988 as the
year to cap a comeback. But they have been unpleasantly surprised
by mounting losses.
   ``Finally this year, people began to make money until Mother
Nature gave us a lousy deal,'' Jeffrey Smith, vice president of the
trade group American Waterways Operators, said Monday.
   A study commissioned by the trade group projected the industry
this year will suffer losses of as much as $200 million on revenue
of $1 billion, Smith said. Operating costs of barge companies have
soared while many of the rates are fixed by long-term contracts,
officials said.
   The barge industry struggled as a whole from 1982 to 1986, when
an oversupply of barges depressed hauling rates. Congress had
proposed several bills that would help the industry by tax
deferrals or direct subsidies, but in August the industry announced
it wanted no help, Smith said.
   Commercial traffic on the dam-regulated Ohio River has continued
without a hitch despite the summer drought, but shallow water in
the lower Mississippi River has tied up barges and $7,000-a-day
towboats. Travel time for barges has doubled this summer.
   In addition, special drought restrictions reduced by half the
number of barges that are allowed to be lashed together, requiring
barge companies to use more tow boats. The restrictions also limit
the load each barge can carry.
   ``A turnaround year turned into a real dumper,'' said Morris
Larson, executive vice president of the Merchants Exchange of St.
Louis, where the price of barge transportation for grain is
determined in trade.
   Slower travel and the smaller loads caused a shortage of barges
and boats this summer, said Richard A. Hain, executive vice
president of M-G Transport Services Inc., a Cincinnati barge
company.
   ``It was difficult to quote prices because there weren't any
barges available,'' he said.
   He said there was a substantial decline in company profits this
summer.
   At Midland Enterprises Inc., another Cincinnati-based line,
profits will be down although the company will still make money,
said Steve Frasher, vice president of operations.
   ``This (drought) was not needed at this time,'' Frasher said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
