<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close 1stLd-Writethru 09-13 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close, 1st Ld-Writethru,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Higher On Wheat Market's Strength</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to make most recent version a 1st
Ld-Writethru; CORRECTS direction of oat trading in final graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop futures prices closed mostly higher Tuesday
on the Chicago Board of Trade as strength from the buoyant wheat
market spilled over into the corn and soybean pits.
   Corn and soybean futures had opened lower in reaction to the
Agriculture Department's higher-than-expected harvest estimates,
issued after the close of trading on Monday.
   The report estimated 1988 U.S. corn production at 4.46 billion
bushels and soybean production at 1.47 billion bushels. The numbers
represent sharp declines from last year's production levels because
of drought damage, but were still above most private forecasts.
   The USDA's wheat-production estimate also was higher than
expected but wheat futures prices rallied on the report's
predictions of declining Soviet and Canadian wheat production and
increasing Soviet grain imports.
   Tuesday's market performance ``is a reflection of the fact that
while everyone was focused on the disappointing numbers put out by
USDA domestically, the world numbers for wheat came out friendly,''
said Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
New York.
   With potential crop-weather problems developing in South America
and severe crop losses a hard fact in the United States and Canada,
``the world situation is still tight'' for wheat, Mao said.
   At the close, wheat was 3 cents to 9} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.11 a bushel; corn was 1
cent lower to 2} cents higher with September at $2.85 a bushel;
oats were 2 cents to 3{ cents higher with September at $2.64 a
bushel; soybeans were 5{ cents to 8{ cents higher with September at
$8.76 a bushel.
</TEXT>
