<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0366</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished higher in mostly
sluggish trading today, getting a last-minute boost from remarks by
Treasury secretary designate Nicholas F. Brady.
   The statements touched off a late buying wave, after stocks
traded slightly lower through most of the session.
   Brady, an investment banker nominated by President Reagan to
replace former Treasury chief James Baker, said at his Senate
confirmation hearing that he expects the nation's trade deficit to
decline at a ``surprisingly fast'' pace over the next few years.
   Analysts said the market interpreted Brady's comments as hinting
that Wednesday's scheduled government report on the merchandise
trade report for July would be encouraging.
   Activity on Wall Street had been stalled today as participants
awaited the July trade report, and Brady's remarks gave the
lackluster market a lift, analysts said. Volume also was dampened,
though less so than on Monday, by the observance of the Jewish New
Year holiday.
   ``Rip Van Winkle would love this one,'' said Bill Raftery, an
analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. ``It's like watching
paint dry on the walls.''
   Analysts said the overall market was dragged down early in the
session by negative news affecting shares of semiconductor
companies, including National Semiconductor Corp.'s loss reported
Monday of $30.5 million in its first fiscal quarter.
   ``That sent the whole group into a tailspin,'' said Hildegarde
Zagorski, an analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The announcement early today that the U.S. current-account
deficit shrank by 9.8 percent in the second quarter to $33.3
billion had little impact since it is a less recent reading of the
trade picture than Wednesday's report.
   The current account is the broadest measure of a country's
trade, while the July merchandise trade report will be a more
narrow and recent indicator.
   ``They're waiting for a signal, either from the outside world or
from the market itself,'' said Michael Metz, an analyst for
Oppenheimer & Co. ``The market lacks real conviction, real
direction.''
   Most observers expect the July report to show a merchandise
trade gap of around $11.5 billion to $12.5 billion.
</TEXT>
