<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished higher Tuesday in
mostly sluggish trading, getting a last-minute boost from remarks
by Treasury secretary designate Nicholas F. Brady.
   The statements touched off a late buying wave led by blue-chip
issues, after stocks had traded slightly lower through most of he
session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials ended 10.67 points
higher at 2,083.04. The closely watched blue-chip indicator fell
10.31 points soon after the opening, recovered a bit and then
stayed in a narrow range until shortly before the close.
   In the broader market, advancing issues narrowly outnumbered
declines in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed
stocks, with 705 issues up, 681 down and 545 unchanged.
   Brady, an investment banker nominated by President Reagan to
replace former Treasury chief James Baker, said at his Senate
confirmation hearing that he expects the nation's trade deficit to
decline at a ``surprisingly fast'' pace over the next few years.
   Analysts said Wall Street interpreted Brady's comments as
hinting that Wednesday's scheduled government report on the
merchandise trade report for July would be encouraging.
   ``I think the comment helped,'' said Ralph Acampora, an analyst
for Kidder, Peabody & Co.
   Brady, who later was approved by the Senate Finance Committee
for consideration by the full Senate, also said he sees no reason
at this time for raising taxes. Brady's nomination is widely
expected to be approved.
   Market activity had been stalled as participants awaited the
July trade report, and Brady's remarks gave the lackluster market a
lift, analysts said. Volume also was dampened, though less so than
on Monday, by the observance of the Jewish New Year holiday.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE totaled 162.49 million shares,
up from 114.88 million in Monday's session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
187.86 million shares.
   ``Rip Van Winkle would love this one,'' Bill Raftery, an analyst
at Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co., said early in the session.
``It's like watching paint dry on the walls.''
   Analysts said the overall market was dragged down in the early
going by negative news affecting shares of semiconductor companies,
including National Semiconductor Corp.'s loss of $30.5 million in
its first fiscal quarter.
   ``That sent the whole group into a tailspin,'' said Hildegarde
Zagorski, an analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Shares of National Semiconductor, one of the most actively
traded companies, fell | to 8{.
   The announcement early Tuesday that the U.S. current-account
deficit shrank by 9.8 percent in the second quarter to $33.3
billion had little impact since it is a less recent reading of the
trade picture than Wednesday's report.
   The NYSE index rose 0.52 to 151.15.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 1.20 to 306.95, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 0.96 at 267.43.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index edged up
0.12 to 296.79. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 382.38, up 0.31.
   Among other stocks actively traded on the NYSE, Detroit Edison
rose [ to 15{, TW Services jumped 1| to 20|, Kroger soared 11} to
51\, IBM advanced 1] to 115 and Exxon was unchanged at 44~.
   On the negative side, Monsanto fell 4 to 74| and General
Electric declined [ to 42].
