<2ND_LINE>AM-Kroger, 1st Ld-Writehru,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chain Ponders Restructuring After Hafts Get OK to Buy Stock</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf pvs, Kroger, one ... 29
states., to UPDATE with final stock price.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BENTLEY BOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kroger Co. said Tuesday it was considering a
$3.77 billion restructuring plan, but said the proposal was not
specifically designed to ward off a possible hostile takeover bid
by Herbert and Robert Haft.
   Kroger, one of the nation's largest grocery chains, said it was
asking its board of directors to approve a plan that would plunge
the company into debt but keep it publicly owned. Kroger has 1,300
supermarkets and other operations in 29 states.
   The announcement sent Kroger stock soaring $11.75 a share to
$51.25 in nationwide trading of issues listed on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   A Federal Trade Commission ruling on Friday allowed the Hafts to
acquire at least $15 million worth of Kroger stock. The Hafts, who
control Dart Group Corp. of Landover, Md., are corporate takeover
strategists and have unsuccessfully chased other supermarket chains
but made huge profits in the process.
   ``This restructuring is not specifically tailored to the Haft
situation,'' Kroger spokesman Paul Bernish said. ``We take it
seriously. But ever since the market became competitive in 1985 or
1986, we've been pretty vigilant about this. We want to keep Kroger
an independent and public company.''
   Kroger said the restructuring would involve substantial but
unspecified bank loans, paying shareholders $48 in cash and
securities per share and allowing them to keep their stock. Kroger
has about 78.57 million shares outstanding.
   Kroger said it will repay the loans using cash flow from
operations, reducing expenses and selling assets. In a 1986
restructuring, Kroger sold its chain of SupeRx retail drugstores,
and Kroger has worked since July to sell off its unprofitable chain
of Florida Choice supermarkets and liquor stores in Florida.
   ``This is a case of extending that process,'' Bernish said.
``Our review of assets will be heightened if this plan is
approved.''
   The FTC ruling was the first official sign of the Hafts'
interest in Kroger. Representatives of the Hafts declined to
comment.
   Supermarket industry analysts said the restructuring plan was a
positive step for Kroger.
   ``This has been an option for Kroger for a long time. It is not
necessarily a response to the Haft announcement, but the Haft
family move was a catalyst,'' said Elizabeth Shiels, analyst for
the investment firm Hilliard Lyons in Louisville, Ky.
   ``Kroger has been looking for ways to reward its stockholders,''
she said. ``This restructuring allows the company to stay public
... This is a prudent move for Kroger.''
   Kroger's stock has traded heavily over the past five months,
partly because of rumors the Hafts and other potential acquirers
were interested in the company.
   If the Hafts were to take over Kroger, ``It's almost certain
that they'll start dismantling the company and selling off its
assets,'' said Gary M. Giblen, vice president at Rotan-Mosle, a
Houston-based investment firm.
   But Giblen also said the Hafts may be serious about running a
grocery company.
   They demonstrated that earlier this spring when they bought a
small Washington, D.C., grocery chain. Instead of selling it off
for the cash, the Hafts are using the company to learn how to
manage a grocery firm, Giblen said.
   The Hafts have failed in their efforts to buy such companies as
Safeway Stores Inc., Supermarkets General Corp. and Stop & Shop
Cos. but have profited in selling stock back to those companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
