<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TimberStrike     09-13 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Timber Strike,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest's Largest Timber Company Workers Ratify Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Woodworkers have ratified a new four-year
contract with Weyerhaeuser Co., a union spokesman said Tuesday.
   About 6,000 union woodworkers in Oregon and Washington approved
the pact, said Chuck MacRae, vice president of the International
Woodworkers of America-U.S.
   Weyerhaeuser's contract with the IWA and the Western Council of
Industrial Workers is nearly identical to contracts negotiated with
Boise-Cascade Corp., Willamette Industries Inc., Simpson Timber Co.
and Champion International Corp., MacRae said.
   It provides for a $1,400 bonus in the first year of the
contract, plus wage increases totaling 11 percent over the next
three years, he said. It allows a week's vacation bonus in the
first year, plus two additional holidays and substantial pension
plan improvements, MacRae said.
   Weyerhaeuser operations were not affected during the summer-long
Northwest woodworkers' strike. Most of the struck companies have
settled, and only about 400 workers remain on strike at two small
mills in Oregon.
   On Monday, about 1,300 woodworkers ratified a four-year contract
with DAW Forest Products Co. and W-I Forest Products Inc.
   At one point, the strike idled 9,000 workers in five states.
</TEXT>
