<2ND_LINE>AM-American-Bass,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bass Group Seeking Partner in Savings & Loan Bailout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bass investment group is seeking a partner
to finance part of its planned acquisition of American Savings &
Loan Association, according to the federal official overseeing a $2
billion government bailout of the thrift.
   The Robert M. Bass Group of Fort Worth, Texas, is negotiating
with at least three companies as it seeks a partner, said M. Danny
Wall, chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board.
   Wall, whose comments outside a savings and loan group's meeting
here were reported Tuesday in the Wall Street Journal, did not
respond to a telephone request for comment.
   Wall did not reveal the identities of the potential partners
except to say they were financial services companies. They were not
federally insured banks or savings and loan institutions, he said.
   The Bass Group, which will gain control of American in exchange
for an injection of $550 million, can sell as much as 49 percent of
the recapitalized American to a partner approved by the bank board,
Wall said.
   The bank board, which will own 30 percent of American, has
pledged an estimated $2 billion in cash and promissory notes over
the next 10 years to rescue the insolvent institution.
   The bank board seized Stockton-based American last week as a
prelude to turning it over the Bass. American's 186 California
branches remain open, and federal insurance remains in force for
all deposits.
   Financial Corp. of America, the holding company for American,
filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the
federal bankruptcy code last week.
</TEXT>
