<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   09-13 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Narrows, Dow Jumps On Hopes For More Improvement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT deficit figure to $33.3 billion sted
$33.8 billion.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reported on Tuesday a sharp improvement in the
broadest measure of U.S. trade from April through June, while
stocks got a boost from predictions that the trade deficit would
continue to decline.
   The Commerce Department said the deficit in the current account
shrank to $33.3 billion in the second quarter, a 9.8 percent
improvement from a first quarter imbalance of $36.9 billion. It was
the biggest quarterly improvement since a 20.1 percent drop in the
final three months of last year.
   The current account covers not only trade in merchandise but
also trade in services, which primarily reflect the flow of
investment earnings between countries.
   On Wednesday, the government will report the merchandise trade
balance for July, a monthly figure watched closely by the financial
markets.
   The Dow Jones industrial average spurted ahead in late trading
Tuesday, encouraged by remarks from Treasury secretary designate
Nicholas F. Brady, who said at his Senate confirmation hearing that
he expects the trade deficit to decline at a surprisingly fast pace
over the next few years.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 blue-chip stocks ended 10.67 points
higher at 2,083.04 after a mostly lackluster session.
   Brady, an investment banker who investigated the causes of last
year's stock market crash, was nominated by President Reagan to
replace former Treasury chief James A. Baker III.
   In other markets, the dollar strengthened slightly, but activity
was slow in advance of the July trade figures. Bond prices gained
as the yield on the government's 30-year issue slipped below 9
percent.
   Oil prices advanced, driven by a rise in wholesale gasoline
prices, which soared on news that refineries and oil platforms were
threatened by a hurricane approaching the Gulf of Mexico. The
contract for October delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose 7 cents to settle at $14.56 a
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Wholesale
unleaded gasoline for October delivery closed up 1.19 cents at
43.81 cents a gallon.
   The government's trade report showed the second-quarter
improvement in the current account deficit occurred because the
deficit in merchandise trade fell to $29.9 billion, down from $35.2
billion in the first quarter, as exports rose to a record level and
imports posted the first quarterly decline in three years.
   The good news was tempered by the fact that America suffered its
first deficit in three decades in the category that includes
investment earnings. The report showed a $492 million imbalance in
services, meaning that foreigners earned more on their investments
during the quarter than Americans earned on overseas investments.
   Still, for the first six months of this year, the current
account deficit has been running at an annual rate of $140.5
billion, a substantial improvement from a record deficit of $154
billion in 1987.
   The improvement has come about because of a boom in U.S.
exports, reflecting declines in the value of the dollar since 1985
which have made American goods competitive once again on overseas
markets.
   Also on Tuesday, the congressional Joint Economic Committee
heard a panel of economists urge further action to cut federal
budget deficits as a way of slowing U.S. domestic demand and
further reducing the trade deficit.
   In other economic news, the government released a state-by-state
report on unemployment in which Vermont emerged as the best job
provider for its residents. Massachusetts slipped from first place
to 10th in the past year among states with the lowest unemployment
rates.
</TEXT>
