<HEAD>Grocery Chain Founder to Retire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L.S. Skaggs, who built American Stores Co.
from a regional drugstore chain into a 1,600-store, nationwide
supermarket and drug giant, will retire once a successor is found,
the company announced Tuesday.
   Skaggs recently reached the mandatory retirment age of 65, but
has been asked by the board of directors to remain on the job while
an executive search committee seeks a new chairman and chief
executive, the company announced.
   American this year bought Dublin-based Lucky Stores Inc. for
$2.6 billion, and is embroiled in a legal dispute with the
California Attorney General's Office, which opposes the purchase on
grounds it would lead to higher consumer prices.
   Skaggs assumed control of the Idaho and Utah drugstore company
in 1950, on the death of his father, who also was named L.S. Skaggs.
   American, which recently moved its corporate headquarters from
Salt Lake City to Orange County, owns Skaggs, Skaggs-Alpha Beta and
Buttery supermarkets in western states, Acme and Star supermarkets
on the Eastern Seaboard, Jewel Food Stores in Chicago and the
27-state Osco drugstore chain.
</TEXT>
