<HEAD>Wickes Adopts Temporary Shareholder Protection Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wickes Companies Inc. has adopted a
temporary shareholder protection plan that requires potential
buyers to keep any offers open through late October, a spokesman
said Tuesday.
   The plan is meant to ``assure shareholders get the best value
possible,'' said Wickes spokesman Steve Stern.
   A management group led by Wickes Chairman Sanford Sigoloff has
offered to buy the company for $12 a share in a $598 million
leveraged buyout.
   Wickes' stock closed at $13.62{, down unchanged from Monday's
close on the New York Stock Exchange.
   That plan included a 60-day wait before the group could begin
buying shares, in order to give other buyers a chance to emerge.
Sigoloff, who led Wickes out of bankruptcy proceedings 3{ years
ago, said earlier the management group would not begin buying
shares until Oct. 20.
   The protection plan requires potential buyers keep their offers
open through Oct. 20, Stern said, adding the plan was not intended
to impede any other offers for Wickes shares.
   The buyout offer has brought numerous inquiries from other
buyers, according to Michael Tennenbaum, senior managing director
at Bear Stearns & Co. Inc., which is advising Wickes management.
   A buyer of Wickes would have to assume $2.1 billion in debt.
   The company's main lines of business are industrial products,
including auto fabrics and aircraft and missile parts; home
improvement and furnishings, including Wickes Furniture and
Builders Emporium do-it-yourself stores in Southern California; and
a group that makes wallpaper and carpet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
